ct energy initiatives towards socio-economic development, such as the Technical Working Group (TWG) on Energy and Infrastructure, have not been able to look beyond the power sector. Only the MEF has incorporated the poverty agenda into its mandate, as it is also the lead organization for the NPRS. BOX 1: KEY CHALLENGES IN INSTITUTIONAL ARRANGEMENTS Major institutions Mandate Linkages between energy and poverty (existing and potential) MIME, DET, Focus on energy and Seek to reduce the cost of Department of industry (excluding electricity and extend Hydroelectricity, and petroleum), energy policy electricity services to rural Department of planning and technical areas Energy Development capacity building MEF Focus on energy and Formulates NPRS at the poverty; control EdC along policy level with MIME EAC Regulate the electricity Aims to improve sector affordability of power services through tariff setting and regulation EdC Focus on electricity As the biggest supplier of generation, transmission electricity, has considerable and distribution potential to expand electricity access in rural and remote areas CNPA Focus on import, trade Regulates oil import and and use of petroleum exploration of oil and gas products deposit REEs Provide energy services in Can stimulate rural rural areas industrial growth and income generation NGOs and Assist in the development Seek cost-effective international and diversification of the alternatives to commercial donors energy sector energy sources in order to boost energy access for the poor TABLE 1 MAJOR INSTITUTIONS IN CAMBODIA WITH LINKAGES BETWEEN ENERGY AND POVERTY 5 Energy and Poverty in Cambodia THE CHALLENGES Weak policy and regulatory framework The importance of energy services in Cambodia\u2019s broad-based poverty reduction policies has been downgraded, such as in the Cambodian MDGs. Following the same pattern, energy policies aimed at developing the power sector have failed to understand the proper place of poverty reduction within their strategies. As a result, poverty reduction and energy development programmes have largely followed mutually exclusive policy paths. Of late, the Government has committed to boost rural access to electricity through various policy initiatives (Table 2). The Rural Electrification Fund (REF) and the Cambodian Energy Sector Strategy (CESS) are welcome steps that promise delivery in the long run. However, they mainly focus on electricity and exclude fuelwood and biomass. Like REF and CESS, most policies have not adequately considered the energy needs and realities of poor communities that need basic energy for cooking and lighting. Strategy/Policy/ Implementing Goal Programme agency Energy Sector MIME, EdC, EAC Establish principles and framework Development Policy for an energy sector that would 1994 satisfy Cambodia\u2019s goals for development and growth, while meeting social and environmental needs Power Sector MIME Contains broad objectives Strategy 1999 (investment and so on) and a preliminary schedule for the implementation of electricity generation, transmission distribution and renewable energy projects.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "4a7fb684-d69e-4654-ae3f-0d61cec19de1": {"__data__": {"id_": "4a7fb684-d69e-4654-ae3f-0d61cec19de1", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-cambodia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in Cambodia", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-cambodia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United N