goals that put focus on poverty alleviation and pay attention to energy provision from fuelwood, kerosene and battery use Integrate poverty issues into energy policies being developed by MIME Support the existing wood energy working group to formulate wood energy policy With adequate donor support, MIME can lead an integrated policy to promote RETs Support MIME to finalize Renewable Energy Legal Framework Support research institutions to do applied research on RETs Support NTTI to enhance the Energy Park as a focal point for promotion of RETs Support MIME to develop Rural Energy Programmes focusing on energy for cooking and lighting; Streamline with programmes focusing on rural electrification by renewable energy Support institutions such as ITC, National Technical Training Institute (NTTI), etc who are doing research on RETs and work together with NGOs such as SME-Cambodia, DATe, GERES and CKN NTTI can enhance the existing Energy Park into a national RET knowledge centre, organizing trainings and courses on RETs The UNDP-sponsored \u201cPreparatory Activities for a Rural Energy Development Programme\u201d should be materialized into a full-scale programme 33 THE CHALLENGES MEETING THE CHALLENGES Many Rural Electricity Enterprises (REEs) stop providing electricity because of increasing fuel prices, few customers and low total demand Households in Cambodia pay among the highest electricity prices in the world (from US$0.18 per kWh in the city to US$1 per kWh in rural areas) Rural families pay a higher price for basic energy for cooking and lighting than families in urban areas A substantial part of fuelwood is consumed by SMEs, such as brick and tile factories, palm sugar producers and rice millers Access Issues Formulate an Action Plan on sustainable supply of basic energy needs and affordable basic energy to rural families Support sustainable and affordable energy supply by implementing energy plantations and efficient charcoal production battery charging and kerosene replacement Increase the vitality and efficiency of REEs; Reduce high losses in grid and promote efficient battery (dis)charging Educate REEs and battery charging stations how to increase their roundtrip efficiency by decreasing network loss and customizing generator size to match electricity demand Promote energy-saving technologies to poor rural and urban families and SMEs Training centres have to be established to teach local entrepreneurs how to produce and sell these technologies themselves Examples of energy-saving technologies are the improved cook stoves, biomass stoves, water filters and the solar lanterns Support REEs who want to use gasifiers, micro hydro, biofuels or other RETs to generate affordable renewable electricity Increase the knowledge on efficient battery charging and use as well as kerosene replacement by solar lanterns Motivate SMEs to use RETs 34 SCHEMATIC REPRESENTATION OF CHALLENGES AND MODALITIES TO MEET THE CHALLENGES (CONTINUED...) THE CHALLENGES MEETING THE CHALLENGES There is a problematic investment environment for energy business in Cambodia: Import tax on renewable energy equipment is extremely high (35%) and the Government of Cambodia does not have sufficient funds nor capacity to support investments Financing Concerns Inadequate local provision of loans for productive uses of energy Inadequate sources for energy project financing to increase basic energy access at a decentralized level Implement government regulations to support tax schemes for RETs Reduce import tax on renewable energy equipment from 35% to 10%, and then use the extra revenues from the increased", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "e956053d-9a42-41d1-8718-5cffceab820a": {"__data__": {"id_": "e956053d-9a42-41d1-8718-5cffceab820a", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/public