 Bangkok. Copyright \u00a9 2007 UNDP United Nations Development Programme Regional Energy Programme for Poverty Reduction (REP-PoR) UNDP Regional Centre in Bangkok UN Service Building Rajdamnern Nok Avenue Bangkok 10200 Thailand http://regionalcentrebangkok.undp.or.th http://regionalcentrebangkok.undp.or.th/practices/energy_env/rep-por ISBN-13: 978-92-1-126179-0 Assigned Sales #: E.06.III.B.7 v Energy and Poverty in China More than a billion people in the Asia-Pacific region do not have access to electricity and 1.7 billion are dependent on traditional biomass fuels for their cooking and heating needs. Access to affordable modern energy services can improve their productivity and enhance living standards. Even so, there are no specific targets for the energy sector in the Millennium Declaration, a historic document signed seven years ago by the world\u2019s leaders. Affordable and sustainable modern energy services are a necessity for countries to meet their Millennium Development Goals (MDGs). Efforts of countries in the Asia-Pacific region to meet these aims will be hindered unless adequate attention is given to the crucial role energy services play in the development process. This is particularly true for the economic, environmental and social well-being of the poor. With fluctuating energy prices, the poor in many of the countries in the Asia and Pacific region face a daunting future. For them, access to affordable and essential modern energy services that could improve their living conditions and ensure a means to earn a living, will fall outside their reach. Recognizing the urgency for countries to factor in access to modern energy services, particularly when shaping national poverty reduction initiatives, the United Nations Development Programme (UNDP) provided technical and financial support for national-level rapid energy assessments. The primary aim of this work, carried out through UNDP\u2019s Regional Energy Programme for Poverty Reduction (REP-PoR) and completed in 2006, was to identify gaps and priority needs in linking energy services provision with poverty reduction. The framework for rapid gap assessments linking energy and poverty was developed as a joint effort of the UNDP Regional Centre in Bangkok (RCB) and UNDP country offices in the region, with the support of experts from the region. The draft framework was discussed at two sub-regional meetings, one held in Bangkok, Thailand (August 2005) and the other in Apia, Samoa (September 2005). The meetings were helpful in customizing the framework to suit specific needs and circumstances of the participating countries. Subsequently, UNDP country offices held national-level stakeholder consultations to consolidate the findings and recommendations of the assessments. This work benefited immensely from the support of government FOREWORD Energy and Poverty in China vi officials and representatives of civil society. Documented in individual country reports, this work serves as resource and reference material for programming and planning for access to modern energy services for the underserved, particularly, the poor. This document is a summary of the Country Report on China and is part of a series of REP-PoR\u2019s Asia-Pacific publications. It draws on the key findings of the Country Report, summarizes the challenges faced at the national level, and provides priority recommendations. Specifically, critical issues related to energy policy, including institutional structures, regulatory frameworks, priority programmes, financing measures, gender concerns, as well as monitoring and evaluation support are highlighted. It offers a way forward, outlining issues and options for the country. Our hope is that this document will be of relevance to national policy makers, development partners, energy service providers, civil society organizations and academia in implementing various measures to promote access to modern energy services for the poor. Marcia V.J.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "9e2f15f2-f0d8-4d17-b10a-46d92ceab54c": {"__data__": {"id_": "9e2f15f2-f0d8-4d17-b10a-46d92ceab54c", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-china", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in China", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-china", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "67fe942a10b69908babd4fab08626503006e5b9c29201d200626884e3b07e92e"}, "2": {"node_id": "9fdc5355-ad7e-48f5-b218-0ad7e15d9b71", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-china", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "cbf47ad462a471193ebe681dc9088d3f7f3d3c73f7b2a323d1b92fe27b0eb2fa"}}, "hash": "97be2673e4b71c4ac3c6d624fe4809f8f4e34481e1d34c714100dacddd0b5a2c", "text": "Marcia V.J. Kran Head of Policy and Programmes UNDP Regional Centre in Bangkok vii Energy and Poverty in China This report sets out to examine the ways and means for providing affordable, accessible and reliable energy services in support of achievement of the Millennium Development Goals (MDGs) and poverty reduction in China. The underlying premise of this study is that access to affordable and sustainable sources of energy has strong links to poverty reduction. This is particularly the case in terms of energy and its effects on household income, health, education, gender and the environment. The", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "79e36e8b-1e13-4611-9f3b-aacfd53d9562": {"__data__": {"id_": "79e36e8b-1e13-4611-9f3b-aacfd53d9562", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-china", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in China", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-china", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "85fa7bca24d3b73c7bdd1b172a9901efdb16c016c20962cb01a0a66d08a270f7"}}, "hash": "85fa7bca24d3b73c7bdd1b172a9901efdb16c016c20962cb01a0a66d08a270f7", "text": "report also offers options for the country to overcome its energy sector challenges. As a result of rapid economic growth, China has seen significant progress in poverty reduction over the past few decades. Energy demand has increased simultaneously, and China is today a major energy consumer as well as a producer in the world. Despite the progress in the energy sector, regional imbalances keep many rural households away from the benefits brought by modern energy services. Although almost all Chinese villages have access to electricity, electricity use in poor households is less than one-third of that in higher-income households, and still a number of households in remote villages are deprived of access to any kind of electricity. China\u2019s poor still use inefficient technologies and sources of energy. Straw and fuelwood account for 54 percent and coal 33 percent of energy requirements of rural households, which indicates that indoor air pollution still poses serious health problems in poor households with traditional cook stoves. Inefficient and coal dependent rural industries are yet another source of pollution that threatens health and environment in China. This study examines critical energy issues in China related to institutional structure of the energy sector, policy and regulatory framework, and sectoral programmes. It analyses reasons for the limited reach of energy services to rural provinces; unsustainable dependence on traditional fuels and inefficient technologies; the restricted supply of energy by rural energy enterprises; and inadequate financing for energy. Gender concerns are also examined in rural energy projects and programmes. It highlights the urgent need for key data and indicators to support monitoring and evaluation of energy access for areas that are least served. PREFACE Energy and Poverty in China viii This report concludes that limited national-level coordinating mechanisms and local-level capacities constrain the targeted provision of energy services to poor communities and the fulfilling of the MDGs. The rationale is that a strengthened institutional approach can synergize energy development strategies with poverty reduction objectives and distribute benefits from improved access to modern energy services more equally. An improved coordination mechanism targeting all energy sector players at the national, provincial and municipality levels and specific capacity-building interventions for rural energy institutions can be evolved to scale-up energy access in the country. Promising energy initiatives can and do exist in China. A pilot programme to build small hydropower plants in rural areas so as to replace traditional fuel with hydropower began in 2003, and by the end of 2004, 27 small hydropower plants were built and 300,000 farmers were able to shift to hydropower. The Ministry of Agriculture has also successfully initiated development of improved cook stoves, biogas and biomass gasification systems in households and rural industries. Nevertheless, the top-down energy-programme formulation in China in general could benefit from wider integration of local concerns. Energy demand surveys and needs analyses among rural households by local governance bodies and capacity building of community-based organizations to engage meaningfully in the exercise can help replace current top-down programming practices. Promoting cooperation and exchange between eastern and western areas of China could also be valuable. Provinces and counties with sound rural energy capacities and with successful energy-service practices could play key roles in facilitating improved energy service systems on a wider scale. The commitment of the Government of China to the promotion of polices for rural energy and renewable energy development over the years is highly commendable. These policies have encouraged government spending in the area of energy, which has led to some tangible success. The Law on Renewable Energy was also put into effect in 2006. Nevertheless, this report also notes that a comprehensive national energy law, which is currently at the draft stage, is of great importance to the effectiveness of the long-term energy strategies and needs to be operationalized soon. Improving affordability of energy services for the poor requires restructuring existing energy service networks and infusing a pro-poor tariff regime within service networks. Independent community electricity networks powered by locally available renewable energy sources (biomass, solar, wind, etc.) could be part of the solution. To achieve greater energy efficiency in rural SMEs and elsewhere, the technology input must be complemented by a strong policy framework that encourages and ix Energy and Poverty in China rewards the efficient use of energy. Especially important is the design of well-targeted pro-poor subsidy and tax policies, as well as improved schemes for encouraging cooperatives to supply micro-financing for small energy projects and income-generating activities. Such policies can have a major impact on the capital costs of rural grid electrification and the development of off-grid solutions. These policies could also be key to ensuring the", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "eb1ae967-ed94-4142-8536-a7e5def951c7": {"__data__": {"id_": "eb1ae967-ed94-4142-8536-a7e5def951c7", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-china", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in China", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-china", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "ada361dda4fe1daa4f57b599a2e76edfdde1f6dec7d964f59a74d8b8073d9914"}, "3": {"node_id": "2086c38b-a914-4c36-b93c-5b0986b01e09", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-china", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "34cab799b450074140def74bbb8ca9fe5eb39b1877bd2c9f92c8054bb2db2d11"}}, "hash": "6b15a8a0478d4ad1e266917ce56a5d7b6ba257d5de92f5337936e707edd524b5", "text": "provision of low-cost energy services to poor people. We trust that this report is unique in terms of its insights into bridging the gaps between access to energy and poverty reduction in China. Our aim is to provide country-specific information on institutional structures, energy resources, policy recommendations, and capacity and financial gaps that can point the way towards improving access to modern energy services, particularly for the poor. Nandita Mongia Regional Programme Coordinator and Team Leader Regional Energy Programme for Poverty Reduction UNDP Regional Centre in Bangkok xi Energy and Poverty in China ACKNOWLEDGEMENTS Energy and Poverty in China: Challenges and the Way Forward is the result of a partnership initiative of the United Nations Development Programme (UNDP) Asia-Pacific Regional Energy Programme for Poverty Reduction (REP-PoR). It benefits from collaboration between the UNDP Regional Centre in Bangkok (RCB), UNDP China Country Office, key national stakeholders and regional experts. This report is the fifth in the series of nine country reports for Asia and a synthesis report on similar lines for the Pacific Island countries. Like any multi-stakeholder work, this report reflects the efforts of many people over the last two years. We would like to express our appreciation for the inputs, suggestions and support provided by them. Our appreciation goes to the excellent support of the Energy and Environment Team of UNDP China in the entire process of the gap assessment and the preparation of the original Country Report. The UNDP Country Office focal point in China, He Ping, provided strong support through many rounds of review and comments, in addition to providing critical data and information to complete this report. We convey our profound gratitude to key officials of the Ministry of Agriculture, the National Development and Reform Commission, Energy Research Institute of China for their expert reviews and comments at the national consultations of the gap assessment that preceded the preparation of this report. We would like to acknowledge the national experts, Mr. Fang Yan and Mr. Liu Xin, who were responsible for preparing the original Country Report and going the extra mile in capturing, consolidating and processing all the inputs gathered from an elaborate country consultative process. Ibrahim Hafeezur Rehman provided overall technical backstopping and insightful guidance in the preparation of the original report to the country team. The analytical structure and conceptualization of the gap assessment report went through many rounds of reviews and revisions by the core REP-PoR team in RCB, namely Nandita Mongia, Thiyagarajan Velumail, Thomas Jensen and Bhava Dhungana, during the last two years. We appreciate the inputs from Kamal Rijal, Abu Sadat Moniruzzam Khan, Usha Rao, Sooksiri Chamsuk and Sanna Salmela-Eckstein who contributed at different stages to finalizing the country report. Energy and Poverty in China xii We appreciate and acknowledge Keen Media for editing and doing the layout of this report. All of the above-mentioned efforts have made the writing of this report possible.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "2086c38b-a914-4c36-b93c-5b0986b01e09": {"__data__": {"id_": "2086c38b-a914-4c36-b93c-5b0986b01e09", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-china", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in China", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-china", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "ada361dda4fe1daa4f57b599a2e76edfdde1f6dec7d964f59a74d8b8073d9914"}, "2": {"node_id": "eb1ae967-ed94-4142-8536-a7e5def951c7", "node_type": null, "metada