te 1970s. Since then, China has set the stage for rapid economic growth with continuous experimentation and multi-staged market reform. China\u2019s energy policies also emanated from the overall reforms for economic development. Its primary goals were to increase energy supply, optimize energy structure, and improve the quality of people\u2019s lives as well as their environment. Improving", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "6e17c2f8-c6ea-436c-aba3-115c8bb63f1c": {"__data__": {"id_": "6e17c2f8-c6ea-436c-aba3-115c8bb63f1c", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-china", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in China", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-china", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "06d6e659bd059f30190c54dda86a09c8b104254603868d187fc5882458b51b60"}, "3": {"node_id": "b5b87dee-4ec5-4d70-9864-462d25351ef0", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-china", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "42907c9df05c9c5d39a718710788c9a553e50c21f4ff104d87aea5795132cf9f"}}, "hash": "d2b46cf117a8cece9e00baa63f280d99bdcde5620736dc9bf5ea5514cd41f009", "text": "the energy efficiency of cooking and heating facilities and increasing the supply of commercial energy in rural areas were major components of the energy policy. To some extent, one of the key reasons behind China\u2019s success lies in the decoupling of economic growth with energy growth through policies and extensive energy efficiency programmes. Significant progress has also been made in policies and regulations at the local level. Due to efforts made by various agencies, a legal framework has gradually been established for rural energy development. Over 20 provinces have adopted proactive policies to encourage rural energy development. A lot of municipality- and county-level governments have also formulated relevant policies and regulations. Despite impressive achievements, China still has formidable challenges on the poverty front. The poor residing in rural China\u2019s hinterlands still live in sordid conditions and remain highly vulnerable to natural calamities. They are distanced from industrialized coastal provinces and are therefore lacking access to the benefits of modern energy services. According to the 2000 Monitoring and Evaluation Report on Rural Poverty in China, electricity use in poor households is less than one-third of that in higher-income households (NBS 2001). This keeps low-income sectors of the population away from the benefits of economic development and opportunities brought about by electricity services. Similarly, many rural households still use inefficient sources of energy \u2013 such as straw and fuelwood \u2013 for residential heating and cooking. In 2004, straw and fuelwood together had a 54 percent share in rural residential energy use, while liquefied petroleum gas (LPG) had a toehold at 1 percent (see Figure 1). This indicates the persistence of known social and economic fallouts attributed to these traditional fuel sources, such as exposure to indoor air pollution (IAP), increases in respiratory ailments, loss of productive time, and environmental degradation. 3 Energy and Poverty in China BACKGROUND FIGURE 1 COMPOSITION OF CHINA\u2019S RURAL RESIDENTIAL ENERGY USE (2004) B THE CHALLENGES THE CHALLENGES In rural China, the dominance of traditional fuels and the absence of modern energy services threaten to derail China\u2019s commitments towards the MDGs. An analysis of China\u2019s energy sector, with special attention to its connections to the country\u2019s rural poverty reduction agenda, indicates that gaps are slowing the impact that modern energy could have on the lives of the rural poor. Some of these gaps are discussed in this document. Institutional arrangements for energy access and poverty reduction efore the 1980s, \u2018rural energy\u2019 was not a strong agenda item and an integrated rural energy management system did not exist. The focus on rural energy development had been on individual technologies for specific problem solving. In the mid-1980s, the Central Government set up the Leading Group for the Comprehensive Development of Rural Energy to coordinate among various agencies. It was led by the former State Planning Commission, and comprised ministries such as the Ministry of Agriculture (MoA), the State Forestry Ministry (SFM), the Ministry of Water Resources (MoWR) and the Ministry of Power Industries (MoPI). Similar leading groups were also established at provincial and county levels. Source NBS (2005) 4 Energy and Poverty in China THE CHALLENGES 2 The State Planning Commission was renamed the State Development Planning Commission (SDPC) in 1998. 3 In 2003, the SDPC was restructured into the NDRC. The former State Planning Commission was responsible for overall planning, design and coordination, and for allocation of financial resources. The MoA was responsible for development of energy-saving technologies, such as energy-saving cooking stoves and stoves to heat kangs (brick-beds used in rural China\u2019s northern regions); promotion of technologies that utilize agricultural by-products and waste (through biomass gasification, carbonization, liquefaction, or ethanol production and fermentation) as well as human and animal waste; and development of new energy sources, such as solar, wind, geothermal, and small-scale hydropower. The SFM was responsible for planting and utilization of fuelwood. It was the responsibility of the MoWR to construct small-scale hydropower plants and the MoPI to construct power grids for rural areas. As economic reform in China deepened, the country\u2019s energy institutional arrangements experienced a sea change. As per the rules of the new economy, energy enterprises were pushed into the market. They became the major actors in market competition, while the Government\u2019s role was geared towards energy programming and energy macro- management. Energy institutions at both the national and local levels became relatively decentralized.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "b5b87dee-4ec5-4d70-9864-462d25351ef0": {"__data__": {"id_": "b5b87dee-4ec5-4d70-9864-462d25351ef0", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-china", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in China", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-china", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "06d6e659bd059f30190c54dda86a09c8b104254603868d187fc5882458b51b60"}, "2": {"node_id": "6e17c2f8-c6ea-436c-aba3-115c8bb63f1c", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-china", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "d2b46cf117a8cece9e00baa63f280d99bdcde5620736dc9bf5ea5514cd41f009"}}, "hash": "42907c9df05c9c5d39a718710788c9a553e50c21f4ff104d87aea5795132cf9f", "text": "Energy institutions at both the national and local levels became relatively decentralized. Organizations such as the former State Development and Planning Commission (SDPC)2, the State Economic and Trade Commission (SETC), the MoWR and the MoA undertook the task of energy management. The roles of these organizations were defined in terms of the immediate managing objectives, while the comprehensive and", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "ea0cbdfc-decc-4d5f-940f-2d88b7e68609": {"__data__": {"id_": "ea0cbdfc-decc-4d5f-940f-2d88b7e68609", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-china", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in China", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-china", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "129e98dabb9c8f4538342317cd9c68f0a772d2a1317a18c3a703d0609b7dceb0"}, "3": {"node_id": "f1e71a9f-98ae-454d-ab09-160002a8e821", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-china", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "befbba8332e16ca29b987bdd8703b248e45ccd6d0dd20778f173cfa6c0ee478b"}}, "hash": "eee3c070c740435f625d8985360e094e02dea33ff448243c6e9d911b3326e1f7", "text": "long-term management was weak. Furthermore, the decentralized energy management model in China lacked strategy management; it could not adapt to the sustainable development demands on energy and economy. In March 2003, the new Chinese Government proposed and passed the new institutional reform scheme of the State Council and decided to establish the National Energy Bureau (NEB) within the newly built National Development and Reform Commission (NDRC)3. The NEB was established by reorganizing the former SDPC, the former SETC, and some other commissions and bureaus. At a national level, it acts as a comprehensive energy management organization. NEB\u2019s main responsibility is to study and establish national energy development strategies, policies and regulations, and programmes. It has to guide and coordinate the development of the energy industry, examine and 5 Energy and Poverty in China THE CHALLENGES supervise the price of energy, and manage the energy sector strategically. The implementation of this reform scheme has had a crucial impact on the sustainable development of energy in China. Yet, since the NDRC and other ministries wield the authority, achieving synergy between them has been challenging, and the NEB has not been able to manage the energy work very well. For example, in the same year that NEB was created, the State Electricity Regulatory Commission (SERC) was also established. Only a year later did the Central Government demarcate the functions of electricity pricing and electricity market supervision between the NDRC and the SERC. And, operationally, their work areas are still not distinct. This is one of the key reasons why the new electricity power law cannot be finally modified and issued. Within the NDRC (and besides the NEB), there are also other departments \u2013 such as the Economy Operation Department, Price Department, and Resource and Environment Department \u2013 that have the power to conduct energy management exercises. With the fast developing Chinese economy, energy has become a vital strategic issue that concerns national economic development, social stability and national security. The National Energy Leading Group (NELG) was established on 13 May 2005. The aim of NELG is to provide coordination of energy policy development at the highest level of the Government. The Group is headed by Premier Wen Jiabao, and the ministers of the following ministries are the members of the Group: NDRC, Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Ministry of Science and Technology (MoST), National Security Science and Technology Commission, Ministry of Finance (MoF), Ministry of Land and Resources, MoA, Ministry of Commerce (MoC), State Assets Commission, State Environmental Protection Administration, State Administration of Work Safety, and SERC. The Deputy General Chief of Staff at the Headquarters of the General Staff of the People\u2019s Liberation Army (PLA) is also a member. To support the work of the NELG, the Office of the National Energy Leading Group (ONELG) was formed in May 2005. ONELG is a policy development think-tank. Its key policy responsibility is to provide in-depth research and analysis into key energy issues in China. Currently, ONELG is in charge of the development of the Energy Law, conducts research in other macro energy policies and provides recommendations to the State Council (see Figure 2). Achieving synergy between the NDRC and other ministries has been challenging. 6 Energy and Poverty in China THE CHALLENGES FIGURE 2 CHINA\u2019S NATIONAL ENERGY INSTITUTIONAL ARRANGEMENTS At the provincial level, institutions such as the provincial Economic and Trade Commission (ETC), the provincial Development and Reform Commission (DRC), and the Electric Power (Power Grid) Company organize and manage the production and logistics of electric power, coal, oil, and so on. They also execute the orders of the Government for these energy sources. The local energy institutions\u2019 frameworks follow the provincial one. Within this hierarchical institutional arrangement, access to energy services in rural areas has been taken into consideration at all levels. In this regard, the Leading Group for the Comprehensive Development of Rural Energy, set up by the Central Government, continues to coordinate among various energy agencies. The coordination aims to identify rural energy needs and implement suitable development projects, within the original structure for rural energy management (see Figure 3).", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "f1e71a9f-98ae-454d-ab09-160002a8e821": {"__data__": {"id_": "f1e71a9f-98ae-454d-ab09-160002a8e821", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-china", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in China", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-china", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "129e98dabb9c8f4538342317cd9c68f0a772d2a1317a18c3a703d0609b7dceb0"}, "2": {"node_id": "ea0cbdfc-decc-4d5f-940f-2d88b7e68609", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-china", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "eee3c070c740435f625d8985360e094e02dea33ff448243c6e9d911b3326e1f7"}}, "hash": "befbba8332e16ca29b987bdd8703b248e45ccd6d0dd20778f173cfa6c0ee478b", "text": "Source State Council (2005) 7 Energy and Poverty in China THE CHALLENGES FIGURE 3 INSTITUTIONAL ARRANGEMENTS AT THE DECENTRALIZED LEVEL In addition to the endeavours of national- and local-level energy agencies, efforts to provide access to energy services have also been made by non-energy-sector institutions such as the Poverty Alleviation Office in the State Council, or the National Poverty Alleviation Leading Group (NPALG). Yet, just as it has taken time to achieve a fairly integrated institutional framework for energy issues, a national-level coordinating agency that can create synergy between", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "ca51a99a-1133-4808-ab29-4a813758b057": {"__data__": {"id_": "ca51a99a-1133-4808-ab29-4a813758b057", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-china", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in China", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-china", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "aeb945e3a2bc66af2f2ae26a5908d654ace0309ca9e049a0670be512a7431bb7"}}, "hash": "aeb945e3a2bc66af2f2ae26a5908d654ace0309ca9e049a0670be512a7431bb7", "text": "the energy and poverty issues is still relatively weak. Due to the current institutional arrangement, access to energy services is missing from most poverty reduction strategies. \u25a0 Ineffective mechanisms for coordinating energy and poverty issues. \u25a0 Lack of guidance by rural energy technology institutes to the relevant research and policy development bodies. \u25a0 Limited capacity at local-level institutions. BOX 1: KEY INSTITUTIONAL CHALLENGES RELATED TO THE INTEGRATION OF ENERGY WITH THE POVERTY AGENDA Access to energy services is missing from most poverty reduction strategies. Source Kewen (2000) 8 Energy and Poverty in China THE CHALLENGES Policy and regulatory frameworks do not adequately address cost and affordability Policies and regulations are essential for rural energy development. They not only guide the development of rural energy, but also serve as a foundation for the rural energy market. Since the 1990s, China has formulated a number of policies to promote rural energy development. In 1994, \u2018rural renewable energy development\u2019 was incorporated into China\u2019s Agenda 21, the Tenth Five Year Plan for Economic Development, and Long-term Objectives for 2010. In 1995, the State Council of China ratified the Report on the Development of New Energy and Renewable Energy. In 1997, China put into effect the Law of the People\u2019s Republic of China on Energy Conservation, which is not only about energy conservation, but also requires that rural energy development be strengthened. Article 38 of the law states the following: \u201cGovernments at all levels shall promote rural energy development according to the guiding principle of respecting local conditions, developing multiple energy sources which complement one another, and utilizing energy comprehensively and efficiently, and devote necessary efforts to develop renewable and new energy sources such as methane, solar energy, wind energy, hydro energy and thermal energy.\u201d This law serves as a legal basis for the development of rural energy and for the formulation of special or local rural energy development policies and regulations. These policies have encouraged government spending in the area of energy, which has led to some tangible success. Since 1998, the Chinese Government has spent 180 billion yuan in renovating the rural power grids, reforming the rural power management system, and adopting a policy of \u2018same price for the same power grid\u2019 for both urban and rural areas. After just three years of these efforts, the price of electricity decreased and the quality of power supply improved. Many farmers purchased home appliances and consumed more electricity to manufacture agricultural by-products. Despite the progress in policy interventions that carry modern energy services to rural areas, however, high cost and low affordability keep the rural and poor populations at bay from modern energy services. In 2000, it was estimated that about 7 million households in remote villages were deprived of access to any kind of electricity. Likewise, many poor households in electrified villages have been unable to benefit from electricity services because of low income. Electricity consumption by poor rural households is less than a third of higher-income households (UNDP 2001). Many poor households in electrified villages have been unable to benefit from electricity services because of low income. 9 Energy and Poverty in China THE CHALLENGES Since 2002, the Central Government has been issuing policy documents on rural development to combat these statistics. These documents underscore the importance of small-scale rural infrastructure facilities, including water-saving irrigation facilities, drinking water facilities for humans and animals, methane facilities, water and power facilities, roads, grassland fences, and so on. The Agriculture Law of the People\u2019s Republic of China emphasizes that in the process of rural economic development, natural resources shall be used rationally. It also states that renewable and clean energy sources shall be developed, while ecological agricultural practices shall be encouraged so as to protect and improve the environment. In 2003, the Chinese Government kicked off a pilot programme to build small hydropower plants in rural areas so as to replace traditional fuel with hydropower. The primary objective of the programme was to subsidize some rural areas to build small hydropower plants so as to lower the price of electricity. Farmers could then replace traditional fuels \u2013 firewood or coal \u2013 with low-priced electricity for cooking and heating. This would not only lessen farmers\u2019 dependency on firewood for fuel, but also protect forests and vegetation cover, and conserve ecological resources. By the end of 2004, the programme had been implemented in 26 counties (or municipalities) of five provinces (Sichuan, Yunnan, Guangxi, Guizhou and Shanxi). Twenty-seven small hydropower plants were built, and 300,000 farmers were able to shift to hydropower. With these small successes in rural renewable energy, more attention has also been given to", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "acf6cb99-1e84-4f40-bbf8-32db7772e8aa": {"__data__": {"id_": "acf6cb99-1e84-4f40-bbf8-32db7772e8aa", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-china", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in China", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-china", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "c0a30e852cf4ffb6b7962f406c3ee772905b0a827c9482be6036dd296e41592d"}, "3": {"node_id": "c671bc90-0159-4559-b978-7ad7137d6ff3", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-china", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "ddb398ed97583d7a2be2de08fcfaa2e31f12819310608b6c1615ca8206d57c0e"}}, "hash": "f9c2bdfcf3eeefabce89d3e22afd936579da90fd1d361eba3c2c5db0c15b309c", "text": "renewable energy at a national level. China\u2019s National People\u2019s Congress ratified the Law of the People\u2019s Repub- lic of China on Renewable Energy and it was put into effect on 1 January, 2006. The law addresses the development of renewable energy as a national interest, and requires the support of all members of society. It also stipulates that the Government shall take on major responsibilities in developing renewable energy. To this effect, the law establishes legal mechanisms in five respective areas: market cultivation and protection; resource development and planning; technological and industrial support; price support and cost sharing; and financial support and economic incentives. It also stipulates that the Treasury of the Central Government shall establish a special \u2018renewable energy development fund\u2019 to support renewable energy research and development, the formulation of product and technical standards, and energy development in economically disadvantaged regions. 10 Energy and Poverty in China THE CHALLENGES Despite these policy interventions, a legal national energy system has not yet been set up, which weakens the effectiveness of long-term energy strategies and polices. A draft of China\u2019s first energy law is being reviewed for further revisions. It is expected to be finalized in 2008. This overarching law for the country\u2019s energy industry and trade will address issues of energy planning, exploration, conservation, reserves and technological innovation. Hopefully, these policy advances will further the spread of modern energy access that rural China has been witnessing since the late 1970s. Progress has been made \u2013 for example through the previously mentioned hydropower plants \u2013 and rural consumption of modern commercial energy sources (coal, oil, electricity, and so on), vis-\u00e0-vis the total rural residential and energy consumption, has risen from 28 percent in 1987 to 43 percent in 2004. In China, both residential and productive energy consumption in rural areas has increased greatly between 1987 and 2004 (see Figure 4). In the same period, the use of crop straw and fuelwood in the total rural household energy mix saw a decrease from 71 percent to 54 percent. Almost all Chinese villages (99 percent) had access to electricity in 2003 with variation across the country, ranging from 86 percent in Qinghai to 100 percent in many areas like Hubei, Shandong and Jiangsu; and the use of modern energy for cooking also saw a substantial increase (see Figure 5). Yet, while access to modern energy is on the rise, the issue still requires critical attention with regards to affordability and the equal im- plementation of macro-level change across broad rural regions. FIGURE 4 CHINA\u2019S RURAL RESIDENTIAL AND PRODUCTIVE ENERGY CONSUMPTION: 1987-2004 Source NBS (2005) 11 Energy and Poverty in China THE CHALLENGES FIGURE 5 NUMBER OF RURAL HOUSEHOLDS USING CLEAN ENERGY IN CHINA: 1987-2004 A top-down programme framework with inadequate rural participation The current strategy of rural energy programmes in China emphasizes new energy development and utilization, clean energy and energy efficiency. The programmes are based on policies and objectives announced in the Tenth Five-Year Plan for New Energy and Renewable Energy Industry Development 2004-2020 (NDRC 2001), the Medium and Long-term Energy Development Planning Outline (NDRC 2004a), and the Medium and Long-term Energy-Conservation Plan (NDRC 2004b). The programme framework is guided by China\u2019s environmental priorities of reducing greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions and conserving non-renewable energy assets. For instance, the Demonstration County of \u25a0 Lack of policy a