oal having the largest share in rural domestic energy consumption (87 percent combined), energy efficiency programmes focus on improving the efficiency of traditional cook stoves that use these fuels. It is estimated that approximately 150,000 children under the age of five years die every year from acute lower-respiratory infections that have a direct link with IAP caused by inefficient cook stoves (Smith 2005). Such cook stoves have low-heating efficiency (less than 10 percent) and are used by over 40 million rural households, mostly in China\u2019s poorer interiors. This figure would be much higher if not for the decades of technology development which have facilitated a degree of popularization of high-efficiency cook stoves. These cook stoves can operate on fuelwood with a 20-30 percent heating efficiency, or on coal stoves with a 30-40 percent heating efficiency. The increased penetration of clean energy sources for cooking is being simultaneously pursued. Table 1 illustrates an increase in the number of households using clean energy in China between 1986 and 2004, with biogas utilization in particular being widely adopted in rural areas. Source MoA (2005); Editorial Board of CREY (1998) TABLE 1 NUMBER OF RURAL HOUSEHOLDS USING CLEAN ENERGY IN CHINA: 1986-2004 (10,000 HOUSEHOLDS) 1986 352.41 78.77 2.02 1.60 71.16 1987 365.9 123.75 2.18 4.07 102.27 1988 368.82 190.33 2.2 8.31 170.47 1989 376.67 339.64 4.34 24.57 380.49 1990 272.21 471.38 6.83 35.8 547.45 1991 392.79 752.56 29.5 41.7 826.13 1992 404.46 1007.38 38.13 57.69 1016.44 1993 433.82 1354.43 50.37 117.51 1321.7 1994 463.75 1673.64 57.36 146.66 1612.83 1995 517.45 2035.48 64.25 173.84 1986.78 1996 517.85 2048.44 40.56 91.47 1788.24 1997 NA NA NA NA NA 1998 NA 2744.12 29.03 54.63 2198.77 1999 610.27 3030.74 49.68 55.12 2121.32 2000 664.03 3284.93 51.36 57.09 NA 2001 872.57 4081.21 115.12 88.75 NA 2002 1027.43 4066.92 100.38 71.63 NA 2003 1228.60 4645.72 80.24 92.72 NA 2004 1465.07 5035.57 98.17 115.52 NA H