 RSMEs (including manufacturers of bricks, cement, coking coal, foundry and paper) is much lower than that of the country\u2019s average (32 percent). In 2000, the manufacturing areas mentioned above accounted for 55 percent of the total energy consumption of RSMEs in China. Consequently, they were also responsible for high levels of emissions \u2013 57 percent of the total rural air pollution is a result of coal combustion for RSME use. In the 1980s, the Government initiated its energy efficiency strategy for industries, which focused on technological innovation. The approach has been successful in urban industrial set-ups. However, it has had limited impact on RSMEs, which are neither state-owned enterprises nor bodies with modern-market incentives to embrace technological innovation. RSMEs in China account for 43 percent of total rural energy consumption (Editorial Board of CTVEY 2005). Lack of accessible information, capacity development and incentive mechanisms are the major barriers that hinder RSMEs from participating in technical upgrades and training projects organized by the Government, such as SETC and MoST. Constrained rural energy entrepreneurship Notwithstanding the", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "0547e4dd-2d42-4c5b-9e8d-ee9670771aa0": {"__data__": {"id_": "0547e4dd-2d42-4c5b-9e8d-ee9670771aa0", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-china", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in China", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-china", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "c985b137974ad6694644e0e9492749915a05211f90f03db7c8c09ae107e5c846"}, "3": {"node_id": "74e97f4d-db77-4aa7-927c-9c462fc1deee", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-china", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "0918f43b5e5f1c2bb24116c350c1e23c5921b808882635cdcafe9f8b50a44667"}}, "hash": "80fb67131d06555aec1c235c355a593f0d1f589322463bfe660a3944f25deef5", "text": "overarching state control on productive activity in China and the consequent dominance of state-owned industries, private entrepreneurs have gradually created a niche for themselves. In 2005, the State Council Notice on Encouraging and Guiding the Development of Individual-owned, Private-owned, and Other Types of Non-state-owned Economy was issued to permit non-state-owned capital to enter industrial and service sectors. \u25a0 Households with low incomes continue to use traditional cook stoves. \u25a0 RSMEs experience barriers to the promotion of energy efficiency due to lack of accessible information and capacity development. BOX 4: KEY CHALLENGES IN PROMOTING RURAL ENERGY EFFICIENCY 15 Energy and Poverty in China THE CHALLENGES The energy sector in particular has seen growing private investment, with the untapped potential for modern energy services in rural China attracting keen entrepreneurial interest (see Figures 6a and 6b). There are two types of private energy entrepreneurs: the energy production-based type that produce energy or sell equipment and parts; and energy service enterprises that provide after-sales service for equipment and parts, technology consulting and training. By 2004, over 1,100 private energy production-based enterprises had established themselves in rural areas, employing over 19,000 people. These enterprises have been particularly active in the renewable energy sector \u2013 solar energy, biomass, biogas, and so on. In the same year, 2,240 private energy service producers emerged in rural China, employing over 15,000 people (MoA 2005). However, rural energy enterprises (like all RSMEs) are beset by problems of obsolete technology, inadequately trained personnel, and restricted access to credit and finance. The financial and technological hurdles are especially acute in energy-based ventures, which require more investments in modern technology and processes than, for example, a traditional-style brick- or cement-making facility. As a result, many energy-based enterprises fail to sustain themselves in the long run. FIGURE 6A RURAL ENERGY PRODUCTION- BASED ENTERPRISES Source MoA (2005) 16 Energy and Poverty in China THE CHALLENGES FIGURE 6B RURAL ENERGY SERVICE ENTERPRISES \u25a0 Rural energy enterprises are beset by problems of obsolete technology, inadequately trained personnel, and restricted access to credit and finance. \u25a0 Lack of standard operating rules or policies to guide non-state- owned enterprises wishing to enter the energy industry. \u25a0 Lack of official incentive mechanisms further dissuades private enterprise from investing in areas deemed unprofitable. BOX 5: KEY CHALLENGES IN PROMOTING ENERGY ENTREPRENEURSHIP Constrained financial support for rural energy development China\u2019s transition from a planned economy to a market economy forced changes in financing for rural energy development. Previously, in the 1980s, the Central Government provided annual funds for rural energy development from its financial budget. Then, over the course of the 1990s, government support shifted to a loan mechanism for rural energy projects, including infrastructure, technological innovation and small hydropower plants, which were supported through loans from banking institutions. However, since the restructuring of the financial sector, the state-owned banking institutions have emerged as independent commercial banks, and provisions like loans for energy projects have been abolished. Source MoA (2005) 17 Energy and Poverty in China THE CHALLENGES One benefit of this modality is that rural areas earlier serviced only by the government-owned Agricultural Bank of China and Agricultural Development Bank of China can now theoretically gain access to commercial bank loans. However, in actuality, many rural entrepreneurs have found it difficult to take advantage of commercial bank funding. Loans to RSMEs comprised only 6 percent of all bank loans in 2003, a figure attributed largely to the lack of information in banks about the profit potential of rural enterprises, and rural energy enterprises in particular. For instance, banks have limited knowledge about the biogas industry, and therefore have not developed credit services for biogas projects. Since the late 1990s, the support for rural energy development has reverted to the previous modality: the Government acts as the major fund provider for rural energy projects and rural energy development depends mainly on fiscal support. Thus, energy funding in China has become a self-propagating problem, as exemplified in the biogas industry. Government-subsidized biogas construction projects have led farmers to believe that the Government will provide a subsidy at the time of construction of a biogas plant. Therefore, many farmers are not willing to utilize loans from energy service enterprises.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "74e97f4d-db77-4aa7-927c-9c462fc1deee": {"__data__": {"id_": "74e97f4d-db77-4aa7-927c-9c462fc1deee", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-china", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in China", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-china", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "c985b137974ad6694644e0e9492749915a05211f90f03db7c8c09ae107e5c846"}, "2": {"node_id": "0547e4dd-2d42-4c5b-9e8d-ee9670771aa0", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-china", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "80fb67131d06555aec1c235c355a593f0d1f589322463bfe660a3944f25deef5"}}, "hash": "0918f43b5e5f1c2bb24116c350c1e23c5921b808882635cdcafe9f8b50a44667", "text": "Therefore, many farmers are not willing to utilize loans from energy service enterprises. Instead, the traditional administrative command and financial subsidy modules have persisted, thus narrowing RSME opportunities for clean-technology adoption and capacity development. \u25a0 Commercial financial institutions prefer to stay away from rural financial markets and focus on the more profitable urban markets, only limited market-oriented schemes for energy projects are unavailable to RSMEs, thus rural energy construction remains over dependent on government subsidies. \u25a0 Due to policy limitations, rural cooperative financing \u2013 especially", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "57837eaa-536b-4c12-af31-56c4f54d97b8": {"__data__": {"id_": "57837eaa-536b-4c12-af31-56c4f54d97b8", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-china", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in China", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-china", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "fb4058cbe0edda96ee1c0c3cb38cc02e5108744276418347550afea2387fcb45"}}, "hash": "fb4058cbe0edda96ee1c0c3cb38cc02e5108744276418347550afea2387fcb45", "text": "micro-credit \u2013 is difficult to develop, resulting in the growth of informal financing that in turn increases the financial risks of borrowers. BOX 6: KEY CHALLENGES RELATED TO FINANCING Gender concerns Chinese women are the backbone of rural economies, with about 74 percent of women economically active at the local level. Hence, any energy initiative that focuses on poverty reduction would necessarily require special Banks have limited knowledge about the profit potential of rural energy enterprises. 18 Energy and Poverty in China THE CHALLENGES mechanisms to involve women. Even more importantly, it is doubly beneficial to include women in energy initiatives because the energy needs of women are often different from men \u2013 for example with regards to cooking and traditional work. There has been a lack of focus on reducing drudgery for poor, rural women (mostly caused by traditional cooking practices). These deeper dimensions of poverty keep rural women excluded from healthier lives and empowerment. Even though improved cook stoves have been relatively well-disseminated in China, traditional stoves and kitchen ranges (generally with two heat openings \u2013 one for cooking food and the other for livestock) still persist. Each of these heat openings has a huge burning chamber, but rarely possesses an installed chimney. Biofuel burned in this kind of installation has low heat efficiency. Yet, in 2004, 41 million Chinese farmers living in low-income regions (out of a total of 230 million farmers) were still using these inefficient, old-style stoves and kitchen ranges. The smoke and dust from these stoves and kitchen ranges has adverse effects on health, especially that of rural women. They are the direct victims of IAP caused by inefficient energy use. According to a survey done for a rural energy research project (in natural reserve zones in Sichuan Province in 2005) by the World Wide Fund for Nature (WWF), energy consumption in low-income households is not lower than energy consumption in high-income households, as might otherwise be expected. There are two main reasons for this: firstly, the stoves or kitchen ranges in low-income families have very low energy efficiency (as mentioned above) which results in unnecessary waste of fuelwood; secondly, in low-income regions most farmers still use traditional methods to raise animals such as pigs, which consume quite a lot of fuelwood. While pig rearing is still the most important source of family cash revenues in rural areas in China, it consumes a lot of energy. In economically and technologically advanced regions, farmers usually feed their pigs compound or hybrid feedstuff, neither of which require reheating before being served. In poor areas, conversely, the feed needs to be heated before it is served to animals. An investigation related to energy consumption at farms shows that energy used for heating animal feed is even more than that for cooking food for humans. Millions of farmers still use inefficient stoves in low-income regions. 19 Energy and Poverty in China THE CHALLENGES Lack of linkages between energy and poverty in monitoring and evaluation frameworks In 1993, China established the statistical reporting system for rural energy programmes and projects to collect information on processes and trends relating to renewable energy programmes in rural areas. This has provided the basis for strategy and policy formulation and development of future rural energy programmes. Indicators for this system were further developed in the following years. This led to the yearbook entitled Statistical Summary of Rural Renewable Energy in China in 1996, issued by the MoA\u2019s Science, Technology, and Education Department. From then on, it has been annually published with updated findings. Similarly, to facilitate the enforcement of various poverty alleviation policies and programmes, the NBS launched a poverty-monitoring system for selected rural areas. This culminated in the publication of the 2001- 2010 Action Plan for Rural Poverty Alleviation of China. Despite the presence of such capable monitoring and evaluation (M&E) systems, the monitoring systems and indicators pertaining to energy and poverty operate largely independent of each other. \u25a0 Limited involvement of women in new energy technologies extension programmes. \u25a0 Use of inefficient energy technology by women in rural households. \u25a0 Insufficient attention paid to the poor and women in energy management and development at the national level. \u25a0 Lack of representation by women in the existing rural energy programme framework; women and gender issues are insufficiently represented in programme formulation. BOX 7: KEY CHALLENGES TO ADDRESSING GENDER ISSUES IN ENERGY DEVELOPMENT \u25a0 The baseline data bank of M&E for rural energy projects has not been well-established, rendering the development of energy-poverty indicators much more challenging. \u25a0 Awareness and recognition of the importance of monitoring energy projects has not been", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "892391aa-be02-46cf-a4d4-14db44012503": {"__data__": {"id_": "892391aa-be02-46cf-a4d4-14db44012503", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-china", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in China", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-china", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "fe40fc6d534ee5496e626319650dbc94f84ec9f2c9423c6e365ea05e0b53b7c5"}}, "hash": "fe40fc6d534ee5496e626319650dbc94f84ec9f2c9423c6e365ea05e0b53b7c5", "text": "adequately shared by local governments and related departments. BOX 8: KEY CHALLENGES TO AN EFFECTIVE MONITORING AND EVALUATION FRAMEWORK 20 Energy and Poverty in China THE CHALLENGES Inadequate management and dissemination of energy information China\u2019s energy information is primarily disseminated through three channels: annual reports, such as the Chinese Energy Statistic Yearbook published by the NBS; reports and technical documents from energy associations, such as the China Rural Energy Association (CREA); and energy-related websites, such as the web portal China5e.com, maintained by the consultancy firm Falcon Power Ltd. However, much of the information disseminated in these venues focuses on production and supply of energy, and there is little focus on energy\u2019s linkages with poverty. This hampers targeted interventions in this area. Further, while the MoA and the NBS remain in control of rural energy data collection, the development of the national economy and resultant institutional reform has transferred some data collection functions (including energy-poverty indicators) from the Government to industrial associations. This has weakened data collection capacity at the local level since such associations do not have the services of local administrative units at their disposal. At the national level, China has yet to build an enabling environment for free access to data related to energy, in particular rural energy. Policy formulation for information disclosure has been delayed, and the traditional reluctance to share official information continues to restrict access to energy information. \u25a0 The energy sector lacks an integrated information management system. \u25a0 In some cases, there are no leading organizations to coordinate information collection and processing. \u25a0 Limited access to official information, such as that pertaining to energy. BOX 9: KEY CHALLENGES TO PROPER INFORMATION MANAGEMENT 21 Energy and Poverty in China THE CHALLENGES Strengthening institutional focus on energy and poverty issues he institutional arrangements must include mechanisms to synergize energy development strategies with poverty reduction objectives. A start could be made by strengthening the energy access for poverty reduction agenda of the NPALG. The NPALG could also be linked with the Leading Group for the Comprehensive Development of Rural Energy, thus enabling energy-poverty synergy at the local level. Another way to foster a stronger poverty reduction component in institutional arrangements would involve the creation of a poverty reduction unit within the State Energy Leading Group. This unit could be mandated to serve as the apex energy-poverty institution in China, coordinating the many objectives of various energy-sector players, vis-\u00e0-vis energy-poverty linkages. Specific efforts should be undertaken in the following areas to build the capacity of rural energy institutions: 1. Deepen research into the national energy development strategy Governments and related agencies at all levels should deepen their understanding of the strategic position of rural energy. This needs to be followed by the formulation of a rural energy development plan, in accordance with local conditions. Efforts should be made to make the rural energy development plan a part of the national energy development plan. This plan should then be listed in the finance budget at all levels. 2. Promote harmony among energy-integrated administrative departments Rural energy development is based on national energy management and has a close association with other energy management agencies, especially rural renewable energy development. Other efforts that need to be explored are: a. enhancing synergy among the national energy-integrated management agencies; b. managing conflicts between monopolization and competition in the energy industry; and c. the unfair distribution of energy benefits through reorganization and merging within the energy industry. MEETING THE CHALLENGES T Synergize energy development strategies with poverty reduction. 22 Energy and Poverty in China MEETING THE CHALLENGES 3. Strengthen networking, partnerships and international cooperation Energy management departments and agencies should organize energy- based enterprises to participate in academic activities, support related research, and promote cooperation with the Government and other strategic partners. 4. Monitor and evaluate national and rural energy development processes To measure the implementation of sustainable development, an indicator system should be set up. On the one hand, it could be used to monitor and evaluate development levels, trends and the speed of all aspects in a certain period. On the other hand, it could be used to measure the degree of harmony for all integrated fields. The system would help the Government to master the necessary information so as to decide the priority level of rural energy development processes. Promoting policy and regulations for equitable access to modern energy services Policies and regulations not only guide rural energy development; their formulation is also important for the proper functioning of the rural energy market. The affordability barrier that blocks rural poor from electricity services can be bridged \u2013 to a", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "322b31ae-c789-4caa-bdba-9c13721ef932": {"__data__": {"id_": "322b31ae-c789-4caa-bdba-9c13721ef932", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-china", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in China", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-china", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "97c21e7be33e8aee6ef7aa7d614656fa06ca44c1e228f4accd2c69ab817ba855"}}, "hash": "97c21e7be33e8aee6ef7aa7d614656fa06ca44c1e228f4accd2c69ab817ba855", "text": "large extent \u2013 by restructuring existing electricity service networks. The SERC, in its role as the apex electricity tariff supervisor, is best placed to initiate such a restructuring exercise, with the final objective being to infuse a pro-poor tariff regime within service networks. The cost barrier to electricity access, acute in remote areas, can also be resolved by aggressively pushing independent community electricity networks (powered by locally available renewable fuels such as biomass, solar, wind, and so on). Such off-grid interventions would require the marshalling of research and development skills by the MoST and other technology-focused institutions. At the same time, ground-level implementation and monitoring can be assigned to local governance bodies and community groups. Additionally, given that most of the rural energy service systems are located in developed areas (such as eastern and central China) and that the western areas are facing the difficulties of deficient energy service systems, the cooperation and exchange between eastern and western areas should be promoted. The provinces and counties with sound rural energy capacities, energy construction projects, and enterprises with good Cooperation and exchange between eastern and western areas should be promoted. 23 Energy and Poverty in China MEETING THE CHALLENGES practice on energy production and services should conduct technology exchange and training, and establish cooperative enterprises. At the national level, China could take many steps to reduce regional imbalances in modern energy access and alleviate poverty through: a. integrating poverty reduction goals into energy sector planning and focusing on policies that address the energy needs of rural poor; b. developing integrated and holistic rural energy strategies and programmes; c. establishing financing mechanisms and frameworks at all levels with a focus on microfinance and approaches that support local energy service companies; and d. building local capacity through community-based organizations. Approaches to an effective rural energy programme framework From a policy standpoint, the Government\u2019s rural energy programmes should approach rural energy concerns directly from the local level, building capacity through community-based organizations and enhancing participation. Local governance bodies in provinces and counties could expand their roles in the energy programme framework by initiating energy demand surveys and need analyses among rural households. Such an approach would include energy-related concerns of the poorest sections of rural society, and also the unique challenges faced by women in energy access and use. It could also be useful to draw lessons learned from the programmes and projects supported by international organizations such as UNDP, the World Bank and Asian Development Bank (ADB). These organizations supported China in implementing renewable energy projects, in terms of policy development and capacity-building. Many pilot projects were also established for demonstration. Such programmes emphasized how to overcome obstacles relating to policy, technology, market concerns and financing. These programmes have been more likely to produce effective results than programmes which do not consider removing these obstacles. Greater technology intervention for energy efficiency Considering that poor populations cannot afford commercial energy and electrical services due to their low-income level, indigenous energy resources should be popularized and utilized efficiently. Local governance bodies could initiate energy demand surveys and need analyses among rural households. 24 Energy and Poverty in China MEETING THE CHALLENGES As mentioned earlier, IAP claims numerous lives in China. For this reason, improved domestic energy technologies need greater attention in rural energy development strategies. Fuel-saving stoves are beneficial for rural areas and have a wide potential for use. Having already facilitated some degree of efficiency improvements \u2013 achieved with various cook stove designs \u2013 China needs further innovations to cut costs and increase their popularity. The Chinese Government should delegate lead roles in both cost reduction and popularization to institutions such as the National Integrated Rural Energy Programme Leading Group and the MoA\u2019s Energy-saving Appliances Quality Inspection Centre. The Women\u2019s Federation could also play an important role in disseminating knowledge on IAP, with the goal of raising awareness on the dangers of inefficient combustion in houses, and thus raising the demand for new energy technologies. As biogas technology evolves, technology service providers have the ability to design and implement all stages of the projects including pre-process, anaerobic digestion, biogas distribution, fertilizer making and after-treatment of digestive fluid. The biogas technology can be designed according to the types of waste, such as agricultural, livestock, landfill and mixed waste. This 'fuel' is fed into an anaerobic digester to produce biogas. One benefit is that biogas tanks serve as purification devices for waste water. This particularly fits the needs of small- to medium-size cities and population-concentrated villages and towns without a big waste water treatment facility. Such tanks are built under- ground and can gain", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "25f40618-8345-46b4-9776-bdb6bfd08312": {"__data__": {"id_": "25f40618-8345-46b4-9776-bdb6bfd08312", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-china", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in China", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-china", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "609a5ee95250c07c531bf0e70aecba5bc6ce729c43fd1e3e59d232d047dc9830"}}, "hash": "609a5ee95250c07c531bf0e70aecba5bc6ce729c43fd1e3e59d232d047dc9830", "text": "wide application due to low costs and the simplicity of management and maintenance. More efforts should be made to popularize existing mature and advanced energy-saving technologies in high-energy consumption enterprises among RSMEs in China. To engender energy efficiency in RSMEs, the technology input must be complemented by a strong policy framework that encourages and rewards the efficient use of energy. This could include the extension of the two management methods currently being tested on a pilot scale to RSMEs in China (Energy-saving Voluntary Agreement and Contract-binding Energy Management) and ensuring RSME participation in technical upgrades and training projects. Incentives to rural energy entrepreneurs Having facilitated the emergence of rural, energy-based entrepreneurship, China must now focus on facilitating access to technology, training and finance for rural energy enterprises. This can be achieved by coordinated action from relevant institutions, such as the NDRC, MoST, MoF, and China needs further innovation to cut costs and increase popularity of improved energy technologies. 25 Energy and Poverty in China MEETING THE CHALLENGES industry associations, such as the China Rural Energy Association and China Biogas Association. On the policy front, standardized rules and policies must be implemented to facilitate easier private participation in the rural energy sector. An incentive regime \u2013 comprising targeted subsidies, tax incentives and favourable loan policies \u2013 can also be developed by relevant agencies to encourage private energy entrepreneurship in remote areas. Such incentives are already put in place by provincial governments to spur renewable energy development. For example, Inner Mongolia and Xinjiang provinces are exempted from tax for renewable energy enterprises. Sichuan and Guangzhou provinces offer preferential pricing on cement for building biogas tanks at the factory price. Such incentive models can be studied and replicated by all provincial governments. A diversified financing system for rural China In order to improve the financing capacity of rural energy construction, the following measures should be taken: \u2022 Provide fiscal discounting and encourage credit cooperatives to supply micro loans for small energy projects, especially in remote villages, in order to solve the shortage of farmers\u2019 auxiliary funds in energy construction. \u2022 Clarify the property rights of communities\u2019 energy establishments and improve the management. \u2022 Encourage the participation of private enterprises and cooperation between the Government and enterprises so as to facilitate enterprise development and industrialization. Measures to improve supply and efficiency include: a. commercialized operations and management; b. regular competition between private enterprises in the process of construction and operation; and c. participation of users and the public in planning, construction and supervision of the establishments. \u2022 Establish security funds for the construction of energy establishments to encourage financial institutions to provide loans for rural energy projects. \u2022 Extend pilots undertaken for generating demand for the incentives and schemes. \u2022 Provide training to improve the financing capacity of farmers and the whole community. \u2022 Create greater awareness among the banks on potential renewable energy options and financing needs. 26 Energy and Poverty in China MEETING THE CHALLENGES \u2022 Document and disseminate information on profitability of rural enterprises and rural energy enterprises. \u2022 Charge the usage of rural energy establishments. For example, some local governments take protective price measures. Shanghai set a relatively high price for the civil cooking use of biogas as to RMB 1.2 per cubic metre. Such wide-ranging changes would require the involvement of the NDRC, with inputs and assistance from MoC, MoF and provincial governments. Mainstreaming gender concerns in energy-poverty linkages Increasing energy utilization efficiency and improving the indoor environment of rural households \u2013 and thus improving women\u2019s health conditions \u2013 requires the development of energy-saving technologies. Greater effort needs to be made to replace or modify the remaining rural traditional stoves and kitchen ranges. The Central Government should draft a nationwide plan to replace and renovate traditional stoves and kitchen ranges, especially in low-income regions. The construction of the whole rural energy system should be enhanced. Renewable energy technologies should be further developed and utilized. This should be done with consideration to local conditions, participatory approaches, complementary utilization of different energies, combined use of fuels and actual benefits. Any energy initiative for poverty reduction needs to also be seen from the lens of gender. Mechanisms and systems should be evolved for ensuring that gender issues are incorporated into the plan of action and energy programme framework. Awareness-raising and capacity-building on gender tools among policy makers could be highly beneficial. The Women\u2019s Federation at various levels should be involved in information dissemination regarding IAP caused by biomass smoke and about renewable energy technologies in general. Developing an energy-poverty framework for monitoring and evaluation Rural energy programmes need to promote", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "56003619-cc55-47e4-a3f0-35a1f35a0962": {"__data__": {"id_": "56003619-cc55-47e4-a3f0-35a1f35a0962", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-china", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in China", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-china", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "b8c251d256624db3d6ddac9706c359903e14aee873a37fdf6bbb664620525d07"}}, "hash": "b8c251d256624db3d6ddac9706c359903e14aee873a37fdf6bbb664620525d07", "text": "poverty reduction more effectively in the future. For this to happen, the energy-poverty indicators should be developed while the existing monitoring standards and criteria are enhanced. This would involve setting up a baseline data bank of M&E for rural energy projects along with adequate awareness and training for local government partners. This new energy-poverty M&E system can be jointly developed by the NBS; the Science, Technology, and Education 27 Energy and Poverty in China MEETING THE CHALLENGES Department of the MoA; and the Technology Development Centre for Energy and Environmental Protection. An information management system for the energy sector The absence of an energy information management system has hindered the effectiveness of China\u2019s rural energy development programmes. It is, therefore, urgent for China to establish a nationwide energy information system through an energy information engineering project. This project should be led by a relevant, competent agency (for instance, the NBS) and could be applied in two phases. The first phase could focus on the establishment of the information system, while the second phase could enable the development of an information resource network at the national, provincial and local levels. Such a system could funnel information into the system. A special focus on generating energy-poverty information is required. For example, the project could address issues such as the percentage of income spent by poor households on energy services, or the acceptable cost of off-grid electricity for the rural poor. The national rural energy information database should be the core of the information exchange on national rural energy. This could be the basis of national rural energy information collection and could make data processing timely, effective and accurate. It could also form the reference point for national rural energy policy formulation and strategic rural energy planning. According to the current Chinese rural energy management system, the national rural energy database should include information from national enterprises, regional enterprises, sectoral enterprises and major energy enterprises. nergy has a deep impact on the nation\u2019s economic development, security concerns and environment. Improved rural energy services can enhance living standards and create a healthier living environment through the application of solar, biogas and energy-saving technologies. Rural energy systems need to be developed to alleviate poverty and improve the role of women in rural development. Some countermeasures in this direction could be enabling policies, capacity- building, increase in investments, strengthening information access and disclosure, promoting technology innovation for the rural energy development, and conducting more research on energy and poverty alleviation. E CONCLUSION A special focus on generating energy- poverty information is required. 28 SCHEMATIC REPRESENTATION OF CHALLENGES AND MODALITIES TO MEET THE CHALLENGES THE CHALLENGES MEETING THE CHALLENGES Integration of local concerns, participation and needs, including information sharing and feedback mechanisms, are not adequately ensured in the existing top-down rural energy programme framework Inadequate attention to rural policy and implementation barriers during the programme formulation stage Adequate policy attention has not been paid to mechanisms that would make energy services affordable to the poor Regional imbalances in modern energy access due to unfavourable economies of scale in the rural areas Cost barrier remains acute in remote areas Policy and Regulatory Framework Programme Concerns Local level institutional capacities are weak Ineffective mechanisms for coordinating energy