finance RSMEs experience barriers to the promotion of energy efficiency due to lack of accessible information and capacity development Households with low incomes continue to use traditional cook stoves No standard operating rules or policies exist to guide non-state-owned enterprises wishing to enter the energy industry Access Issues Commercial financial institutions prefer to stay away from rural financial markets and focus on the more profitable urban markets; only limited market-oriented schemes for energy projects are available to RSMEs, thus rural energy construction remains overdependent on government subsidies Due to policy limitations, development of rural cooperative financing (especially micro-credit) is difficult, resulting in the growth of informal finance, which, in turn, increases the financial risks of borrowers Financing Concerns Improved domestic energy technologies need greater attention in rural energy development strategies Further innovations needed with regards to improved cook stoves in order to cut costs and increase popularity Delegate lead roles in both cost reduction and popularization to institutions such as the National Integrated Rural Energy Programme Leading Group and the MoA\u2019s Energy-saving Appliances Quality Inspection Centre More efforts should be made to popularize existing mature and advanced energy-saving technologies in high-energy consumption enterprises among RSMEs Technology input must be complemented by a strong policy framework that encourages and rewards the efficient use of energy Extend good pilot projects and ensure RSME participation in technical upgrades and training projects Further promote growing rural energy-based investment Facilitate access to technology, training and finance Involve relevant institutions such as NDRC, MoST, and MoF and industry associations such as CREA and China Biogas Association Implement standardized rules and policies to facilitate easier private participation in the rural energy sector Relevant agencies to further develop an incentive regime, comprising subsidies, tax incentives and favourable loan policies Existing incentive models can be studied and replicated by all provincial governments Establish a diversified financing and investment system, which includes security funds to enable financial institutions to extend loans for rural energy projects Encourage more commercialized and participatory project schemes; Extend pilots undertaken for generating demand for the incentives and schemes; Provide training to improve the financing capacity of farmers and the whole community Create greater awareness among the banks on potential renewable energy options and financing needs; Document and disseminate information on profitability of rural enterprises and rural energy enterprises The proposed financial mechanism should include the provision of fiscal discounts to solve fund shortage Support credit cooperatives to provide micro loans to small energy projects, especially in remote villages Involve NDRC to work closely with MoC, MoF and provincial governments 30 Energy and Poverty in China SCHEMATIC REPRESENTATION OF CHALLENGES AND MODALITIES TO MEET THE CHALLENGES (CONTINUED...) THE CHALLENGES MEETING THE CHALLENGES Gender Concerns Insufficient consideration is given to the poor and to women in energy management and development at the national level (e.g. the use of inefficient energy technology by women in rural households persists) Women and gender issues are insufficiently represented in the energy programme framework (e.g. limited involvement of women in new energy technology extension programmes) The baseline data bank of M&E for rural energy projects is not well established, and indicators for energy and poverty are missing The energy sector lacks an integrated information management system; In some cases, there are no leading organizations to coordinate information collection and processing, and information is mainly government controlled an