Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in Malaysia", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-malaysia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "9c80ca6a0cdcdd3c4a2e9b5e3d2b5269f296629d3ee4ad0ec8986115693e6f6e"}}, "hash": "9c80ca6a0cdcdd3c4a2e9b5e3d2b5269f296629d3ee4ad0ec8986115693e6f6e", "text": "challenges in meeting the needs of the poor. Malaysia is ranked among the most developed and industrialized countries in the Asia-Pacific region. As a result of robust economic growth and substantial wealth redistribution policies, the country has witnessed significant poverty reduction over the past few decades. The country has extensive electricity coverage, including rural areas. Ninety-five percent of the rural population is served through the grid. Even the more isolated areas are serviced through diesel generators, solar, and mini-hydro sources. Nonetheless, these gains have not been matched by the provision of cleaner sources of energy for heating and cooking, especially in the remote areas of Sabah and Sarawak. This study examines critical energy access issues in Malaysia, especially in pockets of unserved or underserved sections, including the institutional structure of the energy sector, policy and regulatory frameworks, and sectoral programmes. It analyses reasons for the narrow reach of energy services to some rural communities, dependence on traditional fuels and inefficient technologies, the restricted supply of energy by rural energy enterprises and inadequate means of financing for energy. Gender concerns are also examined in rural energy projects and programmes. The report highlights the urgent need for key data and indicators to support monitoring and evaluation of energy access for areas that are least served and maintain sustained political commitment to sound energy sector management at national, sub-national and local levels. Malaysia has a well-established institutional structure working towards the targeted provision of energy services for poor communities viii Energy and Poverty in Malaysia THE CHALLENGES countries. Subsequently, UNDP country offices held national-level stakeholder consultations to chart the implementation of the assessments, guide the process and validate the findings and recommendations of the assessments. This work benefited immensely from the support of government officials and representatives of the civil society. The work has since been documented as country reports, which currently serve as resource and reference material for partners in country- level programming and planning for advancing access to modern energy services for the unserved and, in particular, the poor. This report is a summary of the original elaborate Country Report on Malaysia and is part of a series of REP-PoR\u2019s Asia-Pacific publications. It draws on the key findings of the Country Report and summarizes the challenges faced at the national level, and provides priority recommendations. Specifically, critical issues related to institutional structure, policy and regulatory frameworks, programmes, financing measures, gender concerns, as well as monitoring and evaluation support are emphasized. In particular, an attempt has been made to present Malaysia country-specific energy access challenges and way forward diagrammatically in the form of a flow chart to enable the reader a macro view of the issues and options. As an advocacy tool, it is felt that this summary report will be of relevance to national policy makers, development partners, energy service providers, civil society organizations and other interested persons, including the academia, in preparing and implementing various measures to promote access to modern energy services for the poor and the unserved to support national efforts in poverty reduction. and in meeting the MDGs. Hence, the Government has been reasonably successful in bringing together fragmented energy markets, and removing barriers to efficient functioning of existing and new markets at national and sub-national levels. Central oversight of energy services for poor people not only has implications towards more efficient and cost- effective use of energy, but also serves to address issues of environmental and health hazards. Concurrently, this central coordinating mechanism has been often successful in addressing market failures, and bridging gaps in areas where markets are absent. These include addressing issues of providing energy services in challenging, remote and sparsely populated geographical areas. The report revealed that despite the unambiguous benefits arising from the centralized institutional structure, there remain several challenges that could be addressed for further improved and sustained energy access. As of date, there is limited private sector participation in rural electrification and energy entrepreneurship, especially SMEs (small and medium enterprises), micro-enterprises and local entrepreneurs in rural areas. This is further weakened by the lack of community-based self- help systems. Extensive efforts in the provision of grid-supplied energy have been complemented by attempts to harness renewable energy sources but remain sparse. While renewable energy sources are particularly cost-effective in many rural areas of the country where vast quantities of biomass sources are available, they need to be upscaled by addressing the barriers that limit their spread. The provision of affordable modern energy for cooking in remote rural areas remains a challenge. The commitment of the Government of Malaysia to achieve total electrification by 2020, including in the remote areas", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{m