gy sector, it would also offer diversification in energy resource mix for the country. The Government\u2019s commitment to rural electrification also needs to be complemented by a programme to deliver affordable modern cooking fuel to remote communities. In addition, major indicators that incorporate rural energy figures in terms of access, poverty and gender ix Energy and Poverty in Malaysia THE CHALLENGES concerns should be established and closely monitored. Continuous assessment of various programmes is crucial to achieve the targeted goal of poverty reduction, especially in Sabah and Sarawak. We trust that the report is unique in terms of giving insights into bridging the gaps between the access to energy and poverty reduction efforts in Malaysia. Our aim is to provide country-specific information on institutional structures, energy resources, policy recommendations and capacity and financial gaps that can point the way towards improving access to modern energy services, particularly for the poor. Nandita Mongia Regional Programme Coordinator and Team Leader Regional Energy Programme for Poverty Reduction UNDP Regional Centre in Bangkok xi Energy and Poverty in Malaysia Energy and Poverty in Malaysia: Challenges and the Way Forward is the result of a partnership initiative of the United Nations Development Programme (UNDP) Asia-Pacific Regional Energy Programme for Poverty Reduction (REP-PoR). It benefits from collaboration between the UNDP Regional Centre in Bangkok (RCB), UNDP-Malaysia Country Office, key national stakeholders and regional experts. This report is the third in the series of nine country reports for Asia and a synthesis report on similar lines for the Pacific island countries. Like any multi-stakeholder work, this report reflects the efforts of many people over last two years. We express our appreciation for the inputs, suggestions and support provided by them. We appreciate the excellent support of the energy and environment cluster and the human development cluster of UNDP Malaysia, who participated in the process of the gap assessment and the preparation of the original country report. In addition to providing critical data and information to complete this report, the UNDP Country Office focal point in Malaysia, Asfaazam Kasbani, provided consistent support by undertaking many rounds of review and comments. We would like to acknowledge the national experts Chamhuri Siwar and Norasikin Ludin, who were responsible for preparing the original country report and going the extra mile in capturing, consolidating and processing all the inputs gathered from an elaborate country consultative process. Ibrahim Hafeezur Rehman provided overall technical support and guidance during the preparation of this report to the country team. We convey our gratitude to key officials of Economic Planning Unit (EPU), Ministry of Energy, Water and Communications (MEWC), Ministry of Rural and Regional Development (MRRD), Department of Statistics (DoS), Energy Commission (EC), Pusat Tenaga Malaysia (PTM), Universiti Kebangsaan Malaysia (UKM), Ministry of Education (MoE), Ministry of Health (MoH), Sabah State Government, Sarawak State Government, Jabatan Kerja Raya (JKR) and Tenaga Nasional Berhad (TNB) for their expert reviews and comments at the national consultations of the gap assessment that preceded the preparation of this report. The analytical structure and conceptualization of the gap assessment report went through many rounds of reviews and revisions by the core ACKNOWLEDGEMENTS xii Energy and Poverty in Malaysia REP-PoR team in RCB, comprising Nandita Mongia, Thiyagarajan Velumail, Thomas Jensen and Bhava Dhungana, during the last two years. We appreciate the inputs from Kamal Rijal, K S Kannan, Abu Sadat Moniruzzam Khan, Sooksiri Chamsuk and Sanna Salmela-Eckstein, who contributed at different stages while the country report was being finalized. We appreciate and acknowledge TERI Press for designing and editing this repo