lion in 1970 to 219,700 in 2004 (EPU 2006). Economic", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "10b3afe7-6bf3-413a-91d9-76afeb53cf45": {"__data__": {"id_": "10b3afe7-6bf3-413a-91d9-76afeb53cf45", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-malaysia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in Malaysia", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-malaysia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "f5f901be9f01c77910ad3f70dc96d4c46704b9f2bce465ce80c21a457402ba88"}, "3": {"node_id": "69c002e9-5acd-455c-b52e-736d828a5400", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-malaysia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "d092b12ba1e345b642afbe416dc2ae1b07334bc6044d4396f6164cd42b49c01d"}}, "hash": "1ae6846203b56057ef7443607eacea545a4f0eb7f14d2b1002e9a3e92f704bd1", "text": "growth from, and wealth redistribution strategies of, the New Economic Policy (1971\u20131990), the National Development Policy (1991\u20132000) and the National Vision Policy (2001\u20132020) have led to a reduction in poverty levels. The Development Programme for the Hardcore Poor, which focuses on economic, social, human and physical development, and the micro-credit scheme for women from the lower-income groups have facilitated their access to employment and improved livelihoods. The energy sector witnessed considerable growth in demand, almost parallel to the country\u2019s economic growth. The growth in electricity demand was the highest from the industrial sector (10.7 percent), followed by the residential sector (8.4 percent) and the commercial sector (7.9 percent). As Malaysia became more industrialized and urbanized, electricity rapidly became the main source of energy, with the industrial sector being its largest consumer. There was a positive correlation between the growth rates in annual gross domestic product (GDP) and final energy demand between 1980 and 2002, as shown in Figure 1. The drop in final energy demand between 1995 and 2000 was caused by the Asian economic crisis that affected many Asian countries in 1997. Rural and suburban areas in Malaysia are served by the electricity grid and receive adequate (almost 95 percent) electricity supply. The isolated areas, where the grid does not reach, obtain their supply mostly through the Government support in the form of diesel generators and solar and mini-hydro sources. The Malaysian rural electrification experience has demonstrated that as electrification expands its reach, poverty levels tend to decrease, as shown in Figure 2. Energy access and poverty reduction are, therefore, correlated significantly. In addition to other Government programmes, the rural electrification programme has significantly contributed to this positive impact. However, gains in electricity use have not been matched by the provision of cleaner energy sources for cooking and heating. Fuelwood BACKGROUND There is a significant correlation between access to energy and poverty reduction. 3 Energy and Poverty in Malaysia THE CHALLENGES remains the primary source of energy for heating and cooking in some parts of the rural areas. Despite the reduction in consumption levels from 85 percent in 1950 to 28 percent in 2004, communities in remote areas in the states of Sabah and Sarawak still largely rely on inefficient energy sources, such as fuelwood and kerosene. This issue is closely linked to poverty and poses an enormous challenge to poverty reduction initiatives in Malaysia. This report examines the challenges in harmonizing the energy sector policies with poverty reduction goals in Malaysia. FIGURE 1 ANNUAL GROWTH RATES OF GROSS DOMESTIC PRODUCT AND FINAL ENERGY DEMAND Source DoS (2004) BACKGROUND FIGURE 2 INVERSE RELATIONSHIP BETWEEN POVERTY REDUCTION AND RURAL ELECTRIFICATION, MALAYSIA, 1985\u20132000 Source DoS (2004) 4 Energy and Poverty in Malaysia THE CHALLENGES Malaysia Energy Balance 2004 The following is the energy balance for 2004, as reported in the National Energy Balance 2004 (MEWC 2005). Supply of commercial energy In 2004, the primary supply of commercial energy grew only by 1.9 percent, as compared to a 7.5 percent increase during the previous year. The growth took place because of higher production of natural gas at 57,768 kilotonnes of oil equivalent (ktoe), an increase of 9 percent from 53,010 ktoe in 2003. At a lesser rate, the production of crude oil increased by a narrow margin of 2.7 percent from 37,026 ktoe in 2003 to 38,041 ktoe in 2004. Despite a smaller margin in production, import of petroleum products registered a positive growth of 26.2 percent. The production of coal in 2004 increased by more than 100 percent, but minimal in quantum as compared to other fossil fuels. Import of coal has consistently increased at an annual rate of 50 percent since 2002. Coal import increased by 52.2 percent, from 5,268 ktoe in 2003 to 8,019 ktoe in 2004. Since the commencement of PETRONAS\u2019s (the national petroleum corporation) third liquefied natural gas (LNG) plant in Bintulu in March 2003, conversion of natural gas to LNG has continuously increased. A total of 22,944 ktoe of LNG was produced in 2004, as compared to 18,965 ktoe in 2003, registering an increase of 21 percent. The total output of refineries also increased, albeit by 1.9 percent in 2004, due to increase in the production of diesel, motor petrol and fuel oil.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "69c002e9-5acd-455c-b52e-736d828a5400": {"__data__": {"id_": "69c002e9-5acd-455c-b52e-736d828a5400", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-malaysia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in Malaysia", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-malaysia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "f5f901be9f01c77910ad3f70dc96d4c46704b9f2bce465ce80c21a457402ba88"}, "2": {"node_id": "10b3afe7-6bf3-413a-91d9-76afeb53cf45", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-malaysia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "1ae6846203b56057ef7443607eacea545a4f0eb7f14d2b1002e9a3e92f704bd1"}}, "hash": "d092b12ba1e345b642afbe416dc2ae1b07334bc6044d4396f6164cd42b49c01d", "text": "Final demand of commercial energy In 2004, the final energy demand was recorded at 37,322 ktoe, an increase of 7.9 percent vis- -vis 3.9 percent in 2003. This was the result of increased demand from all sectors, especially transport and industry. The transport sector remains the leading consumer of final energy, accounting for 41.2 percent, after witnessing an increased growth of", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}"