4. The incidence of poverty reduced between 1970 and 2004. THE CHALLENGES Centralized institutional structure for rural energy development M alaysia has a matured institutional set-up in the energy industries, covering the oil and gas sector to the electricity segment. The Economic Planning Unit (EPU) has the overarching responsibility towards energy policy and planning, both for conventional and non-conventional sources of energy, and poverty 6 Energy and Poverty in Malaysia THE CHALLENGES reduction in Malaysia. The Ministry of Rural and Regional Development (MRRD) and the Ministry of Energy, Water and Communications (MEWC) work in close coordination for the rural electrification programme. In addition, MEWC works in tandem with the Energy Commission (EC) and Pusat Tenaga Malaysia (PTM \u2013 the Malaysian Energy Centre) to coordinate national programmes in energy efficiency and renewable energy. Due to sharp increase in international oil prices, the Ministry of Plantation, Industries and Commodities had launched a drive towards the development of palm bio-diesel1 as a source of renewable energy. Malaysia\u2019s power system \u2013 generation, transmission and distribution \u2013 had historically been a Government responsibility. However, the heavy costs incurred in constructing power plants prompted the entry of the private sector into electricity generation. The Electricity Supply Act (1990) enabled licensed independent power producers (IPPs) to build their own generation plants and sell power to utility companies, under regulation of the then Department of Electricity Supply, now known as the EC. MEWC regularly monitors and reviews the supply and demand situation, and makes recommendations to the Government on issues such as plant requirements, tariff reviews and supply\u2013demand requirements.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__ty