E ELECTRICITY SECTOR has established a number of ministries, departments and agencies to undertake various social development functions and sub-functions. The Government institutions that coordinate poverty reduction and rural development programmes have energy as a component in their respective mandates. Within the area of rural energy development, although there exist state and local authorities, it is mostly implemented centrally through the federal government. The primary responsibility of determining, initiating and implementing rural development programmes lies with MRRD, which is also responsible for rural electrification. Where grid extensions are not feasible, MRRD uses options like solar photovoltaic (PV) systems. 8 Energy and Poverty in Malaysia THE CHALLENGES Policy and regulatory framework Malaysia is well endowed with energy resources such as petroleum, natural gas, hydro and coal. Its energy policy can be traced to the formulation of the Petroleum Development Act (1974), which paved the way for the establishment of PETRONAS and its exclusive rights of ownership for exploration and production of oil and gas resources. The Energy Policy of 1979, the National Depletion Policy of 1980, the Four Fuel Diversification Policy of 1981 and the Fifth Fuel Policy of 2001 reveal the Government\u2019s intention of sustainable development of energy. The National Energy Policy contains three guiding principles for the energy sector. 1 To ensure adequate, secure and cost-effective energy supply through the development and utilization of alternative sources of energy, including non-renewable and renewable ones 2 To promote efficient utilization of energy and discourage wasteful and non-productive patterns of energy consumption 3 To minimize the negative environmental impacts of the energy supply chain, that is, energy production, transportation, conversion and utilization. The National Depletion Policy, incorporated into the National Petroleum Policy, is aimed at safeguarding national oil and gas reserves by ensuring a control mechanism in production at major oil fields. The Four Fuel Diversification Policy complements the National Depletion Policy as it aims to create a supply mix of oil, gas, large-sized hydropower and coal to reduce the nation\u2019s heavy dependence on oil, particularly in the power sector. In 2001, the Four Fuel Policy was expanded to include renewable energy as the fifth fuel option in the power generation mix. BOX 1: KEY INSTITUTIONAL CHALLENGES Malaysia has a fairly good institutional structure in place to coordinate various activities related to poverty reduction and rural electrification. However, it would further strengthen the existing institutional structure if the following two specific gaps are taken care of. P Community-based self-help systems are missing. P Private-sector participation in rural electrification is limited, except for a few private diesel generators and solar vendors in the rural areas, as well as contractors of centrally planned programmes. Policies in the energy sector reveal the Government\u2019s intention of sustainable development of energy. 9 Energy and Poverty in Malaysia THE CHALLENGES It is the responsibility of MRRD to determine and initiate appropriate policies and implement rural development programmes. These functions involve basic utilities such as road infrastructure, water and rural energy services. The Ministry\u2019s initiatives include the development of mini hydro plants and the provision of electricity through solar PV systems, where grid-connected supply cannot be extended at reasonable rates. Supporting rural electrification programmes, MRRD plays an important role in identifying rural areas as beneficiaries of the solar home system and the diesel generator and grid-line projects. The Ministry is also responsible for activities such as carrying out maintenance works at sites throughout Malaysia, providing solar equipment, conducting technical visits to the maintenance sites, coordinating the maintenance for solar equipment and so on. During the Ninth Plan period (2006\u20132010), greater emphasis will be placed towards balanced regional development. This will be done through further diversification of the economic base of each of the states", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "a7a64693-18b9-415a-becb-a0bf1ab71faa": {"__data__": {"id_": "a7a64693-18b9-415a-becb-a0bf1ab71faa", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-malaysia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in Malaysia", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-malaysia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "8094481292ae9d39d7b456f9c9bebf661a4303b71971a1efa58e43373b2ca6a2"}, "3": {"node_id": "7a72cb0e-7877-4255-b5ed-852f299fbc35", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-malaysia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "9bafa4854a388104b401ef6259b950443b421ff5b15da7053cfa185e818214fb"}}, "hash": "7ab266ef16ece5524a0aced5447eab479c9f2fa3be653237023be08095d2bba0", "text": "in Malaysia to attract more investment, create more job opportunities and generate higher income. The main objective of this will be to narrow development gaps between regions and states, as well as between rural and urban areas. Measures will be undertaken to reduce disparities in terms of per capita income and household income, incidence of poverty in less-developed states. Further, disparities of infrastructure and utilities between the states in Peninsular Malaysia and between the Peninsular, Sabah and Sarawak will also be reduced. The total development allocation for rural development projects for the Ninth Malaysia Plan is 28.4 billion ringgit2 (EPU 2006). The Government is committed towards total rural electrification and this gets reflected in its programme initiatives and development budget allocations, as part of the country\u2019s five-year national development plans (Malaysia Plans). Under this strategy, electricity supply options for the rural population are determined by MRRD, together with the power utilities. Rural electrification continues to be identified as one of the key components of the country\u2019s rural development and welfare programmes. It is promoted as part of an integrated approach to rural development planning and programme developments (including water, telecommunications and roads supply) and recognized as a vital element in the drive towards poverty reduction. The five-year Malaysia (development) plans allocate substantial funding to rural electrification, with funds ranging from 3.78 million ringgit for the First Five-Year Plan to 275 million ringgit for the Ninth Five-Year Plan (EPU 2006). Rural electrification is a key component of the country\u2019s rural development and welfare programmes. 2 Conversion rate: US $1 = 3.7 ringgit 10 Energy and Poverty in Malaysia THE CHALLENGES The rural electrification programme is aimed at supplying electricity to homes and villages, which are beyond the operational areas of the local authorities, including the orang asli (indigenous communities). Rural electrification forms part of efforts to provide social amenities to enhance the quality of life and living standards among the rural communities. Since the 1970s, rural electrification has been incorporated in the New Economic Policy framework to eradicate poverty and increase the quality of life in rural areas, especially that of the rural poor. The increasing use of electricity is expected to raise productivity and income in the agriculture, industry and commercial sectors, as also affect modernization and cause attitudinal change in the rural sector. In the Ninth Malaysia Plan (2006\u20132010), the implementation of the rural electrification programme will be intensified to improve the quality of life of rural communities, especially in Sabah and Sarawak. Towards this end, about 54,680 housing units will be supplied with electricity through the solar hybrid and micro-hydro systems. A larger portion of the Malaysian Electricity Supply Industry Trust Account (MESITA) allocations will be utilized in the implementation of these programmes. By the end of the Plan period, rural electricity coverage (as a percentage of total rural housing units) in Sabah and Sarawak is expected to increase to 80.6 percent (from 72.8 percent in 2005) and 89.6 percent (from 80.8 percent in 2005), respectively. For Malaysia, the national rural electrification coverage will increase from 92.9 percent in 2005 to 95.1 percent in 2010 (EPU 2006). Grid extension has always been accorded priority, especially due to its low costs and established infrastructure. Other decentralized energy systems \u2013 such as diesel generator sets, solar home and solar hybrid systems \u2013 are implemented for use in remote areas that are not serviced by grids. More than 5,000 villages have benefited from the programme since it was first initiated in 1998. However, the long-term plan of the Government is to extend grids, wherever economically viable. MESITA was formally established on 1 January 1997, under a Trust Deed issued by the Ministry of Finance (MoF). Major independent power producers, including the Tenaga Nasional Berhad (Generation), which sells electricity to the Peninsular Grid, make annual contributions to the Trust Account to fulfil their national obligation towards electricity supply in the country. The rate agreed by the contributors is pegged at one percent of the total audited annual turnover of the previous year. The total contributions made up to 2002 amounted to 365.5 million ringgit. Projects allowed under the MESITA Trust Deed comprise rural electrification programmes; research and development (R&D) Rural electricity coverage is expected to increase substantially by 2010.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "7a72cb0e-7877-4255-b5ed-852f299fbc35": {"__data__": {"id_": "7a72cb0e-7877-4255-b5ed-852f299fbc35", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-malaysia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in Malaysia", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-malaysia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "8094481292ae9d39d7b456f9c9bebf661a4303b71971a1efa58e43373b2ca6a2"}, "2": {"node_id": "a7a64693-18b9-415a-becb-a0bf1ab71faa", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-malaysia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "7ab266ef16ece5524a0aced5447eab479c9f2fa3be653237023be08095d2bba0"}}, "hash": "9bafa4854a388104b401ef6259b950443b421ff5b15da7053cfa185e818214fb", "text": "11 Energy and Poverty in Malaysia THE CHALLENGES programme for the electricity industry such as development of new and renewable sources of energy; training and education for human resource development in the electricity sector; energy-efficiency programmes; and the promotion and development of the electricity supply industry. Over the years, a bulk of the allocated funds was meant for rural electrification projects.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "338aeb4f-eae3-41ce-91c3-1da2bad927c3": {"__data__": {"id_": "338aeb4f-eae3-41ce-91c3-1da2bad927c3", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-malaysia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in Malaysia", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-malaysia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "9871e23fbce4de26324a33442d0ff95260c3fd2e2712d3b7aba82cb82f344ae8"}, "3": {"node_id": "cc08e8a4-3e60-4194-a1f7-b64dc7b76450", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-malaysia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "c505b9b9aafac907b36e3f01af0550d4b8301b79519d9232ec5e24eec546436f"}}, "hash": "5fd6b941a9047346eee56a6993928087b564d08001db9951995697601f35acde", "text": "As of 2006, a sum of over 180 million ringgit has been disbursed through MESITA\u2019s rural electrification projects, benefiting over 40,000 households. MESITA, thus, managed to play a catalytic role in carrying out the development programme of the electricity supply industry on a sustainable basis. With strong rural development strategies comprising substantial funding \u2013 both from the Government and through MESITA \u2013 access to energy for the poor in Malaysia has improved. Meanwhile, domestic non-electricity energy resources are generally market-based and sold in many shops in the rural area. Access is further enhanced as a result of the strong, integrated rural development approach of the Government, which includes road access for rural communities. Fossil fuels such as gasoline (for transportation), liquefied petroleum gas or LPG (for cooking) and kerosene (for cooking and lighting) are widely sold even in un-electrified places, such as deep rural pockets of Sabah and Sarawak. The Government\u2019s decision to intensify the development and use of renewable energy as the fifth fuel resource is manifested by the country\u2019s fifth fuel diversification policy, related to renewable energy, energy efficiency and R&D. To encourage energy generation through renewable energy, the Government implemented many incentives, such as investment tax allowance, import duty exemption and sales tax exemption. The Government introduced the National Biofuel Policy in August 2005 to encourage the production and utilization of palm oil as an alternative environment-friendly fuel. MESITA\u2019s rural electrification projects benefited over 40,000 households. BOX 2: KEY CHALLENGES IN THE POLICY FRAMEWORK With concerted efforts backed by strong policy support and focus on the states of Sabah and Sarawak, Malaysia should achieve total electricity coverage by 2020. However, the following issues may thwart the progress. P Lack of strong support from the Government and utilities to implement the renewable energy policy. P Unavailability of mechanisms to encourage private developers to participate in rural electrification programmes. 12 Energy and Poverty in Malaysia THE CHALLENGES However, the implementation of the renewable energy policy has not shown significant progress. At the end of 2005, only 12 MW of biomass- generated electricity had been connected to the national grid. In 2002, Government launched the BioGen Project3 in the Malaysian palm oil industry. Funded by the United Nations Development Programme (UNDP) and Global Environment Facility (GEF), the project aims to remove barriers to facilitate wider implementation of Small Renewable Energy Project (SREP). This is so because most of the biomass energy projects are located in remote areas. Programme framework with varied strategies A programme framework with varied strategies makes the Malaysian experience a success story, as far as energy provision and poverty reduction are concerned. Rural electrification, the cornerstone of Malaysia\u2019s rural development programme, has seen accelerated growth since the First Malaya Development Plan (1956\u20131960) recognized it as a necessary component of the country\u2019s rural growth strategy. An integrated grid extension programme was adopted by Malaysia, with a major thrust on provision of 24-hour electricity to the target groups, along with 100 percent supply coverage for the whole country. In addition to grid-supplied electricity, Malaysia has attempted to harness the benefits of renewable energy (particularly, biomass energy) to provide electricity, especially to remote rural areas. Since this option is cost-effective and biomass energy sources are available in vast quantities, a gradual shift towards renewable energy sources would mean a higher rate of poverty reduction and a corresponding rise in living standards. The SREP scheme was launched by the Government in 2001 to integrate renewable energy into the country\u2019s energy sector. Two new renewable energy projects, located in Sabah (palm oil wastes) and Selangor (landfill wastes), were commissioned in 2004 (EPU 2006). However, the implementation of the SREP scheme has been hampered by the low tariff offered by the utility and high capital investment costs. The Government will also need to introduce a more conducive environment by initiating measures for a more level playing field for renewable energy resources. The highly subsidized natural gas, for example, has become the primary fuel for power generation in the country. The Solar Home System (SHS) Programme initiated in the early 1990s is geared towards supplying electricity to rural areas not connected to The implementation of the renewable energy policy has not shown significant progress. 3 Biomass Power Generation and Cogeneration using wastes from Palm Oil mills Demonstration Project 13 Energy and Poverty in Malaysia THE CHALLENGES High costs of PV systems hinder the expansion of SHS Programme.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "cc08e8a4-3e60-4194-a1f7-b64dc7b76450": {"__data__": {"id_": "cc08e8a4-3e60-4194-a1f7-b64dc7b76450", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-malaysia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in Malaysia", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-malaysia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "9871e23fbce4de26324a33442d0ff95260c3fd2e2712d3b7aba82cb82f344ae8"}, "2": {"node_id": "338aeb4f-eae3-41ce-91c3-1da2bad927c3", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-malaysia", "Author