stalled as well as provide skill-based training to maintain the systems. the grid. These areas, inhabited by indigenous communities, include villages in Peninsular Malaysia, Sabah and Sarawak. This development has led to a significant enhancement in educational levels and improvements in living standards in the target areas. Further expansion of the SHS Programme is, however, inhibited by the higher costs of PV systems, albeit these costs are expected to decrease in the near future. Moreover, problems of overuse of electricity and vandalism too have to be taken into account. Villagers are disappointed when electricity generated is below their expectation and leads to vandalism in various ways. Batteries are used for purposes other than those advocated and solar panels broken. The system has also failed due to its low maintenance. A systematic programme of building local capacity to maintain these systems and raising awareness of the functionality of SHS has clearly been lacking. Access to energy supply Electricity in Malaysia is mainly provided through the grid, and the Peninsular area is well connected to the grid. Almost all households in rural Peninsular Malaysia have access to electricity. There is limited access to the grid in the remote and mountainous terrains in Sabah and Sarawak\u201485 percent and 90 percent, respectively. Overall, most housing units in Malaysia (93.1 percent) have access to 24-hour electricity supply (DoS 2004). Since grid extension is uneconomical for scattered, low-density loads, most rural parts of Sabah and Sarawak are electrified by local diesel generating sets, SHSs and micro-hydropower systems. 14 Energy and Poverty in Malaysia THE CHALLENGES BOX 4: KEY CHALLENGES PERTAINING TO ENERGY ACCESS P Unfavourable geographical features hinder complete rural electrification in the states of Sabah and Sarawak, and remote orang asli villages in Peninsular Malaysia. P Since the population in Sabah and Sarawak is sparse and spread out, the market for electricity has been limited. Sabah and Sarawak make up a mere 20 percent of Malaysia\u2019s population. P Private developers have been reluctant to take up renewable energy programmes because of reasons such as lack of information and knowledge about the features and benefits of alternative forms of energy, high initial investment, lack of a level playing field against subsidized conventional fuels, lack of adequate fiscal incentives and the absence of standardized equipment and quality control. Rural electrification involves providing heavily subsidized grid extensions and isolated generators. In Sabah, 11.9 percent of households receive electricity supply for less than 24 hours a day, while 16.1 percent of households have no electricity at all. The situation is marginally better in Sarawak, where only 5.75 percent of the households are without electricity supply (DoS 2004). The Government is seeking to intensify the development of renewable energy, particularly biomass, as the \u2018fifth fuel\u2019 resource under the country\u2019s Fuel Diversification Policy. The policy has been reinforced by fiscal incentives such as investment tax allowances and SREP, which encourages the connection of small renewable power generation plants to the national grid. Yet another programme called the Solar Project aims to provide power supply to rural areas that are not connected to the grid especially orang asli villages. These villages are located far from the grid and pose logistical problems for diesel supply due to lack of adequate road access. SHS could easily meet the modest energy needs of average rural households, but not for productive uses. The supply of domestic petro-products in Malaysia is market-based. Gasoline, LPG and kerosene are widely available even in the isolated areas of Sabah and Sarawak, made possible by good road or river transport access. The penetration of petrol-genset has increased from 5 percent in 1960 to 40 percent in 2004; penetration of kerosene has reduced from 75 percent in 1960 to 10 percent in 2004, while the penetration of LPG has increased from 5 percent in 1970 to 70 percent in 2004. In Sabah, about 16 percent of households receive no electricity at all. 15 Energy and Poverty in Malaysia THE CHALLENGES Untapped potential for development of energy-efficient systems It is necessary to ensure that the available renewable energy systems operate with high efficiency for maximum output, bearing in mind the high initial costs. While there is a high level of thermal efficiency in", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "c7e4da57-63d0-4bcd-8c1a-d6ef129f7d70": {"__data__": {"id_": "c7e4da57-63d0-4bcd-8c1a-d6ef129f7d70", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-malaysia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in Malaysia", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-malaysia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "90c6ce187d4f790a8ce466a200e5fba8bc4d00dd3ca3600958ed8e5741409f9f"}, "3": {"node_id": "4bf434fa-91fd-45c4-af00-984e009718cf", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-malaysia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "65c1a5fe15629583342bb2e95412db4d199a465580e9770963d1a053375f24b0"}}, "hash": "9ed68f64600bab4c4b9679ea039ec7f23a77c59ccd4ec1814691b7123747c819", "tex