THE CHALLENGES Insufficient financial assistance for entrepreneurship in energy service delivery Numerous enterprises in rural areas, including rice and oil mills, weaving set-ups and handicraft establishments, use electricity for lighting and motive power. To support the use of modern energy in productive work, the Government has established funding opportunities for small and medium enterprises (SMEs). Loans obtained from these funds can be utilized to purchase farm equipment and machinery that run on electricity. Fish and agro-processing industries in rural areas are potential and actual beneficiaries of rural electrification. For instance, reliable electricity supply enables fishermen in coastal areas to keep their daily catch in freezers. Similarly, provision of electricity allows cottage industries to operate longer everyday, thus enhancing productivity and supplementing income. However, the impact of electrification on SMEs in rural areas has not been documented, making it difficult to identify specific gains in rural income generation resulting from modern energy provision. This is aggravated by the fact that the existing data framework does not identify SMEs by location. BOX 6: KEY CHALLENGES TO ENERGY ENTREPRENEURSHIP P Special funds set up by the Government to promote small and medium enterprises do not target entrepreneurs involved in energy service delivery, particularly in the productive use of energy services. Thus, there is a lack of incentives for these enterprises to operate in rural areas. P There are no policies that highlight the linkages between energy entrepreneurship and poverty reduction. Subsidies and fiscal allowances need to be offered to rural industries that use electricity, similar to the special tariffs offered to energy-intensive industries. Monetary allocation and credit schemes The Government has put in place a subsidy for fuels, providing a reprieve to disadvantaged households. Since early 2006, the consumer price of premium petrol (RON 97) was fixed at 1.92 ringgit per litre. Without the subsidy and tax exemption, the price of RON 97 in Peninsular Malaysia would be 2.46 ringgit per litre. For diesel, the non-subsidy price is 2.07 ringgit, whilst the consumer price is 1.26 ringgit. The impact of electrification on SMEs in rural areas has not been documented. 17 Energy and Poverty in Malaysia THE CHALLENGES The extra cost in the form of taxes foregone and subsidies is borne by the Government and this amounted to 14.7 billion ringgit in 2005. Likewise, the unsubsidized retail price of LPG in Peninsular Malaysia is 3.21 ringgit per kilogram. However, consumers buy it at the subsidized price of 1.75 ringgit per kilogram.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "4bf434fa-91fd-45c4-af00-984e009718cf": {"__data__": {"id_": "4bf434fa-91fd-45c4-af00-984e009718cf", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-malaysia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in Malaysia", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-malaysia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "90c6ce187d4f790a8ce466a200e5fba8bc4d00dd3ca3600958ed8e5741409f9f"}, "2": {"node_id": "c7e4da57-63d0-4bcd-8c1a-d6ef129f7d70", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-malaysia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": 