nother outcome of heavy subsidies is the smuggling of fuel, particularly diesel, to neighbouring countries. The Government also has to spend extra on enforcement personnel and equipment in order to arrest/curb smuggling activities. Also, huge subsidies are \u2018opportunity costs\u2019, that prevent the country from allocating more to national development, which would otherwise benefit a larger segment of its population. Savings from subsidies could be used to build more schools, hospitals and public BOX 7: KEY CHALLENGES TO PROVIDING FINANCIAL ASSISTANCE FOR ENERGY PROJECTS P Electricity tariffs under the rural electrification programme are not standardized. This hampers the drive towards complete poverty reduction. Tariff rates charged by SESB and SESCO for domestic, commercial and industrial categories are higher as compared to those charged by Tenaga Nasional Berhad, primarily because of the power generation costs. With the poverty incidence higher in rural Malaysia, these rates burden rural users with unaffordable energy costs and adversely impact the poverty reduction objective. P The participation of development financial institutions in rural energy financing is not significant. Banks and financial institutions are hesitant to support renewable energy projects, as they are not accepted as viable alternatives to conventional sources of energy, such as electricity. P Energy prices are highly subsidized. Provision of subsidies to oil and gas undermines the efforts to promote energy efficiency and renewable energy. 18 Energy and Poverty in Malaysia THE CHALLENGES facilities, which would provide long-term benefits to future generations. Both the rich and the poor are seen to benefit from subsidies, which are actually meant for the latter. Subsidies also risk the ability of the Government to reduce the budget deficit. To reduce energy prices for consumers, the micro-hydro project at Long Lawen (Sarawak) has been beneficial for households, as it helps by helping them set aside savings from their incomes. With 60 households having won access to electricity from the project, the total annual benefit accrued to these households amounts to US $5,644.8, indicating the project\u2019s high net value. As income from the Long Lawen project increases, an excess annual fund of US $2,200 in the project account is expected (Richards 2004). This surplus allows electricity to be supplied at reduced rates to families below the poverty line. Nevertheless, the project will need a survey of households by income to identify those eligible for reduced tariffs. Monitoring and evaluation systems focused on quantitative indicators The energy sector monitoring and evaluation (M&E) systems in Malaysia have not been able to incorporate qualitative indicators in project assessments. Primary indicators for energy M&E are gleaned from the national energy balance report prepared on a quarterly basis by MEWC and its key agency, PTM. This report provides data on energy usage and trends. The energy indicators are also taken from EC, which publishes annual statistics on electricity generation, distribution, sale and tariff. These statistics include the performance of IPPs and small renewable energy producers too. MRRD is the authority responsible for implementing and monitoring the progress of projects on rural electrification, but the indicators monitored are quantitative and relate to financial disbursement and implementation only. Additionally, EPU assesses the status of rural electrification and provides annual indicators on rural electrification in Peninsular Malaysia, Sabah and Sarawak. On the other hand, the population and housing census of the Department of Statistics (DoS) provides information on housing units with electricity in different states. Private contractors are hired to monitor the maintenance of SHSs in the rural households of Sabah and Sarawak (for example, the contractor hired for monitoring SHSs reports to BP Solar Malaysia, which collates the data and information). This information is then put forward to MRRD for further processing and evaluation. In the energy sector, qualitative indicators. are absent in project assessments. 19 Energy and Poverty in Malaysia THE CHALLENGES Policy initiatives on access to information There are several sources of information on energy use and its trends in Malaysia. EC provides information on electricity tariff, sales, generation mix and capacity, transmission and distribution, and system performance of the three regional utilities (TNB, SESB, SESCO), IPPs and other electricity distributors. The performance of some rural energy community-based organization projects, such as the Long Lawen and solar projects in Bario, Sarawak, has been documented. PTM is another organization that has also been entrusted with the task of documentation and dialogue with regard to energy, including the task", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "eb468c78-0cb7-4a0a-8192-d6d77e186c80": {"__data__": {"id_": "eb468c78-0cb7-4a0a-8192-d6d77e186c80", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-malaysia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in Malaysia", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-malaysia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "6c3e98982a0f391849c0ae0ab53314ae4e0f2789b2f8d601114273e251c29575"}, "3": {"node_id": "217af0dd-f808-48c5-ada7-e6c6eadb30f8", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-malaysia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "b86d27f5d146b401558d61f27cc066c3665d097d44c1b8858bfc2e9bdada3f58"}}, "hash": "277936f4a13a7ea26f52bbb0e400f2d4ddfc2a9869c63e669173d3f18a384577", "text": "of compiling the annual national energy balance. Various completed and ongoing projects \u2013 such as the Malaysian Industrial Energy Efficiency Improvement Project, BioGen Project, the Malaysian Building Integrated Photovoltaics (MBIPV) Project, and the Danish International Development Agency-sponsored Energy Efficiency and Demand Side Management Project \u2013 promote information dissemination and awareness generation. Such information-generating activities can go a long way in promoting the concept of rural poverty reduction through energy efficiency, if combined effectively with authoritative data on poverty. Generating awareness on energy efficiency and renewable energy can help reduce poverty. BOX 8: KEY CHALLENGES RELATED TO MONITORING AND EVALUATION FRAMEWORK P Lack of mechanisms, capacity and qualitative indicators to monitor the socio-economic impact of modern energy supply to rural populations. P Need for a coordinated approach to carry out monitoring and evaluation of rural energy service activities and study its impact on poverty reduction. BOX 9: KEY CHALLENGES TO FACILITATING ACCESS TO INFORMATION P Absence of income-level categorization of electricity access data in the census reports of DoS. P Gender disaggregated data on female income and employment (in terms of energy) are not methodically collected. The impact of electricity and renewable energy on women below the poverty line in rural Malaysia is yet to be evaluated and addressed. P Available data do not incorporate the rural energy sector and its linkage with poverty reduction. 20 Energy and Poverty in Malaysia THE CHALLENGES Gender concerns Poverty among women is a major concern for Malaysia, and the Government has made impressive advances in narrowing the gender gap, in terms of improved income and access to productive resources, education and health care. Economic growth has been accompanied by greater participation of women in the formal workforce as well as through the introduction of a range of other economic activities. However, gender gaps continue to exist. For example, women fare worse in the health and education indicators; wage differentials persist; and women are under- represented in the formal labour market. The Eighth Malaysia Plan (2001\u20132005) noted that the incidence of poverty among matriarchal households had increased from 15.1 percent in 1997 to 16.1 percent in 2001. This was partly because of the financial crisis that hit the country in 1997\u20131998, leading to retrenchment of industrial workers, many of them women. Poverty among Malaysian women takes on serious undertones if the urban\u2013rural divide is taken into account. However, there are positive developments to help women improve their financial status as well. One such endeavour is that of the not-for- profit organization Amanah Ikhtiar Malaysia (AIM), which provides micro- credit to rural women to set up small, self-owned enterprises. Close to 362,000 women (including single mothers) have benefited from this special micro-credit scheme. Another 1,500 women have received assistance under a micro-credit scheme run as part of the National Savings Bank (EPU 2001). During the Eighth Malaysia Plan (2000\u20132005), women in Malaysia were also included in the energy-based entrepreneurship initiatives. Several financial institutions (national banks and not-for-profit organizations) provided assistance to the women in the lower-income groups. For example, cook stoves were provided to women working in fish and agro- processing enterprises. Overall, the issue of poverty among women- BOX 10 KEY CHALLENGE RELATED TO GENDER CONCERNS P Though the EPU and MRRD have been fairly successful in formulating strategies for rural electrification, energy institutions have not addressed the impact of these strategies (through surveys and monitoring) on rural women. These institutions must take into account gender-sensitive energy service programmes, which perceive women as central to the poverty reduction agenda. The incidence of poverty among matriarchal households had increased to 16.1 percent in 2001. 21 Energy and Poverty in Malaysia THE CHALLENGES headed households has caught the attention of policy-makers and corrective steps are being taken, even though much remains to be done. MEETING THE CHALLENGES Encourage multi- stakeholder participation in the rural energy sector. Ensuring institutional participation in rural energy development A s rural energy service is an issue that cuts across myriad sectors, there is a strong need to establish multi-stakeholder participation in the development, implementation and monitoring stages. This can be achieved through the involvement of different stakeholders and institutions at multiple levels. Simultaneously, this has to be supported by favourable mechanisms and policy convergence strategies, promoted through the use of resources prevalent in the rural economy.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "217af0dd-f808-48c5-ada7-e6c6eadb30f8": {"__data__": {"id_": "217af0dd-f808-48c5-ada7-e6c6eadb30f8", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-malaysia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in Malaysia", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-malaysia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "6c3e98982a0f391849c0ae0ab53314ae4e0f2789b2f8d601114273e251c29575"}, "2": {"node_id": "eb468c78-0cb7-4a0a-8192-d6d77e186c80", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-malaysia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "277936f4a13a7ea26f52bbb0e400f2d4ddfc2a9869c63e669173d3f18a384577"}}, "hash": "b86d27f5d146b401558d61f27cc066c3665d097d44c1b8858bfc2e9bdada3f58", "text": "A mechanism that could enable such an initiative is the establishment of what may be an Inter-Agency Committee on Rural Energy for Poverty Reduction. It can be coordinated by EPU and MRRD, comprising officials from MEWC, TNB, SESB, SESCO, EC, the Ministry of Women, Family and Community Development and the Ministry of Agriculture and", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "dc1e2646-08b8-4def-944a-a0e8b359b9c0": {"__data__": {"id_": "dc1e2646-08b8-4def-944a-a0e8b359b9c0", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-malaysia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in Malaysia", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-malaysia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "0e0a86cd08af3834e6869456dac83dbadc2edd0f18e4c95dcae536b61b4bd7bb"}, "3": {"node_id": "e6470d45-a5ef-4097-97ac-a0cf7136965c", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-malaysia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "ec99cb9da4f2c6a16fb871973b59e245ebfaa5bdd1150c6e4bce5a7225414cba"}}, "hash": "631288cb4367c0f3005dac3128b169bb8d8a00fd5230510d27448a28bbd337c5", "text": "Agro- based Industries. Developing community-based programmes There is an urgent need to develop community-based energy programmes that see local communities manage the operation and maintenance of electricity systems. This is particularly needed in the remote regions of Sabah and Sarawak, where local utility service providers are unable to do so. Such programmes, if implemented, will develop and enhance local capacities and reduce operational costs, thereby increasing affordability for lower-income groups and contributing to poverty reduction. The privatization of the rural electrification programme (which can greatly reduce the Government\u2019s burden in funding rural electrification projects) could also offset the high cost of centralized generation and distribution, and set free a host of much-needed resources for poverty reduction. A new policy is needed to promote efficient delivery of energy services for poverty reduction in remote provinces. Among others, the policy could mandate the Government\u2019s support for setting up renewable energy projects, such as SHSs, micro-hydro systems and hybrids in remote and inaccessible areas. MEETING THE CHALLENGES 22 Energy and Poverty in Malaysia THE CHALLENGES In the march towards total energy availability and poverty reduction, it is important to recognize and emphasize the involvement of local communities in adopting renewable energy sources. Their participation is key to the acceleration of rural electrification programmes in remote and inaccessible areas. Adequately trained local communities with high awareness levels would be best suited to exploit energy availability for economic advancement. Making rural energy appropriate for local conditions could prove beneficial in the long run. Spatial, climatic and geographical considerations must be taken into account when deciding on the suitability of energy technologies. This could lead to greater electrification and energy efficiency for states such as Sabah and Sarawak. The two states could also be made the focus of SREPs. Smaller renewable energy projects (less than 1 MW) should also be promoted. These could prove to be truly effective in a country with geographical diversity. Promoting renewable energy, including biofuels and hydropower Biomass, another alternative to fossil fuels, is seen as a viable source of energy in the current millennium. The use of alternative energy has been further strengthened as the Government adopted it as the fifth fuel besides oil, gas, coal and hydro for the country\u2019s power generation sector, starting from 2000. Promoting renewable energy in the electrification of rural areas in Sabah and Sarawak is a viable strategy. A coordinated policy between relevant organizations (MEWC, MRRD, state authorities, SESB and SESCO) for the development of renewable energy and energy efficiency for total electrification of Sabah and Sarawak should be formulated. It may be essential for the Government to focus its SREPs on Sabah and Sarawak. The use of biofuel could contribute to poverty reduction by generating employment and making energy services affordable to the lower income group, especially in the wake of ever increasing prices of petrol and diesel. It will also help address the hardships faced by rural people, particularly in the remote areas of Sarawak. A well thought-out, broad-based biofuel policy for rural electrification could be implemented in order to diversify electrification technology. The biofuel manufactured could be more effective in the operation of generators in areas such as Bario, Bakelalan and Kapit in Sarawak. Hydroelectricity, especially in mini- or micro-hydro form, is already being used as a viable energy option in Malaysia to supplement fossil fuels. MEETING THE CHALLENGES Promote renewable energy in the rural areas of Sabah and Sarawak. 23 Energy and Poverty in Malaysia THE CHALLENGES Incentives for rural energy entrepreneurs Funding organizations, research institutions and academic bodies should treat rural energy systems as a priority area in research, documentation and capacity-building exercises, with the aim to develop suitable policy incentives for rural energy entrepreneurs. The impact of energy on rural enterprises must be highlighted by means of documentation, training programmes and publications. The Ministry of Science, Technology and Innovation could act as the funding agency for research under the Intensification of Research in Priority Areas mechanism. Funds for SMEs should target entrepreneurs involved in energy service delivery in rural areas and also labour-intensive enterprises in rural and remote regions. The services of national development banks and various other financial institutions could be harnessed for this purpose. It is also recommended that rural industries using electricity are granted subsidies and fiscal allowances, based on a percentage of their electricity consumption.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "e6470d45-a5ef-4097-97ac-a0cf7136965c": {"__data__": {"id_": "e6470d45-a5ef-4097-97ac-a0cf7136965c", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-malaysia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in Malaysia", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-malaysia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "0e0a86cd08af3834e6869456dac83dbadc2edd0f18e4c95dcae536b61b4bd7bb"}, "2": {"node_id": "dc1e2646-08b8-4def-944a-a0e8b359b9c0", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-malaysia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "631288cb4367c0f3005dac3128b169bb8d8a00fd5230510d27448a28bbd337c5"}}, "hash": "ec99cb9da4f2c6a16fb871973b59e245ebfaa5bdd1150c6e4bce5a7225414cba", "text": "This task needs to be taken up by MoF and entities such as TNB, SESCO and SESB, along with IPPs. Easy access to financial options for small rural energy projects Money lenders tend to associate small-scale consumers with high credit risk. One way of addressing this misperception is", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "e12dab5f-4ed1-43a6-95a7-7be11c42b0e7": {"__data__": {"id_": "e12dab5f-4ed1-43a6-95a7-7be11c42b0e7", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-malaysia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in Malaysia", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-malaysia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "aee826051f50235adc04771cc7661de7a53e63b2a2c9e107550d12599baca369"}}, "hash": "aee826051f50235adc04771cc7661de7a53e63b2a2c9e107550d12599baca369", "text": "to organize villagers into groups that are collectively responsible for income generation and repayment of the loan. It may be relevant here to adapt and replicate experiences of micro-credit schemes targeted at women in rural areas by AIM. The inclusion of fiscal components in renewable energy projects (similar to BioGen and MBIPV projects co-sponsored by UNDP and GEF) could help popularize non-conventional sources of energy in rural Malaysia, especially in Sabah and Sarawak. Further, a system of small- scale lending scheme can be established to provide loans to a non- governmental organization, which can then facilitate lending for village or small-scale projects, similar to the Long Lawen micro-hydro project in Sarawak. Deregulation of the rural energy market and extension of MESITA fund to include Sabah and Sarawak could ensure a higher degree of energy access for the lower-income groups in rural Malaysia. MEETING THE CHALLENGES Put in place innovative financing schemes targeted at women in rural areas. 24 Energy and Poverty in Malaysia THE CHALLENGES Creating monitoring and evaluation indicators for energy and poverty assessments An immediate step is the appointment of a relevant organization to develop a comprehensive database on the rural electrification programme and its impact on poverty reduction. PTM \u2013 as the national energy centre \u2013 is recommended as the focal point to centralize information and develop a database that can be used to assess linkages among poverty reduction, gender and energy availability for rural areas. The community-based approach to M&E, such as in the small hydropower project in Long Lawen, Sarawak, could serve as a model for ongoing and future small-scale hydro projects in rural and remote areas. EC should distinguish between rural and urban electricity transmission and distribution. Such a move will not only aid energy and development with regard to rural electrification, but also be a definitive milestone in the area of poverty reduction, through intensified rural electrification. Proper research and documentation are principal requirements for the M&E process. PTM, the Centre for Training in Renewable Energy and Energy Efficiency and local universities should collaborate to incorporate rural energy systems as subjects of research and knowledge dissemination. The Malaysian Energy Database and Information System established by PTM could be assigned projects dealing with rural energy and poverty so that data can be collected, collated and published systematically. Development of indicators for comprehensive monitoring of energy and poverty concerns should also be undertaken by PTM. Greater focus on facilitating access to energy information A range of activities can be carried out to share relevant, timely and important information on Malaysia\u2019s energy and poverty scenarios such as publication and dissemination by MRRD. Data collected through monitoring of SHSs, for instance, could be consolidated, analysed and published, with easy access to stakeholders and those interested. The impact of energy on rural enterprises, incomes and poverty reduction needs to be highlighted through documentation, workshops and publications. For instance, DoS could take on the task of managing data on energy inputs in the micro, small and medium enterprises. PTM can act as a platform for consultation and dissemination of data and information on rural energy systems through periodic workshops, training modules and seminars, and also act as a one-stop centre for all information on rural energy in Malaysia, including the impact on the communities. MEETING THE CHALLENGES Develop a comprehensive database on the rural electrification programme and its impact on poverty reduction. 25 Energy and Poverty in Malaysia THE CHALLENGES Available technologies such as the geographic information system could also be utilized to map energy and fuel sources at the village, district and regional levels. This would simplify the identification of areas and villages not earlier surveyed and facilitate effective planning and implementation. Mainstreaming gender issues The Government funds for SMEs in rural areas must mandate the use of clean energy within their loan portfolios. Such loans could be specifically directed for integrating efficient energy supply to women-owned and operated enterprises. Documentation of gender-specific impact of electricity (and other energy forms) on productivity and income gains in rural enterprises such as rice mills, weaving enterprises, batik and crafts establishments, fish processing and so on would help replicate best practices. CONCLUSION M alaysia\u2019s strong, sustained economic growth has made a positive contribution towards poverty reduction, socio- economic development and provision of basic needs, including access to energy services. Although there is no rigorous study on the direct relation between poverty and rural electrification, there is a strong inverse correlation between the two. Rural electrification has been seen to aid socio-economic welfare of the poor. It has led to improved education, health, employment, agriculture, as well as growth in", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "a79843cf-b5e6-4ce9-b978-8dc5d6098853": {"__data__": {"id_": "a79843cf-b5e6-4ce9-b978-8dc5d6098853", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-malaysia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type