d20e1e54ca41a96f29f866de2ca0b76a0a19ba52082e8bdf1c7997"}}, "hash": "081bd01e95d20e1e54ca41a96f29f866de2ca0b76a0a19ba52082e8bdf1c7997", "text": "tion reports on Nepal\u2019s energy sector and its linkages to poverty concerns, gaps therein and modalities for overcoming the same. It aims to facilitate the inclu- sion of a strong energy component into the Nepal\u2019s socio-economic develop- ment programmes. US$ 5", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "fd7850a7-f7b4-42c2-a2e5-7b2088405cea": {"__data__": {"id_": "fd7850a7-f7b4-42c2-a2e5-7b2088405cea", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-sri-lanka", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in Sri Lanka", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-sri-lanka", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "3b8e761b921d97c417fc03f3f5894d85183f142da682a0d839561d98708b7d7d"}, "3": {"node_id": "3ed83482-f3b0-4200-aec3-28db24d1098b", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-sri-lanka", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "82efa35e4c71200e55c150fd89444ca348856f2ad98060aed53b426381f4e825"}}, "hash": "6fc8bee54ca758e81c1055b49a5077fdb8ddbaa3e55756b9368289f6709840d5", "text": "Regional Energy Programme for Poverty Reduction UNDP Regional Centre in Bangkok Challenges and the Way Forward ENERGY AND POVERTY IN SRI LANKA Energy and Poverty in Sri Lanka iv Design and layout: Keen Media (Thailand) Co., Ltd. Cover images: IFAD/G. Bizzarri, UNDP-Sri Lanka The analysis and policy recommendations of this report do not necessarily reflect the views of the United Nations Development Programme (UNDP), its executive board or its member states. The report is an independent publication commissioned by UNDP. It is the fruit of a collaborative effort by a team of eminent experts, stakeholders and the Regional Energy Programme for Poverty Reduction (REP-PoR) team of the Regional Centre in Bangkok. Copyright \u00a9 2007 UNDP United Nations Development Programme Regional Energy Programme for Poverty Reduction (REP-PoR) UNDP Regional Centre in Bangkok UN Service Building Rajdamnern Nok Avenue Bangkok 10200 Thailand http://regionalcentrebangkok.undp.or.th http://regionalcentrebangkok.undp.or.th/practices/energy_env/rep-por ISBN-13: 978-92-1-126190-5 Assigned Sales #: E.06.III.B.7 v Energy and Poverty in Sri Lanka FOREWORD More than a billion people in the Asia-Pacific region do not have access to electricity and 1.7 billion are dependent on traditional biomass fuels for their cooking and heating needs. Access to affordable modern energy services can improve their productivity and enhance living standards. Even so, there are no specific targets for the energy sector in the Millennium Declaration, a historic document signed seven years ago by the world\u2019s leaders. Affordable and sustainable modern energy services are a necessity for countries to meet their Millennium Development Goals (MDGs). Efforts of countries in the Asia-Pacific region to meet these aims will be hindered unless adequate attention is given to the crucial role energy services play in the development process. This is particularly true for the economic, environmental and social well-being of the poor. With fluctuating energy prices, the poor in many of the countries in the Asia and Pacific region face a daunting future. For them, access to affordable and essential modern energy services that could improve their living conditions and ensure a means to earn a living will fall outside their reach. Recognizing the urgency for countries to factor in access to modern energy services, particularly when shaping national poverty reduction initiatives, the United Nations Development Programme (UNDP) provided technical and financial support for national-level rapid energy assessments. The primary aim of this work, carried out through UNDP\u2019s Regional Energy Programme for Poverty Reduction (REP-PoR) and completed in 2006, was to identify gaps and priority needs in linking energy services provision with poverty reduction. The framework for rapid gap assessments linking energy and poverty was developed as a joint effort of the UNDP Regional Centre in Bangkok (RCB) and UNDP country offices in the region, with the support of experts from the region. The draft framework was discussed at two sub-regional meetings, one held in Bangkok, Thailand (August 2005) and the other in Apia, Samoa (September 2005). The meetings were helpful in customizing the framework to suit specific needs and circumstances of the participating countries. Subsequently, UNDP country offices held national-level stakeholder consultations to consolidate the findings and recommendations of the assessments. This work benefited immensely from the support of government Energy and Poverty in Sri Lanka vi officials and representatives of civil society. Documented in individual country reports, this work serves as resource and reference material for programming and planning for access to modern energy services for the underserved, particularly, the poor. This document is a summary of the Country Report on Sri Lanka and is part of a series of REP-PoR\u2019s Asia-Pacific publications. It draws on the key findings of the Country Report, summarizes the challenges faced at the national level, and provides priority recommendations. Specifically, critical issues related to energy policy, including institutional structures, regulatory frameworks, priority programmes, financing measures, gender concerns, as well as monitoring and evaluation support are highlighted. It offers a way forward, outlining issues and options for the country. Our hope is that this document will be of relevance to national policy makers, development partners, energy service providers, civil society organizations and academia in implementing various measures to promote access to modern energy services for the poor. Marcia V.J.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "3ed83482-f3b0-4200-aec3-28db24d1098b": {"__data__": {"id_": "3ed83482-f3b0-4200-aec3-28db24d1098b", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-sri-lanka", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in Sri Lanka", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-sri-lanka", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "3b8e761b921d97c417fc03f3f5894d85183f142da682a0d839561d98708b7d7d"}, "2": {"node_id": "fd7850a7-f7b4-42c2-a2e5-7b2088405cea", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-sri-lanka", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "6fc8bee54ca758e81c1055b49a5077fdb8ddbaa3e55756b9368289f6709840d5"}}, "hash": "82efa35e4c71200e55c150fd89444ca348856f2ad98060aed53b426381f4e825", "text": "Marcia V.J. Kran Head of Policy and Programmes UNDP Regional Centre in Bangkok vii Energy and Poverty in Sri Lanka PREFACE This report sets out to examine the ways and means to providing affordable, accessible and reliable energy services in support of achievement of the Millennium Development Goals (MDGs) and poverty reduction in Sri Lanka. The underlying premise of this study is that access to affordable and sustainable sources of energy has strong links to poverty reduction. This is particularly the case in terms of energy and its", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "9a596527-41c6-4513-91a7-0c0d4313f068": {"__data__": {"id_": "9a596527-41c6-4513-91a7-0c0d4313f068", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-sri-lanka", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in Sri Lanka", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-sri-lanka", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "36b49e4a91e3526efb021c63c6c97db1cfecb9ecf195d77dd675764e56238f23"}}, "hash": "36b49e4a91e3526efb021c63c6c97db1cfecb9ecf195d77dd675764e56238f23", "text": "effects on household income, health, education, gender and the environment. The report also offers options for the country to overcome its energy sector challenges. This study is valid in the context of Sri Lanka, where the income gap is widening between the rich and the poor, and the country is heavily dependent on energy imports, especially in the electricity and transport sectors. Biomass is an important source of energy in Sri Lanka, particularly for the rural poor. About 90 percent of energy for cooking in the rural areas comes from biomass sources, the remaining 10 percent from kerosene and LPG. In Sri Lanka, nearly 80 percent of the biomass comes from non-forest resources, namely agricultural and plantation work. Seventy percent of the biomass is collected free from home gardens and plantations, and 30 percent is purchased, mainly in urban areas. Electricity and modern fuels are burdensome on poor households due to affordability, quality of services and supply constraints. This study examines critical energy issues in Sri Lanka related to the institutional structure of the energy sector, policy and regulatory framework, and sectoral programmes. It analyses reasons for the limited reach of energy services to rural provinces; unsustainable dependence on traditional fuels and inefficient technologies; the restricted supply of energy by rural energy enterprises; and inadequate financing for energy. Gender concerns are also examined in rural energy projects and programmes. It highlights the urgent need for key data and indicators to support monitoring and evaluation of energy access for areas that are least served. This report concludes that while strong institutional arrangements and policy focus on electrification enhance conditions of rural households and industries, the exclusion of traditional biomass from considerations limits the creation of a comprehensive pro-poor energy strategy in Sri Lanka. Improved capacities of government entities, especially at the provincial Energy and Poverty in Sri Lanka viii level, could enhance rural energy development, thus promoting the provision of energy access for the poor. A comprehensive regulatory framework that includes all significant energy sources needs to be developed, including the renewable energy sector. Renewable energy projects are mainly driven by external agencies, yet there should be more focus on renewable energy technologies (RETs) that can be handled from within. Several NGOs are active in developing these types of RETs that are suitable to local conditions. Promising energy initiatives can and do exist in Sri Lanka. For instance, the Renewable Energy for Rural Economic Development (RERED) and the Energy Service Delivery (ESD) projects, financed by the Global Environment Facility and the World Bank, have enhanced the adoption of renewable energy technologies for electricity generation since 1997. The RERED and ESD project components have resulted in improvements in local capacities, for example in design, implementation and operation stages of village level projects. In addition, the Government is helping the poor to establish a livelihood through dendro power initiatives. These initiatives have potential in ensuring active participation of the community, building local capacities and the technology base that could support poverty alleviation activities. The policy focus of the National Energy Policy and Strategies (NEPS) of Sri Lanka 2006 to expand the delivery of affordable energy services to a larger share of the population, to improve energy sector planning, management and regulation, and to revitalize biomass as a significant resource of commercial is highly commendable. The establishment of Sri Lanka Sustainable Energy Authority (SEA), officially launched in October 2007, is also an important step undertaken by the Government toward a strengthened framework for the energy sector, particularly for renewable energy development, demand-side energy efficiency improvement and energy conservation. Capacity-building for institutional and technical capacities within SEA is also planned with the help of the Asian Development Bank. The Government\u2019s plan to expand the share of grid-electrified households to 85 percent and off-grid electrified households to 8 percent, and the share of renewable energy in total energy generation to 10 percent by 2015, as stated in NEPS 2006, is yet another very positive step. These government-supported targets must be complemented, however, with additional strong efforts towards implementation and the goal of improved energy access for poverty reduction to correct socio-economic imbalances. Equally important is providing poor households with access to alternative sources of affordable modern fuels and efficient energy ix Energy and Poverty in Sri Lanka technology. Well targeted pro-poor subsidies and cost-efficient tariffs are therefore imperative. Such policies can have a major impact on the capital costs for rural grid electrification and the development of off-grid solutions. These must be complemented by strengthened and improved schemes for the provision of energy related microfinance for micro-scale enterprises and different income-generating activities. We trust", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "dc167ae9-5462-4205-8290-11b01933df84": {"__data__": {"id_": "dc167ae9-5462-4205-8290-11b01933df84", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-sri-lanka", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in Sri Lanka", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-sri-lanka", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "e2ce7cd9ba72fff5833aabf12f12138addf8f898011cb7bb753c455b35e2e121"}, "3": {"node_id": "cddb0606-3a40-4dcc-a91b-271670c61f49", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_U