ent}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "8bbe71bf-fe59-42a1-952b-5fef2662c1ac": {"__data__": {"id_": "8bbe71bf-fe59-42a1-952b-5fef2662c1ac", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-sri-lanka", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in Sri Lanka", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-sri-lanka", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "00f941a3f13aff7a8f38acd80a2d6861ab9799cb66330236199e5ded6915f915"}, "2": {"node_id": "52b3a2df-90fd-4112-99a2-0e931e93d035", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-sri-lanka", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "bed82161203a64445c2a907138b7a6df3f0bf88f6dc2dc4b30528fadd9818244"}}, "hash": "9cf1f61ffc146db24d607ca2e968ff24f0f3a41c9a119386174ea4c3087648cf", "text": "The rate of poverty (23 percent) and the Gini coefficient (0.46), however, indicate that benefits from a 5 percent gross domestic product (GDP) growth in the 1980s and 1990s have not yet percolated to the poor (Bandusena 2005). In addition, the gap between the rich and the poor appears to be widening in the country. The income of the poorest 20 percent of the population has grown only by 5.7 percent while that of the richest 20 percent has grown by 140 percent. The rural sector, including Sources UNFPA 2007; IEA 2006; UNDP 2007; and UNDP 2006 S Capital Colombo Area 65,610 square kilometres Population (2007) 21.1 million Total primary energy supply/Population (2004) 0.49 toe/capita Gross domestic product (GDP) (2004) 18.67 billion US$ 2000 Energy Production (2004) 5.16 Mtoe Poverty (the most recent year available during 1990-2005) 5.6% (population below income poverty line US$1) Population without electricity (2005) 6.7 million Traditional fuel consumption (2003) 60.4% of total energy requirements Electricity Consumption / Population (2004) 345 kWh/capita Net Imports (2004) 4.41 Mtoe GDP per unit of energy use (2004) 8.3 US$ 2000 PPP per kg of oil equivalent CO2/Population (2004) 0.65t CO2/capita 2 Energy and Poverty in Sri Lanka THE CHALLENGES THE CHALLENGES T the plantation sector, is an important component of economic development, with a population of nearly 85 percent of the total population engaged in agricultural activities. The energy needs of the rural sector are met through means such as animal power, wood and agro- waste for heat generation; electricity for lighting and high-end uses such as television, radio and other electrical appliances; and fossil fuels for transportation. Currently, 90 percent of Sri Lanka\u2019s export earnings of all agricultural products are expended on imports of petroleum products, a statistic that is both uncomfortable and unaffordable in the current energy-poverty scenario of the country. Sri Lanka, which has the unique distinction of using auto-diesel for large power generating units, fulfils all its fossil fuel needs", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "f96e1d07-3a13-4a10-a50d-d92c06cb14d5": {"__data__": {"id_": "f96e1d07-3a13-4a10-a50d-d92c06cb14d5", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-sri-lanka", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in Sri Lanka", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-sri-lanka", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "3fbb04a8afc712c5c039910b224f8079f1e5192741eea1aafdd8b891cbcf39aa"}}, "hash": "3fbb04a8afc712c5c039910b224f8079f1e5192741eea1aafdd8b891cbcf39aa", "text": "through imports. The steadily rising prices of conventional energy and the 100 percent import of fossil fuel based energy place the weaker sections of Sri Lanka in a difficult situation. There have been some improvements in terms of the institutional, legal, regulatory and financial mechanisms to electrify rural areas. In off-grid areas, the World Bank-funded Renewable Energy for Rural Economic Development (RERED) project and budgetary grant of SLR 10,000 per household by the Central Government changed the situation to a large extent. However, much more needs to be done. Some of the future tasks are already stated in the National Energy Policy and Strategies (NEPS) of Sri Lanka 2006. Institutional arrangements he primary electricity handling institution in Sri Lanka is the national Ceylon Electricity Board (CEB). The CEB possesses 85 percent of the generating capacity and distributes electricity to about 2.5 million customers. The fully publicly-owned Lanka Electricity Company (LECO) not only distributes electricity to about 350,000 consumers in the western and southern coastal belts, but also owns the low-voltage distribution network in its territory. Petroleum supplies are mainly handled by the government-controlled Ceylon Petroleum Corporation (CEYPETCO). The CEYPETCO is supplemented by the Lanka Indian Oil Corporation (LIOC), the first company to enter into the local petroleum market in early 2003 to supply petrol and diesel to the Sri Lankan consumers. All these utilities are overseen by the Ministry of Power and Energy (MoPE). Liquefied petroleum gas (LPG) is mainly handled by several private sector companies, including Shell Gas Lanka (Pvt.) Ltd and 3 Energy and Poverty in Sri Lanka THE CHALLENGES Gas Auto Lanka (Pvt.) Ltd. A regulatory structure for all physical infrastructure industries, such as electricity and petroleum, in the form of the Public Utilities Commission of Sri Lanka (PUCSL) is already in place. Ministries dealing with energy issues exist at the provincial level, but they have limited long-term perspective and the mandate to think or work beyond rural electrification. The Ministry of Samurdhi and Poverty Alleviation and the Ministry of Rural Industries are handling poverty and rural industries but rural energy needs are not included in their main activities. The Ministries of Power and Energy (MoPEs) in the Provincial Councils are mainly concerned with rural electrification as far as poverty and energy issues are concerned. Therefore, even at the decentralized levels, the institutional arrangements mainly concentrate on electricity and fossil fuel supply, although nearly half of the energy requirement of the rural people is met by biomass. There is no specific institution designated to focus on traditional biomass since it is considered as part of the informal sector. Nor does the relatively important animal power used in transport and draft work come under the present institutional structure that is handling energy. In addition, many rural activities require thermal energy either for heating, dehydration, or cooling of produce; therefore, having only electricity-focused institutional arrangements limits coordinated action in meeting the demand efficiently. The use of energy in the form of thermal energy in rural economic activities such as in brick kilns, bakeries and other small-scale manufacturing is handled mainly by non- governmental organizations (NGOs) and community-based organizations (CBOs). The institutional arrangement looking at alternative energy for rural activities is the former Energy Conservation Fund (ECF), which again places significant emphasis on electricity. Institutional responsibilities attributed to ECF were transferred to the Sri Lanka Sustainable Energy Authority (SEA) that was officially launched in October 2007. SEA is mandated to develop and implement policies for renewable energy development, demand-side energy efficiency improvement and energy conservation. Alternative energy research and development (R&D) has been entrusted to the Alternative Energy Division (AED) of the Ministry of Science and Technology (MoST), the National Engineering Research and Development (NERD) Centre, and other institutions. Figure 1 presents the main energy sector institutions in Sri Lanka. Even at the decentralized levels, the institutional arrangements mainly concentrate on electricity and fossil fuel supply. 4 Energy and Poverty in Sri Lanka THE CHALLENGES FIGURE 1 ENERGY SECTOR INSTITUTIONS IN SRI LANKA Policy and regulatory framework Since the late 1970s, successive governments in Sri Lanka have been consistently following the principles of an open economy, with the GDP growing at 4 to 6 percent during this period. Over the years, the Government development policy frameworks have promoted both endogenous and external input based development, yet poverty reduction through rural energy services has not been often clearly stated in development strategies and plans. \u25a0 The institutional arrangement benefits mainly electricity- and fossil fuel-based energy development, also in the rural context. \u25a0 Provincial energy ministries have limited influence on rural energy planning, although they are in better position to", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "877e7804-df62-4c93-a76a-