nal growth. For example, the domestic energy supply and domestic work done by women related to energy supply fall under this third sector. This is a positive statement as far as energy and poverty are concerned. Yet the energy policy emphasis persists in the development and provision of electrical energy. The common assumption is that the supply of electricity would alleviate poverty in the rural areas, although many of the rural activities require thermal energy either for heating, dehydration or cooling of produce. Furthermore, the cost of electricity may not be affordable to the poor. Although the electricity sector regularly carries out elaborate planning about future generation needs, these plans are not implemented as expected for a variety of reasons, such as environmental permits, security situation and project financing. Short- and medium-term proposals outside the long-term generation plans, to meet the changed needs, are often outside the \u2018optimum\u2019 energy mix envisaged in the long-term plans. Power shortages are met, for example, by generating power from auto-diesel which is among the most expensive ways of generating power. Hence, the implementation of these plans has resulted in the cost of electricity rising well above the anticipated values. According to the Long-Term Generation Expansion Plan: 2003-2017, prepared by the CEB, Sri Lanka\u2019s electricity requirement has been growing at an average rate of 7-8 percent annually (MoPE 2005). In 2002, the CEB\u2019s grid access extended to approximately 65 percent of the country\u2019s households but for the rural sector it only reached 45 percent. There are several policies to support the expansion of rural access to electricity. For example, the Sri Lanka Rural Electrification Policy in 2002 stated as its objective to expand access to electricity to 75 percent of Sri Lanka\u2019s population by 2007 through the connection to the main grid, and where this is not feasible through off-grid services at the village or household scale. Due to financial and technical constraints, grid electricity cannot be extended to close to 1.5 million households. These mainly rural households are required to depend on off-grid electrical energy. Power shortages are met, for example, by generating power from auto-diesel which is among the most expensive ways of generating power. 6 Energy and Poverty in Sri Lanka THE CHALLENGES NEPS of Sri Lanka 2006 also states medium-term electrification targets for grid-electrification and off-grid electrification. The Government is aiming at providing 85 percent of households with grid-electricity and 8 percent of households with off-grid by 2015. NEPS 2006 also spells out the policy elements, strategies and specific targets that will guide the development and management of the energy sector in the coming years in order to facilitate the achievement of the Millennium Development Goals (MDGs). It introduces specific new initiatives to expand the delivery of affordable energy services to a larger share of the population, to improve energy sector planning, management and regulation, and to revitalize biomass as a significant resource of commercial energy. NEPS 2006 aims at supporting the following fundamental elements that guide the future of the energy sector in Sri Lanka: \u2022 Fulfill basic energy needs of people and provide energy for economic development. \u2022 Ensure energy security via resource diversification and future energy mix rationalization, which takes into account factors such as economic costs, environmental impacts and reliability of supply. \u2022 Promote energy efficiency and conservation in management and operations of energy systems and in energy utilization. \u2022 Promote optimum development of local resources and minimum dependence on non-indigenous resources. \u2022 Adopt an appropriate pricing policy which takes into account factors such as cost reflectivity, targeted subsidies and local competitiveness. \u2022 Enhance local capacities to manage and develop the energy sector effectively, taking into account technological", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "ce3330ca-1775-4c48-b694-b265c125956c": {"__data__": {"id_": "ce3330ca-1775-4c48-b694-b265c125956c", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-sri-lanka", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in Sri Lanka", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-sri-lanka", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "1bc36cf31e1aed342b4dff571be92415f3837b6de23a51428e6a842b1a5afbe5"}, "3": {"node_id": "267f9582-d17e-42ac-b49d-5ee8e76040cf", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-sri-lanka", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "7359ec5192fcfdda824a3cecc4aa3a608083106000eda6364db7f85edcd1956e"}}, "hash": "936c735af5f15a736cc19ba6e00f4018cc462c21b56ebd36e840c6a7ff70fcd6", "text": "developments and good governance. \u2022 Safeguard current and future consumers and ensure a level playing field to all stakeholders, including all energy sector investors. \u2022 Enhance the quality of energy services through standards and regulations. \u2022 Minimize adverse environmental impacts of energy facilities, with special emphasis on electricity and petroleum sub-sector activities. Although NEPS 2006 acknowledges the need to promote and facilitate the commercial biomass as a new rural industry, it also states that biomass remains as a sub-sector that will not be formally organized the same way as the electricity and petroleum sub-sectors, unless new significant developments occur in terms of biomass becoming an important primary energy source for electricity generation. The Government is aiming at achieving a minimum level of 10 percent of electrical energy supplied 7 Energy and Poverty in Sri Lanka THE CHALLENGES to the grid to be from non-conventional renewable energy (NCRE) by 2015 (MoPE 2006). The policy specifically refers to NCRE promoted for grid electricity generation, which includes small-scale hydropower; biomass, including dendro power, biogas and waste; solar power; and wind power. Therefore, traditional biomass use in industries such as brick making and pottery, which forms a vital economic activity in most villages, still receives limited attention, if any. The emphasis on motive power through wind energy for water pumping is lacking as well. Even the plantation industry relies heavily on fuelwood for heat generation needed in the processing. Therefore, the policy and regulatory framework in Sri Lanka aims at improving the access, affordability and engagement of the rural poor; however the focus is too narrow to benefit those who are mainly using traditional energy sources. \u25a0 The energy policy and regulatory framework focuses on the development and provision of electrical energy. \u25a0 Despite the energy policy, electricity costs in Sri Lanka are high. \u25a0 Recognition of NCRE development exists currently, but it will be considered in the regulatory framework only if its share in electricity production increases. Focus on traditional energy sources is lacking. BOX 2: KEY CHALLENGES IN POLICY AND REGULATORY FRAMEWORK Energy programme framework Over the years government-led poverty reduction programmes have mainly focused on infrastructure development in rural areas and some on electrification. Certain government-led sub-programmes such as Gemi Diriya (Village Strength), Dahasak Vew (Tank Rehabilitation), Maga Neguma (Rehabilitation of Rural Roads), the Dairy Village Programme, and the Gamata Taakshanaya (Technology to Village) focus on issues such as the strengthening of markets, credit, technical support, and implementation capacity of local governments. These are being implemented through the ministries to reduce poverty via infrastructure development in the rural areas. The main government programme, as far as rural energy is concerned, is the supply of electricity through the grid and expansion of rural electrification. The core objective is to supply low-cost electricity by establishing low-cost coal-fired plants and electrify rural areas, whereas renewable energy and biomass options have not been given much emphasis The policy and regulatory framework is too narrow to benefit those who are mainly using traditional energy sources. 8 Energy and Poverty in Sri Lanka THE CHALLENGES in the government plans. Therefore, the renewable energy programmes in Sri Lanka are mainly donor-driven. The RERED and the Energy Service Delivery (ESD) projects financed by the Global Environment Facility (GEF) and the World Bank have raised hopes of maximizing the economic, social, and environmental benefits of rural electrification through the participation of the private sector and households, such as in developing grid-connected mini-hydro power and solar home systems (SHSs). The RERED and ESD project components have resulted in improvements in local capacities; for example in design, implementation and operation stages of village level projects. State-sponsored renewable energy programmes such as the installation of 200 wind turbines to pump water, carried out by the Water Resource Board (WRB) and the supply of wood charcoal by the State Timber Corporation \u2013 initiated to utilize the timber facing threat of inundation by the Mahaveli Development Programme \u2013 are still at a nascent stage. Wind energy programmes undertaken by the Intermediate Technology Development Group (ITDG), which has implemented a 2.5-kW project to supply electricity to 22 houses in Weniwelara, and the NERD Centre on a much smaller scale are only directed towards electricity supply. More recently, the Government has envisaged helping the poor to establish a livelihood through energy supply by supporting the proposed dendro thermal initiative that has been given the cabinet approval.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "267f9582-d17e-42ac-b49d-5ee8e76040cf": {"__data__": {"id_": "267f9582-d17e-42ac-b49d-5ee8e76040cf", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-sri-lanka", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in Sri Lanka", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-sri-lanka", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "1bc36cf31e1aed342b4dff571be92415f3837b6de23a51428e6a842b1a5afbe5"}, "2": {"node_id": "ce3330ca-1775-4c48-b694-b265c125956c", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-sri-lanka", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "936c735af5f15a736cc19ba6e00f4018cc462c21b56ebd36e840c6a7ff70fcd6"}}, "hash": "7359ec5192fcfdda824a3cecc4aa3a608083106000eda6364db7f85edcd1956e", "text": "In 2004 an Inter-Ministerial Working Committee on Dendro Thermal Technology (IMWCDTT) was appointed and its action plan is to implement a five year programme comprising of policy, integrative, economic, technical and communicative actions within a period of three phases", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "8cd6da14-a5d1-4519-b004-3bbd63aa4819": {"__data__": {"id_": "8cd6da14-a5d1-4519-b004-3bbd63aa4819", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-sri-lanka", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in Sri Lanka", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-sri-lanka", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "10620fbafb8f5c2982d4fa23e5c3f2a67d085fcd1d6f38f0df3f1110861ea73f"}}, "hash": "10620fbafb8f5c2982d4fa23e5c3f2a67d085fcd1d6f38f0df3f1110861ea73f", "text": "to realize an installed capacity of 100MW by year 2010 as grid connected electricity. Table 2 summarizes the recommendations from IMWCDTT; however, specific recommendations on how the targets could be achieved are missing. TABLE 1 THE SUMMARY OF THE RECOMMENDATIONS FROM IMWCDTT GIVEN IN JUNE 2005 I. Expedite the Action Plan and proposals made by the IMWC to realize a minimum of 100MW of dendro thermal electric power by 2010 with a provision to review targets at phase II. II. Elevate fuelwood plantation to the level of other commercial crops as a measure of building confidence in the investor community and the fuelwood farming community in order to mobilize large scale fuelwood farming. 9 Energy and Poverty in Sri Lanka THE CHALLENGES III. Incorporate dendro thermal based off-grid power systems into the Rural Electrification Schemes that are funded by donor assistance and local provisions for the benefit of those communities who would not have access to grid electricity. IV. Formulation of a national renewable energy promotion policy framework with special emphasis on the biomass technology to facilitate bank financing, attractive credit systems, soft-loan- based donor assistance, development incentives and expeditious land allocation procedure. V. Explore technical assistance for capacity-building in technology, possible industrial entrepreneurship, fuelwood agronomy and processing aspects. TABLE 1 THE SUMMARY OF THE RECOMMENDATIONS FROM IMWCDTT GIVEN IN JUNE 2005 (CONT\u2019D) Source IMWCDTT (2005) Most rural electricity supply projects are limited in their rural capacity- building potential. This is partly due to the technology involved and the method of executing the projects based on buying and supplying most of the inputs needed. The equipment supplied under a license would also demand maintenance and upkeep to be carried out by the suppliers thus restricting the possibility of technology flow to the village. The CBOs and NGOs with the assistance of private sector participation have faired better in capacity development with regard to alternate energy though it is again confined to rural electricity. The initiative to introduce dendro power at village level has potential in building local capacities and the technology base that could support poverty alleviation activities. The continuous supply of fuel and labour intensive operations of drying, feeding of fuel and routine cleaning of the equipment would ensure active participation of the community. Already existing units have demonstrated how the rural people take up the work involved and adopt their own methods to suit specific requirements. \u25a0 Government-led poverty reduction programmes have mainly focused on infrastructure development in rural areas, while only some have on electrification. \u25a0 Renewable energy programmes are mainly driven by external agencies. \u25a0 Limited emphasis on energy programmes that also focus on improving the livelihoods of the poor. BOX 3: KEY CHALLENGES IN ENERGY PROGRAMME FRAMEWORK Most rural electricity supply projects are limited in their rural capacity- building potential. 10 Energy and Poverty in Sri Lanka THE CHALLENGES Limited emphasis on energy access for poverty reduction In Sri Lanka, access to energy is constrained by inadequate capacity of electricity generation, inability of distribution agencies to supply electricity, unequal eligibility criteria for consumers and limited affordability. Lack of investments is the prime obstacle in access to energy across the country. At commercial rates of borrowing, renewable energy cannot compete with conventional energy. Foreign investment in the rural energy sector has been limited to transport and the distribution of petroleum and LPG. Alternative energy supplies, even in the area of electricity, have to face unequal terms as a result of the unavailability of foreign investments. Access to electricity has been governed by selected criteria of the CEB based on socio-economic indicators. The CEB places high priority on rural communities, which hold promise in terms of markets, demonstrate low risks, and score highly on economic internal rate of return. Energy-poverty linkages are frequently overlooked in poverty reduction strategies; energy is usually not linked with other pro-poor policies and activities. This often leads to less suitable energy services being supplied in isolation from other energy needs in the community. Electricity is only a part of the rural energy demand available to just about 90 percent of the population after complete implementation of the rural electrification programme in Sri Lanka. It is doubtful whether this supply of minimum electrical energy would support any economic activity to reduce poverty. Energy for cooking in the rural areas comes mainly from biomass, accounting for 90 percent of the total; the remaining 10 percent comes from kerosene and LPG. Energy for lighting, which accounts for 7.5 percent of the energy consumed by the poor, comes from electricity (55 percent) and kerosene (45 percent). Nearly 80 percent of the biomass comes from", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "c014fb7d-cb66-4ada-a6f2-1608a3cf26be": {"__data__": {"id_": "c014fb7d-cb66-4ada-a6f2-1608a3cf26be", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-sri-lanka", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in Sri Lanka", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-sri-lanka", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "c3df374af097638c43fbe9c873edfeea765546d67d76e18f9bde36db6339aab2"}}, "hash": "c3df374af097638c43fbe9c873edfeea765546d67d76e18f9bde36db6339aab2", "text": "non-forest resources, namely agricultural and plantation work. While 70 percent of the biomass is collected free from home gardens and plantations, 30 percent is purchased, mainly in urban areas. Figure 2 shows the typical energy use pattern in a grid-connected village. Lighting needs are met mainly by electricity either through grid-connected or off-grid supply. There are some instances of biogas use in cooking and lighting. The development and dissemination of these installations is mainly handled by a small number of NGOs. There has been some improvement in R&D activities and technology transfer through Government institutions contributing to the identification of alternative energy sources. The MoPE has identified the main barriers: investment Energy- poverty linkages are frequently overlooked in poverty reduction strategies. 11 Energy and Poverty in Sri Lanka THE CHALLENGES FIGURE 2 TYPICAL ENERGY CONSUMPTION PATTERNS IN A GRID-CONNECTED VILLAGE costs, availability of resources, and lack of popularization of marginal uses of renewable energy in Sri Lanka. Source Abeygunewardena (2005) Renewable energy supplies through wind energy, solar photovoltaic, etc. are not managed by the Government but by the private sector and NGOs. Fuelwood is not even taken into consideration. The use of energy in the form of thermal energy in rural economic activities such as in brick kilns, bakeries, and other small-scale manufacturing is also handled mainly by NGOs and CBOs; most agencies completely ignore the use of animal motive power. In the near future, the Government expects that hydro-electricity production and biomass-based energy supplies are going to increase only marginally. Much of the large-hydro potential is already developed. This also means that the country\u2019s energy needs have to be met mainly by imported fossil fuels in the medium-term. However, in the longer term, an accelerated development of non-conventional renewable energy and possible development of indigenous petroleum resources are hoped to make a significant change in Sri Lanka\u2019s mix of primary energy resources. (MoPE 2006) In the short and medium term, modern renewable energy is seen to remain out of the reach of the poorer sections of the population. In addition, the oil and gas exploration under way in Sri Lanka, in anticipation of finding reserves to meet the demand of the next 20 years, may not yield expected outcomes. Most agencies completely ignore the use of animal motive power. 12 Energy and Poverty in Sri Lanka THE CHALLENGES \u25a0 Lack of investments limits access to energy across the country. \u25a0 Poor cannot afford the high cost of electricity. \u25a0 Lack of popularization of renewable energy to enhance poverty reduction. \u25a0 Modern renewable energy is seen as the domain of the elite. \u25a0 Private initiatives towards accessing modern energy services are completely out of the reach of rural masses. BOX 4: KEY CHALLENGES TO ENERGY ACCESS Technology efficiency and fuel options Rural energy options in Sri Lanka that can be met with local resources with minimum external inputs include biomass, solar energy, micro-hydro, wind energy, biogas and waste, and dendro power. Fuelwood is used extensively in cooking and in the processing of many plantation crops, such as tea, rubber, and coconut. The annual energy potential of plantation biomass is estimated to vary from 30 to 150 peta joules (PJ) in 2010. It is projected that the total energy consumption in Sri Lanka in 2010 will be 425 PJ. Thus, the plantation biomass could supply about 7 to 32 percent of the total energy consumed in 2010. Solar cooking is not very common in Sri Lanka but solar drying is becoming very popular. Over 60,000 households have been fitted with solar photovoltaic systems of 25-50 W capacity. These SHSs generate sufficient power to meet lighting and communication needs in rural homes but the cost is particularly constraining. A survey carried out by the ECF for the MoPE has shown that while there are 161 micro-hydro units operating in Sri Lanka providing electricity for 3600 households, there are 24 units with a capacity of 385 kW not functioning due to various reasons. About 40 MW of small hydroelectric generating capacity is already in place and many similar sites are being developed. The potential of developing 250 MW of installed capacity with a plant factor of 40 percent, and an energy output of 875 GWh by 2015 is being considered practically feasible. The use of wind power for lift irrigation, which was common some years ago in the north, has now being replaced by engine- or motor- driven pump sets. Biogas plants, both continuous flow type and batch type, of 1-2 tonne capacity are popular. A few large units are installed for disposal of urban waste but most small units in", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "db1c134c-19a6-49e1-a099-4be5281ea412": {"__data__": {"id_": "db1c134c-19a6-49e1-a099-4be5281ea412", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-sri-lanka", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in Sri Lanka", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-sri-lanka", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "3ff9a5920f00ad7a2fb9493297e14e90f2ca855e09a9a439f9143dc30adce089"}}, "hash": "3ff9a5920f00ad7a2fb9493297e14e90f2ca855e09a9a439f9143dc30adce089", "text": "the villages provide for lighting and cooking needs. The use of wind power for lift irrigation has now been replaced by engine- or motor-driven pump sets. 13 Energy and Poverty in Sri Lanka THE CHALLENGES The cost of electricity used by the industrial sector in Sri Lanka is one of the highest in the region. The CEB hopes that by introducing large coal- based electricity generation capacities in Sri Lanka, the generating cost could be reduced to 4 US cents per kWh. Though this figure is subject to criticism, renewable energy projects that cost more than the figure for coal are not encouraged. During 1997-2003, the Renewable Energy and Energy Capacity- Building Project funded by the United Nations Development Programme (UNDP) and the GEF provided support to improve R&D capabilities of several institutions and promoted technology transfer and efficient energy options. This was followed by a smaller grant from 2004-2005 to promote development of efficient use of biomass energy in several industries and home-based enterprises. Studies have shown that the net potential benefit from industrial energy efficiency improvements could produce an annual generation saving of about US$45 million. However, investment barriers have hindered widespread commercialization and large-scale implementation of end-use energy-efficiency improvements. Exploring energy-based entrepreneurship Many rural activities are energy-based, and enterprises in agricultural, manufacturing and service sectors make use of energy in some form or the other. The best way to make energy a factor in reducing poverty is by co-opting the poor as partners in the process of energy supply itself. In the context of large power production, whether coal or hydro, or the supply of imported oil or gas for transport or cooking, there is very little scope for employment opportunities for the poor, let alone entrepreneurial opportunities for them. However, there is ample scope for participation at the grass-roots level particularly in terms of the small-scale energy projects. Yet, human power, biomass, and other forms of renewable energy are subsumed under the notion of progress in providing electricity to the poor. Investment barriers have hindered widespread commercialization and large- scale implementation of end-use energy- efficiency improvements. \u25a0 Ineffective policy formulation results in smaller units suffering from lack of scale economies. \u25a0 Indirect benefits of increase in indigenous knowledge and development of linkages with the community at large are ignored unless they have political undertones. BOX 5: KEY CHALLENGES TO TECHNOLOGY EFFICIENCY 14 Energy and Poverty in Sri Lanka THE CHALLENGES \u25a0 Large power production offers only limited employment opportunities to the poor, let alone entrepreneurial opportunities for them. \u25a0 The tendency to import and supply many items that could be manufactured locally has aggravated rural poverty and increased migration into urban areas in search of work in the cities. Indigenous production has suffered tremendously because of lack of markets and buyers. BOX 6: KEY CHALLENGES TO ENTREPRENEURSHIP OPPORTUNITIES The prospects for income-generating activities that can help break the cycle of poverty often rely on the availability of energy. Apropos to knowledge repositories vis-\u00e0-vis energy-poverty linkages, the Integrated Development Association (IDEA) has published training manuals, and conducted workshops in enterprises such as bakeries, brick kilns, fuelwood stoves, dehydrating food for preservation, biogas, wind generators, water pumps, and tea and tobacco drying. There has been a shift from local manufacturing to more imports from the region to meet industrial needs. The manufacturing of wind turbines for pumping water, a project undertaken by the WRB had come to a halt with the installation of 200 units, which have gone into disuse. Problems encountered in operation and maintenance of these units are reported but there is no central policy or body to address these issues. Highlighting the importance of rural finance through microcredit Poverty is an overwhelmingly rural problem in Sri Lanka. Roughly 88 percent of the poor live in rural areas, which suffer from underemployment, slow growth in agricultural productivity, lack of integration with the mainstream economy, unclear land tenure, and limited access to basic services and infrastructure. The Government\u2019s economic reform programme highlights the role of rural finance in empowering the poor, especially women, and emphasizes the sustainability of rural finance institutions and their integration with the financial sector. According to the Asian Development Bank (ADB) report on commercialization of microfinance in Sri Lanka (ADB 2002), the microfinance industry in Sri Lanka is at a fairly early stage of commercialization. 15 Energy and Poverty in Sri Lanka THE CHALLENGES Organizations based on the cooperative model, such as Cooperative Rural Banks (CRBs), Thrift and Credit Cooperative Societies (TCCSs), and some NGOs offering microfinance have made progress towards commercialization, although the performance of individual institutions within each of", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "5243f5a1-d216-408e-be6c-fbb8053aff87": {"__data__": {"id_": "5243f5a1-d216-408e-be6c-fbb8053aff87", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-sri-lanka", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in Sri Lanka", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-sri-lanka", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "2b77e7469e25e0f5fc22f16be52f299dfdc9219f2d9ed295500b44d7fc437152"}, "3": {"node_id": "a9f3af3c-0887-4274-8f47-95fe75fbe8ea", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-sri-lanka", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "c184a9ffbecd930d94e3d836f94edd0e2a6113346