. A few notable exceptions such as the Hatton National Bank \u2013 with the far-reaching Gami Pubuduwa (Village Reawakening) initiative, which deals with decentralization of microfinance at the village level \u2013 and the Seylan Bank and Sampath Bank exist with a combined number of outstanding microloans covered only 1.2 percent of the industry total at the end of 2000. MFIs rely heavily on savings mobilization to fund their loan portfolios, indicating a fairly high level of commercialization in terms of access to funding sources. The involvement of commercial banks in the provision of microfinance is limited. 16 Energy and Poverty in Sri Lanka THE CHALLENGES Government policies, interventions, and legal and regulatory frameworks discourage new entrants into microfinance and hinder the commercialization of existing MFIs. Microfinance cooperatives \u2013 the largest suppliers of microcredit as well as significant savings \u2013 are not adequately regulated and supervised. Many MFIs suffer from weak governance, lack of clarity in their mission, low levels of understanding of banking and finance, inappropriate accounting practices, and inadequate management information systems. As of now, there is no specific reference to energy or data available on energy-related microfinance, except in the context of the ESD credit programme that promoted financing through banks and microfinance institutions for private sector provision of on- and off-grid renewable energy services. Commercial financing for renewable energy was almost non-existent prior to 1997. The ESD project (1997-2002), funded by the World Bank and the GEF, promoted commercial financing of private sector renewable energy services in grid-connected mini hydro, community- based off-grid village hydro, and SHSs. The RERED project (2002-2007) includes financing of private-sector-owned grid-connected power plants, community-owned off-grid schemes, SHSs, energy efficiency and demand-side management, cross-sectoral energy applications, and technical assistance. Furthermore, the Global Environment Facility/Small Grants Programme (GEF/SGP) \u2013 with a total fund of US$3.5 million (1995- 2006) and 218 projects under biodiversity, climate change, network building and other multi-focus schemes \u2013 has completed three phases of its funding and the fourth phase is planned for 2006-2010. The project has supported a number of initiatives addressing the energy needs of the poor, such as the kitchen stove and the fuelwood plantation programme. It has also been active in promoting small wind generating units made locally, micro-hydro and SHSs to meet rural electricity needs. Microfinance cooperatives are not adequately regulated and supervised. \u25a0 Government policies, interventions, and legal and regulatory frameworks discourage new entrants into microfinance and hinder the commercialization of existing MFIs.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "a9f3af3c-0887-4274-8f47-95fe75fbe8ea": {"__data__": {"id_": "a9f3af3c-0887-4274-8f47-95fe75fbe8ea", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-sri-lanka", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in Sri Lanka", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-sri-lanka", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "2b77e7469e25e0f5fc22f16be52f299dfdc9219f2d9ed295500b44d7fc437152"}, "2": {"node_id": "5243f5a1-d216-408e-be6c-fbb8053aff87", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": 