4a958e5bd0e4ef1e8ae88ad3401eb3d417e786076184d0270534964378235", "text": "sheds, fetching water for drinking and washing take up all their time. A study done by ITDG Sri Lanka shows that 75 percent of the energy requirement for cooking in households can be supplied by their household biogas units. These women and girls, on average, save 2 to 2.5 hours per day when cooking with gas. Most of them (79 percent) use this time for some income earning activities in which they earn the equivalent of 24 percent of their monthly income. Women in the households who raise animals have expressed their satisfaction with biogas units because it reduces their time in disposal of animal waste. Previously, they collected animal waste and disposed of it far away from the sheds, which was a time consuming and tiresome activity. Now the animal waste is being diverted to the nearby biogas units with minimum effort. In addition to the time saving, households using biogas have gained fairly high social status in the villages. The study has also shown that 30 percent of the households who own a biogas unit had earlier used kerosene lamps. Eighty-two percent of them were using bottle lamps which pose severe fire hazards. Also, the very high bio fertilizer value of the slurry is an important determinant in adopting the biogas technology. It can help to reduce the fertilizer budget of the farmer significantly. While energy and fertilizer remain the main uses of biogas at household level, it is being increasingly recognized as a waste disposal technology by the local government authorities for whom garbage is a severe environmental problem. However, women\u2019s participation in capacity development initiatives relating to different energy services is limited, even though there clearly is potential for that. Technical training and discussions pertaining to energy supply are mostly done with men though the main energy users in the rural sector are women. Gender considerations tend to be left out in the energy planning and programming stage. Consequently, gender- and energy-related monitoring and evaluation at the project level tends to be weak, unless more emphasis is directed at the issue. Women's participation in capacity development initiatives relating to different energy sources is limited, even though there clearly is potential for that. 18 Energy and Poverty in Sri Lanka THE CHALLENGES Limited monitoring and evaluation system To assess the relationship between energy and poverty programmes directed towards poverty reduction and livelihood improvement through access to energy, it is important that these programmes are monitored and evaluated regularly. Monitoring and evaluation (M&E) of government activities in Sri Lanka has been almost non-existent, and policy implementation has been hampered by indecision. A number of parallel systems have been set up \u2013 including the budget monitoring system of the External Resources Department under the Ministry of Finance and Planning (MoFP) and, as a response to the insurgent of resources for post-tsunami activities, the Government initiative, known as the Development Assistance Database with the support of UNDP \u2013 to improve the monitoring of the use of financial resources and achievement of results. The newly established Ministry of Plan Implementation (MoPI) will set up an M&E system as part of the National Operations Room with cells at different ministries for governmental and non-governmental activities in Sri Lanka. Donor-funded projects are monitored periodically and extensions depend heavily on performance. The ESD project was extended to RERED mainly due to the excellent performance shown in the first phase. The GEF/SGP projects are also monitored by a steering committee, which evaluates proposals and checks progress. Planners hope to reduce poverty by increasing the consumption of electrical energy. Rural energy use, in the form of thermal heat from biomass and motive power from draft animals, is not included in the assessments. \u25a0 When it comes to energy-related programmes, the gender bias is apparent, particularly in capacity-building programmes, even though positive examples exist, such as introduction of biogas. \u25a0 Technical training and discussions pertaining to energy supply are mostly done with men though the main energy users in the rural sector are women. \u25a0 Capacity development should not be seen only in the narrow project specific capacities. \u25a0 Lack of gender considerations in energy plans and programmes, and weak gender- and energy-related M&E. BOX 8: KEY CHALLENGES TO GENDER CONCERNS 19 Energy and Poverty in Sri Lanka THE CHALLENGES In the absence of a broader perspective, success stories such as photovoltaic electricity provided to over 60,000 houses may not indicate any economic benefit. Baseline surveys to assess socio-economic benefits indicating pre-programme status are absent. Basic energy needs, such as cooking and lighting, are not reckoned in most evaluations, leading to distorted results. Incomplete and", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "62575275-3dd5-4859-88c7-f9c4ad6d4da2": {"__data__": {"id_": "62575275-3dd5-4859-88c7-f9c4ad6d4da2", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-sri-lanka", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in Sri Lanka", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-sri-lanka", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "9ee8949278a572cb45ff725816462361155b0ee52b415b4386389e52a217615d"}}, "hash": "9ee8949278a572cb45ff725816462361155b0ee52b415b4386389e52a217615d", "text": "inadequate access to information Access to information is not only erratic but also incomplete. Analysed data on energy consumption in different strata of society is not available. Further, data on the vital forms of energy that drive the rural economy and domestic chores such as cooking and grinding through thermal and motive power are not systematically recorded. The main medium of communication in the rural sector remains wireless broadcasts such as the Mahaweli Community Radio started in 1981 and Kotmale Community Radio Internet Project in 1991. The latter was set up with the assistance of the United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization (UNESCO) and the Danish International Development Agency (DANIDA) as the lack of electricity and buying power keeps people from investing in other forms of communication. Stations in Mahalluppalama, Giraduru Kotte, Kotmale, and Pollonnaruwa cater to new settlements, while the Mahaweli Community Radio and other such radio services concentrate on rural farm activities but lack development communication strategies. Also the poor regions in provinces such as Uva are not served by the network. Currently, no knowledge-sharing partnership is evident except in NGO networks that specialize in specific areas such as organic farming, Basic energy needs, such as cooking and lighting, are not reckoned in most evaluations, leading to distorted results. \u25a0 Lack of regular M&E of energy programmes and projects beyond donor-funded projects, and particularly pertaining to poverty reduction and livelihoods improvement. \u25a0 The emphasis has always been on electricity as the main focus of any energy-related assessment. Rural energy use in the form of biomass, motive power, and renewable sources has been kept out of any policy analysis tasks carried out by government departments as well as concerned NGOs. \u25a0 Lack of baseline studies to assess socio-economic benefits. BOX 9: KEY CHALLENGES TO MONITORING AND EVALUATION 20 Energy and Poverty in Sri Lanka MEETING THE CHALLENGES rainwater harvesting, and indigenous knowledge. The energy-poverty linkage is completely neglected. Most of the information available is in English and in text form. MEETING THE CHALLENGES S Institutional framework for ensuring an energy-efficient future ri Lanka requires a committed effort towards regulation of its existing energy sources and provision of price subsidies for the poor. Institutional bodies need to be set up for this purpose and some headway has already been made in this direction. PUCSL, established under the Public Utilities Commission Act, does not currently only regulate the electricity and petroleum industries, but it also regulates other utilities such as water service as well. PUCSL will have authority to execute regulation only when the individual industry legislations are enacted and made effective. In addition to the regulatory arrangement, the energy utilities need to be further strengthened to enhance their financial viability and service quality (MoPE 2006). The Government could also take the leadership to bring about the required institutional changes and capacities that enable decentralized decision-making. Issues relating to sustainable energy technologies are mostly dealt with at the microlevel, and therefore, could be addressed well only at a decentralized level. Furthermore, only rural decentralized energy plans could address the realities of the energy requirements for sustainable livelihoods activities covering cooking, lighting, domestic and rural industries which generate or save income. The utility of alternative sources of energy has already been recognized in the island nation. PUCSL and the recently operationalized SEA have been assigned the responsibility to implement the NCRE strategy and to achieve targets (MoPE 2006). Ensuring improved \u25a0 Integrating modern global developments into the rural tradition is one of the biggest challenges facing Sri Lanka today. Information and communication technology projects remain largely insensitive to socio-anthropological dimensions. \u25a0 Limited accessibility to information and partnerships for knowledge- sharing. BOX 10: KEY CHALLENGES TO ACCESS TO INFORMATION 21 Energy and Poverty in Sri Lanka MEETING THE CHALLENGES institutional and technical capacities among key renewable energy development bodies is under way. A project for capacity-building of SEA has been proposed and planned with ADB assistance. The aim is to improve institutional and technical capacities including renewable energy portfolio management capacities. These include identification, assessment, documentation and inventorying of all renewable energy resources and provision of quality information for project developers. In addition, the aim is to enable the creation of an encouraging environment for renewable energy generation in Sri Lanka, in terms of relevant policies, integrated resource planning and financial incentives (ADB 2007). Also other institutions are active in the field of alternative energy sources. The NERD Centre has been assigned R&D work on solar, wind and biomass energy options for small-scale use. Several NGOs such as IDEA, Bio-Energy Association of Sri Lanka (BEASL), and ITDG are working on", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "8d9f07a9-0247-4aac-bc12-864184fa9231": {"__data__": {"id_": "8d9f07a9-0247-4aac-bc12-864184fa9231", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-sri-lanka", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "exclu