ers. Government energy sector plans also identify rural households as important stakeholders in the process of building capacities toward greater integration of energy access for poverty reduction in the development process. Policy and regulatory framework The primary objective of any policy framework that addresses the energy- poverty interface must be the concomitant reduction of poverty and the The aim is to enable the creation of an encouraging environment for renewable energy generation in Sri Lanka. 22 Energy and Poverty in Sri Lanka MEETING THE CHALLENGES maximization of environmental benefits. It is encouraging that the Sri Lanka Rural Electrification Policy 2002 identifies as its key goals maximizing the economic, social, and environmental benefits of rural electrification as well as the leveraging of government resources through the participation of the private sector and the rural society. NEPS 2006 identifies broadly how the energy sector policies can be implemented. These include the enhancement of existing biomass resources, diversification of fuels used in electricity and transport sectors, and implementation of energy efficiency and conservation measures. In addition, it emphasizes the development of indigenous energy sources, in particular, NCRE sources. Certain NCRE technologies require incentives to ensure their up-scaling and contribution to the national NCRE target. These incentives are planned to be technology-specific, based on actual energy generation supplied to the grid, provided on a competitive basis and made available through the Energy Fund. Furthermore, NEPS 2006 stresses regulating the energy sector, including electricity and petroleum sub-sectors, to ensure an effective implementation of pricing policy among other issues (see Table 4). The recent operationalization of SEA and its mandate is in line with the overall strategy to promote clean energy development, energy efficiency improvement and conservation in Sri Lanka. TABLE 2 BROAD BASED IMPLEMENTATION STRATEGIES FOR THE ENERGY SECTOR POLICIES Element Strategies Providing Basic Energy Needs 1.1 Enhance existing biomass resources. 1.2 Improve rural access to commercial forms of energy and develop action plan for implementation. 1.3 Promote energy plantations. 1.4 Target with subsidies, lifeline tariffs. Ensuring Energy Security 2.1 Promote biomass as a modern energy source. 2.2 Diversify fuels used in electricity generation and transport sectors through appropriate technologies with special emphasis on biofuel R&D. 2.3 Enhance regional cooperation, local refining capacities and maintain strategic fuel reserves. Promoting Energy Efficiency and Conservation 3.1 Provide financial and other incentives/ disincentives for achieving supply-side and end-use energy efficiency. 3.2 Formulate long-term funding and awareness raising programmes. 3.3 Ensure dissemination of efficient equipment such as improved cooking stoves, and formulate strategic plans for street lightning. 3.4 Optimize exiting energy generation systems and distribution networks. 3.4 Shift toward less energy intensive transport modes. 23 Energy and Poverty in Sri Lanka MEETING THE CHALLENGES TABLE 2 BROAD BASED IMPLEMENTATION STRATEGIES FOR THE ENERGY SECTOR POLICIES (CONT\u2019D) Source MoPE (2006) Element Strategies Promoting Indigenous Resources 4.1 Promote the use of non-conventional renewable energy resources, seek concessionary financing and \u2018green\u2019 funding, including Clean Development Mechanism (CDM) for appropriate projects. Develop biomass-based projects where land resources/ biomass waste are available, with emphasis on rural income generation. 4.2 Support R&D on adopting new technologies and practices to suit local conditions. Adopting an Appropriate Pricing Policy 5.1 Regulate the energy sector, including electricity and petroleum sub-sectors, to ensure effective implementation of the pricing policy. 5.2 Formulate and update appropriate strategies.", "start_char_idx