policies, a mechanism needs to be evolved to regulate it. A system of giving a notional value to traditional biomass (e.g. fuelwood used in the informal sector) to arrive at meaningful energy policies could be developed. The policy advocacy role to be played by the CBOs and civil society is to expand the debate on energy to go beyond electricity. The planners must be asked to take into account the non-formal sector into their reckoning in energy planning. A mechanism needs to be evolved to regulate traditional biomass. 24 Energy and Poverty in Sri Lanka MEETING THE CHALLENGES Improving livelihoods through dendro thermal initiatives under the energy programme framework In order to arrive at an integrated approach to technology and infrastructure development in the rural areas, energy supply based on biomass, animal power, and alternative sources should be captured in the policy and programme framework. Coordinated efforts and action are needed to bring all these plans to fruition. The development of relevant energy technologies, local capacities and the technology base should be strengthened. The Government envisages the implementation of a programme based on the proposed dendro thermal initiative that helps the poor establish livelihoods through energy supply. The policy also provides for a necessary framework to ensure that all electricity suppliers to rural consumers can compete on equal terms. Subsidies are also to be made available to all parties interested in rural electrification on a competitive basis. The programme also allows for a tariff regime that enables cost recovery at a reasonable return on investment, particularly in isolated mini-grid systems in rural areas accepting the principle of differential pricing. A subsidy mechanism for rural electrification based on the principles of economic efficiency, transparency, and social equity will be established to support rural electrification programmes. Financing for these subsidies is to be facilitated through government and donor assistance. Cultivation of fuelwood to meet the energy needs of rural people, and at the same time meeting soil fertility build up by using nitrogen fixing species, has been promoted by the Coconut Cultivation Board and the Tea Research Institute, in collaboration with the BEASL. Quite recently, the Government has recognized the need to grow fuelwood and has declared a nitrogen-fixing fast growing tree (Gliricidia sepium) as a plantation crop. The development of dendro power in Sri Lanka is primarily through actions taken by the AED. Twelve trial plots were established at different locations in the country to determine the optimum parameters for sustainable energy plantations. Coppice Gliricidia wood was used to demonstrate the feasibility of electricity generation and industrial heat applications. A model is being developed by the AED where an area of 1 hectare of Gliricidia energy plantation with six cows is assigned to a family for improving livelihoods through energy services. Branch coppice wood systematically harvested from the energy plantations is sold to energy conversion facilities. Foliage from these branches is mixed with rice straw and fed to cows. Milk from the cows is sold to the dairy processing industry. Dung from the cows is digested to generate biogas The development of relevant energy technologies, local capacities and the technology base should be strengthened. 25 Energy and Poverty in Sri Lanka MEETING THE CHALLENGES and effluent from the digesters is used as organic fertilizer replacing imported chemical fertilizer. Biogas is used as cooking fuel or for off-grid electricity generation. Small wind generators are being manufactured locally in Sri Lanka as an outcome of the programmes and schemes implemented by the ITDG, which has already introduced bicycle transport and improved stoves over several years. Rural people are being trained to install the stoves and build chimneys by the IDEA. Biogas digesters \u2013 both continuous type and batch type \u2013 are now prepared at the village level. The NERD Centre has been working on gasifiers", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "901f54b4-efa9-4c88-a1e0-03c46c7e543d": {"__data__": {"id_": "901f54b4-efa9-4c88-a1e0-03c46c7e543d", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-sri-lanka", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in Sri Lanka", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-sri-lanka", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "d3fdf7eaa1d7119c1fd85e6b6f8e6c57d6312d6c164f75e84238e14b0233c220"}}, "hash": "d3fdf7eaa1d7119c1fd85e6b6f8e6c57d6312d6c164f75e84238e14b0233c220", "text": "for industrial use from the 1980s and has developed multiple design applications for different uses. It has also developed efficient wood stoves for domestic application. Ensuring greater access to modern energy for poverty reduction and renewable sources of energy Expansion of access to electricity and petroleum-based fuels in rural areas remains as a priority intervention for poverty reduction in Sri Lanka. The NEPS of Sri Lanka 2006 provides for capital subsidies that have been available for grid-connected households to be extended to households seeking off-grid electricity technologies. It also provides for targeted subsidies for household use of electricity and kerosene. These are targeted at low-income groups (i.e. all Samurdhi beneficiary families in on-grid, off-grid or non-electrified, low-income households). The subsidies will be provided from the savings accrued via elimination of cross-subsidies in electricity tariff. Coupons will be issued to, for example, cover fifty percent of the cost of on-grid electricity supply of the first 30 kWh, or coupons of the same value to pay off the cost of off-grid electricity or the cost of kerosene. The institutional responsibility to prepare and implement the plans has been assigned to PUCSL. Communities need access to a range of energy sources to satisfy their energy service needs in different sectors within the community \u2013 households, schools, medical centres, micro-enterprise development, transport, communication, agriculture, etc. These energy needs of the whole community and their linkage to different sectors need to be well understood and considered in energy planning in order to respond to the energy demands with more efficiency and cost-effectiveness. Even though a beginning has been made, there remain a vast number of renewable resources that need to be tapped to tide over the energy crisis and reduce rural poverty. The use of animal power, abundantly available in Sri Lanka, should also be seen as an energy issue and policies must address the issues of grazing land, access to water, etc. in meeting this need. Communities need access to a range of energy sources to satisfy their energy service needs in different sectors within the community. 26 Energy and Poverty in Sri Lanka MEETING THE CHALLENGES A regulatory arrangement is needed to integrate development work in the renewable energy sector. The barriers for funding renewable energy projects need to be removed in order to scale up good initiatives. A strengthened microfinance sector can provide part of the solution. Several initiatives have been in progress in recent years. IDEA has developed large-scale wood burning stoves (Amarasekera 2005) and also introduced paddy-husk burning bakery ovens and brick kilns successfully. The NERD Centre has developed a smoke-free wood stove and energy- efficient gasifiers for small and medium enterprises. Such initiatives must be promoted, encouraged and supported. The former ECF already had certain poverty reduction and energy efficiency projects in the pipeline. Resource assessment such as solar, wind, and hydro mapping by the United States Agency for International Development (USAID) have been conducted. Documents such as the Renewable Energy Policy Compendium, prepared with USAID assistance, and a policy framework for renewable resources-based electricity generation under the RERED project have been developed. Also an Energy Sector Master Plan, with ADB assistance, has been developed and earmarked for implementation. In addition, a National Energy Planning Committee has been appointed and a Renewable Energy Cell has been set up. New improved energy technologies The introduction of the concept of endogenous development based on technology that could be handled from within is the need of the hour. New improved small-scale energy technologies are already in development. A labour-intensive technology such as dendro seems feasible. Apart from meeting fodder and soil fertility needs by growing suitable energy plants as an intercrop with existing farming, technology links to the community are easily established. The BEASL has introduced dendro power as a viable option for village energy supply and sustenance of rural activities. The NERD Centre has been engaged in developing several renewable energy technologies associated with solar, wind, and biomass and has successfully introduced a batch type digester for paddy straw and developed several gasifiers for different uses. IDEA, the national focal point of the Asia Regional Cook Stove Programme and the International Network for Sustainable Energy (INFORSE), is engaged in capacity- building of NGOs in promoting efficient wood stoves (IDEA 2005). The Energy Forum is involved in off-grid power generation and implements promotional strategies for renewable energy technologies supported by 27 Energy and Poverty in Sri Lanka MEETING THE CHALLENGES the Asia Pro Eco of the European Community. The ITDG, with its partner organization Intermediate Technology now known as Knowledge Solvers, is involved in the area of small wind energy", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "3745a7b9-821f-4b19-aa39-a73c5ec633d7": {"__data__": {"id_": "3745a7b9-821f-4b19-aa39-a73c5ec633d7", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-sri-lanka", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in Sri Lanka", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-sri-lanka", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "cd12cebfe48b6b435d9e23af0bae79cd8716d315f0b1d94eb4cd59be36a48af3"}}, "hash": "cd12cebfe48b6b435d9e23af0bae79cd8716d315f0b1d94eb4cd59be36a48af3", "text": "and alternate systems of transport, among several other sustainable energy projects. Besides recommending setting up an agency to act as a repository of knowledge for renewable energy, the IMWCDTT suggested that energy research activities should be coordinated by the proposed agency through an information hub. Information exchanged among stakeholders should be used to manage a national R&D programme on energy in association with the National Science Foundation. Priorities for R&D could be determined at the national symposium, an annual event designed to identify research needs and to monitor progress on ongoing research (IMWCDTT 2005). Energy-based entrepreneurial opportunities Provision of newer and better entrepreneurial opportunities is a challenge that the Sri Lankan policy makers must attempt to overcome. A few initiatives are already in place but much more needs to be done. New technologies suitable for renewable sources, including small applications, are being developed and locally manufactured. As an example, the Organic Rankin Cycle Engines are designed to use any fuel, or direct solar, through concentrators. More promising initiatives should be taken up as national projects and be promoted in a sustainable manner by giving proper recognition and incentives to such programmes. More importance must also be given to disseminating knowledge and imparting maintenance and operating skills at the village level to prevent dependence on external inputs. This will also help evolve a viable technology base in the villages that will sustain other technology needs of the poor. The SARI\u2019s Small Grants Programme for Energy Corporation and Development has granted US$250,000 to the Energy Forum and SLEMA for establishing standards and prices for delivering clean, reliable, and affordable energy to rural families. The Energy Forum has been entrusted with the task of establishing and maintaining standards related to micro- hydro to ensure the effectiveness and sustainability of the system, in the process putting forth a \u2018National Micro-Hydro Standard\u2019. SLEMA would work on electricity pricing in the region granting subsidies to different consumer classes taking into account financial, social and political issues with respect to electricity pricing. A team of experts has prepared a business proposal, which encourages the establishment of a commercial-scale, biomass-based electricity More importance must also be given to disseminating knowledge and skills at the village level to prevent dependence on external inputs. 28 Energy and Poverty in Sri Lanka MEETING THE CHALLENGES generating facility located in a rural area and operated by the private sector. This project also incorporates Clean Development Mechanism (CDM) aspects with a view to implement a CDM project in Sri Lanka for the biomass sector. The ADB-prepared pre-feasibility study has been submitted to the MoPE for implementation by an appropriate private sector institution. The NEPS of Sri Lanka 2006 suggests that Sri Lanka\u2019s non-conventional renewable energy resources could be developed also under the CDM. Therefore, there is potential for carbon finance in appropriate projects such as biomass-based projects where land resources and biomass waste are available, with emphasis on rural income generation. Microcredit: the answer to the problem of financial access The microfinance sector should be strengthened to promote investment in rural areas. Policy changes that emphasize good governance and improved operations of rural finance institutions need to be promoted. If microcredit to help meet the poor\u2019s energy needs is to be promoted, a separate database on credit extended to various energy projects must be maintained. This will allow the planners to locate gaps and suggest incentives needed to promote investment in providing energy supplies and energy-based enterprises. As energy to the poor is bracketed in the informal sector, microcredit institutes would fail to take initiatives unless some inducement is built in at the policy level. The ADB is helping establish a more sustainable rural finance system in Sri Lanka through a loan package totalling US$70 million. The Rural Finance Sector Development Programme aims to revive the rural economy and promote private-sector-led economic growth. Greater attention to gender issues The introduction of biogas can be highlighted as a good example, since it can make a positive difference to women\u2019s lives. It can reduce the time women spend in the collection of firewood and in the kitchen cooking and cleaning utensils and enhance their income-generating activities. Therefore, the labour spent in collecting firewood, tending to livestock, gathering fodder, etc., needs to be taken into account in the planning processes. Furthermore, ensuring the involvement of women in the process of selection, implementation and running of most schemes delivering energy is necessary. Women should be able to participate in capacity development initiatives relating to different energy services. Changes in societal Policy changes that emphasize good governance and improved operations of rural finance institutions need to", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "99a377dd-ff81-4f66-85c4-be4a7ae8f78a": {"__data__": {"id_": "99a377dd-ff81-4f66-85c4-be4a7ae8f78a", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-sri-lanka", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in Sri Lanka", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-sri-lanka", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "1cf96c920412fe482e96d0221a0dc276b4f52ec53d6e05f06c2efbaa55be22ea"}}, "hash": "1cf96c920412fe482e96d0221a0dc276b4f52ec53d6e05f06c2efbaa55be22ea", "text": "be promoted. 29 Energy and Poverty in Sri Lanka MEETING THE CHALLENGES attitudes towards women, work and capacity-building are therefore necessary and should start at very early stages of project formulations and also at school educational levels. Capacity-building for general capacities that could be transferred to other development projects, and for example, information and communication technology (ICT) and other technical training, would benefit women since they have not been encouraged to participate widely before. In view of the fact that women tend to be left out of energy plans and programmes, the aspects raised in the Gender and Energy Tool Kit issued by the UNDP and questions and issues such as the impact of project evaluation on gender issues and identification of gender gaps and gender-related project successes could be made part of the overall M&E structure. Developing a more holistic monitoring and evaluation system The way ahead includes eradicating extreme poverty and hunger through income-generating opportunities; achieving universal primary education; promoting gender equality; improving health by reducing indoor air pollution; increasing access to clean/pumped water; ensuring environmental sustainability through preservation of forest land; and reclaiming eroded agricultural land. There is a need for more balanced and regular energy-related assessments, particularly of the government energy programmes. The M&E processes at institutional and cross-institutional levels should be improved and the existing parallel systems should be linked to capture small-scale initiatives at the local levels. It could also be beneficial to include the traditional rural energy use, in the form of thermal heat from biomass and motive power from draft animals, to the assessments since it remains as a good indicator of rural economic activity. Also, if the programme and project goals are set in collaboration with the participants, then new outcomes and benefits could be assessed in the light of changing situations. This becomes more crucial when poverty and energy are linked as the definition of poverty based on income or consumption may differ widely from one rural setting to another depending on the natural resource base they possess. Besides economic measures, other important aspects such as education, health, environmental sustainability and gender equality need to be assessed. Basic energy needs such as cooking and lighting and labour spent on, for example collecting firewood, need to be included in the assessments. The setting up of a repository of knowledge on the The M&E processes at institutional and cross- institutional levels should be improved and the existing parallel systems should be linked to capture small- scale initiatives at local levels. 30 Energy and Poverty in Sri Lanka CONCLUSION CONCLUSION T energy-poverty linkages and all related aspects must be undertaken on a priority basis in order to have meaningful M&E of projects. This would, at least supply the baseline data to evaluate future project outcomes. Harnessing modern technology for information gathering Information gathering and dissemination are key to an energy-efficient future with poverty reduction as a major challenge. Partnerships with the private sector and the civil society are needed to help bridge the gaps. The media needs to be effectively harnessed for proper information gathering and dissemination. An effective participatory medium must replace the existing government-controlled community radio service and other forms of media that are commercially controlled. Radio has been found wanting in promoting an effective participatory communication system due to one-way communication, an inherent lacunae. Policy changes might be needed to address the issue of telecommunication tariffs. The presentation of the material in the vernacular and in more user-friendly interactive modes is essential to help people access the information. Gamata Taakshanaya (Technology to Village), a programme launched by the Government, hopes to establish computer-linked centres in each of the 320 Divisional Secretary areas, and establish Science and Technology Societies at the village level. Regarding the enhancement of the much-needed infrastructure and human capacity, Sri Lanka will have to look for assistance from the International Telecommunication Union and the Asia Pacific Telecommunity. Wireless technologies can enable villagers to access the network at their local temple, school, or Ayurvedic practitioner\u2019s office. This final stage of ICT delivery to the user is referred to as the \u2018last mile\u2019. Radio and ICTs should be used to improve the delivery of and access to basic information on energy and also on services such as health and education. In particular, they should serve as a tool for empowerment of women and children living in rural areas, and to increase transparency, accountability and effectiveness of governments and civil societies. he demand for energy in Sri Lanka has increased over the years and energy-poverty linkages have been mainly neglected. Unless sustainable energy services delivery mechanisms recover costs", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "704e3204-0f24-4a90-877a-2cc3f87bc953": {"__data__": {"id_": "704e3204-0f24-4a90-877a-2cc3f87bc953", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-sri-lanka", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in Sri Lanka", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-sri-lanka", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "34d16c8d2a61c08ada0c5b9c30f5a29d144acf7389ea7f9f4936f1a71825e880"}}, "hash": "34d16c8d2a61c08ada0c5b9c30f5a29d144acf7389ea7f9f4936f1a71825e880", "text": "and engender economic development, currently underserved rural communities will find it difficult to move forward from the current economic status. More work is required in recognizing the potential and Radio and ICT should be used to improve the delivery of and access to basic information on energy. 31 Energy and Poverty in Sri Lanka CONCLUSION developing all forms of energy in both the formal and informal sectors of the economy that will bring forth the link between energy and poverty. Improved data and analysis to reflect the differing needs of men and women is essential in order to ensure fair delivery of energy services. It is essential that Sri Lanka explores ways of improving the efficiency of energy use and addresses barriers for the slow growth in adopting renewable and cleaner energy sources. The Government should take the leadership to bring about the required policy and institutional changes, including encouraging decentralized decision-making, continuing to leverage resources and creating effective partnerships to build the foundation necessary for efficient delivery of energy services to reduce poverty. 32 SCHEMATIC REPRESENTATION OF CHALLENGES AND MODALITIES TO MEET THE CHALLENGES THE CHALLENGES MEETING THE CHALLENGES Energy policy and regulatory framework focuses on the development and provision of electrical energy; While biomass remains an important source for meeting rural energy needs, there is no special provision to support, control or regulate it Despite the energy policy, electricity costs in Sri Lanka are high The key issues facing the Government include developing a cost-effective electricity tariff setting, directing targeted subsidies and improving the quality of energy services Institutional Structure Policy and Regulatory Framework Provincial energy ministries have limited influence on rural energy planning although they are in better position to assess the needs The institutional arrangement focuses mainly on electricity and fossil fuel based energy development, including in the rural context All significant energy sources need to be included under the regulatory framework Limited coordination and capacities across sectors and stakeholders A regulatory structure is in place for all physical infrasructure sectors, although currently covers electricity, petroleum and water service; The energy utilities need to be further strengthened to enhance their financial viability and service quality Renewable energy sector development mechanisms also need to be evolved and placed within the institutional arrangements The Government should take the leadership necessary to bring about the required institutional changes that enable decentralized decision-making Rural decentralized energy plans could address the realities of the energy requirements for sustainable livelihoods activities Enhance and sustain capacities of provincial energy planners to enable them to contribute to rural energy and off-grid electricity development The cross-sectoral capacity- building initiatives have identified institutions such as the National Council for Economic Development, SEMA, the Administrative Reforms Committee and the National Procurement Agency that can enhance coordination and capacities in relevant areas Build linkages between the private and state sectors in developing national economic plans; Facilitate and manage strategic enterprises; Promote institutional reforms in the public sector; Oversee procurement monitoring, capacity-building, and other policy-related matters Develop a system of giving a notional value to traditional biomass (e.g. fuelwood) used in the informal sector to arrive at meaningful energy policy The policy advocacy role of CBOs and civil society should be to expand the debate on energy to go beyond electricity The planners must be asked to take into account the non-formal sector when engaging in energy planning Regulate the energy sector, including electricity and petroleum subsectors, to ensure effective implementation of the pricing policy Formulate and update appropriate strategies and ensure that the optimal energy supply expansion plans are implemented in time Develop a mechanism for identifying target groups Develop a framework based on the principles of economic efficiency, transparency and social equity to make a cost- effective tariff regime that enables cost recovery at a reasonable return on investment and targeted subsidies Permit reasonable increases in allowed returns to the utilities in order to encourage enhanced quality Ensure energy sector utilities comply with safety and environmental standards 33 THE CHALLENGES MEETING THE CHALLENGES Programme Framework Limited emphasis on energy programmes that also focus on improving the livelihoods of the poor Lack of a balanced energy and poverty programme framework, and renewable energy programmes are mainly driven by external agencies Coordinated efforts and action is necessary in order to bring the plans to fruition Rural energy supply based on biomass, animal power and alternative sources should receive more attention in the policy and programme framework Strenghten development of relevant energy technologies while building local capacities and the technology base Implementation of a programme that helps the poor establish livelihoods through energy supply by the proposed dendro", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "06402249-aa48-4bb5-bfeb-6eb828d0a522": {"__data__": {"id_": "06402249-aa48-4bb5-bfeb-6eb828d0a522", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-sri-lanka", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in Sri Lanka", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-sri-lanka", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "ada744cabd5d99dcc0760d710c0bc8232da74cbbb26ee553a5adb3425f31fade"}}, "hash": "ada744cabd5d99dcc0760d710c0bc8232da74cbbb26ee553a5adb3425f31fade", "text": "thermal initiatives A model is being developed by AED in which an area of 1 hectare of Gliricidia energy plantation with six cows is assigned to a family for improving livelihoods through energy services The AED model encourages families to: 1)Harvest wood and mixed foliage from the energy plantations to sell to energy conversion facilities and to feed cows, respectively; 2)Sell milk from the cows to the dairy processing industry; 3) Generate biogas and use effluent as organic fertilizer; 4) Use biogas as cooking fuel or for off-grid electricity generation 34 SCHEMATIC REPRESENTATION OF CHALLENGES AND MODALITIES TO MEET THE CHALLENGES (CONTINUED...) THE CHALLENGES MEETING THE CHALLENGES Access Issues Lack of popularization of renewable energy and of further development to enhance poverty reduction Poor families cannot afford the high cost of electricity Lack of investments is the prime obstacle in access to energy across the country; At commercial rates of borrowing, renewable energy cannot compete with conventional resources Indirect benefits of an increase in indigenous knowledge and development of linkages with the community at large are ignored unless they have political undertones Large power production offers only limited employment opportunities to the poor, let alone entrepreneurial opportunities for them Energy efficient solutions are not recognized and promoted adequately; in particular, smaller units suffer from lack of scale economies Limited accessibility to information and partnerships for knowledge sharing Capital subsidies that have been available for grid- connected households are to be extended to households seeking off-grid electricity technologies Energy needs of communities and their linkage to different sectors need to be well understood and considered in energy planning in order to respond to energy demands with more efficiency and cost-effectiveness The microfinance sector should be strengthened to promote investment in rural areas Create targeted subsidies for household use of electricity and kerosene Targeted at low-income groups (i.e. all Samurdhi beneficiary families) in on-grid, off-grid or non- electrified, low-income households The subsidies will be generated from the savings accrued via elimination of cross-subsidies in electricity tariff Vast unused renewable resources need to be tapped for energy generation and poverty reduction Develop a regulatory mechanism to support development work in renewable energy sources, such as paddy-husk burning bakery ovens and brick kilns, energy efficient wood stoves and gasifiers Existing initiatives and pilots need further support; for example, via strenghtened microfinance/ microcredit initiatives Introduce the concept of endogenous development based on technologies that could be handled from within the country Meet domestic/village energy needs and livelihood activities by using dendro power or other endogenous renewable energy technologies Strenghten the provision of newer and better entrepreneurial opportunities for the poor, and make the poor partners in the process of energy supply itself With small-scale energy projects, there is ample scope for participation at the grass roots level Take up promising projects and programmes and promote them in a sustainable manner by giving them proper recognition and incentives New improved solutions must be promoted and encouraged further There are several solutions that are feasible at the village level to minimize smoke-induced health hazards, such as improved stoves, improved kitchens, etc. Wood used in a less harmful manner should be advocated instead of simply considering to replace it with LPG or electricity converted from fuels that could be used directly in thermal application at much higher efficiency Enhance partnerships with the private sector and civil society to help bridge the gaps Use Radio and ICTs to improve the delivery of and access to basic information on energy and also on services such as health and education Radio and ICTs should in particular serve as a tool for empowerment through information of women and children living in rural areas, and to increase transparency, accountability and effectiveness of governments and civil societies 35 THE CHALLENGES MEETING THE CHALLENGES Financing Concerns Many MFIs suffer from weak governance, lack of clarity in their mission, low levels of understanding of banking and finance, inappropriate accounting practices, and inadequate management information systems Lack of supportive policies and interventions as well as sound legal and regulatory frameworks for rural finance and microfinance sectors Capacity development should not be seen only in narrow project specific capacities Women are not normally involved in management, operation and decision- making relating to energy, nor in capacity development activities and technical training, even though positive examples such as introduction of biogas already exist Gender Concerns Lack of gender considerations in energy plans and programmes, and weak gender and energy related M&E Strenghten the microfinance sector to promote investment in rural areas Promote policy changes that emphasize good governance and improved operations of rural finance institutions Develop a", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "e4147e6a-21c7-4c8d-bb61-3e47ac3a2eb3": {"__data__": {"id_": "e4147e6a-21c7-4c8d-bb61-3e47ac3a2eb3", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title