l the inhabited islands by 2008; and to reduce GHG emissions through the increased use of alternative energy and renewable energy technologies (RETs) (SEP 2004). An interactive and \u25a0 Limited coordination between relevant government agencies and their energy-related interventions and limited capacities to formulate strategies that enable the provision of energy access for the poor. \u25a0 No specific capacity-building initiatives for energy service delivery institutions that focus on synergizing the energy and poverty issues. \u25a0 Lack of coordination and, more importantly, lack of cooperation and partnerships among the different actors in the provision of electrical energy (especially between STELCO and IPPs) to expand electricity access to the several inhabited islands that do not receive 24-hour electricity (NEP 2005). \u25a0 Limited influence of the local administrative bodies over energy generation and distribution at the decentralized levels. \u25a0 Lack of public-private partnerships to enhance access, efficiency and development of energy services. BOX 1: KEY CHALLENGES IN INSTITUTIONAL FRAMEWORK 8 THE CHALLENGES Energy and Poverty in the Maldives participatory process was initiated as part of the formulation process of the draft NEP between the Government, other stakeholders and relevant groups in order to incorporate views of market actors and energy consumers for addressing the complex nature of the energy sector. The NEP sets a target of 12 percent for the share of renewable energy in the energy mix to be achieved by 2015 (NEP 2005). In the Maldives, the energy tariff structure is normally determined through a process in which the local bodies recommend a price that is then approved by the regulatory body, ensuring that the price is not above a set ceiling. These are then implemented by the local bodies with minor adaptations. Electricity pricing is a little more diffused, since the IDCs determine local electricity rates. MEEW would, however, like to set a uniform price across the Maldives, but no study has been conducted so", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "b4fe3628-6c90-499d-a6a5-778c8c1e94fe": {"__data__": {"id_": "b4fe3628-6c90-499d-a6a5-778c8c1e94fe", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-maldives", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in the Maldives", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-maldives", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "440af8b47f0df7e0ce4e684ffb1647064deae87e8030d27c954997a300320770"}, "3": {"node_id": "c6adc8d0-6b7e-493e-9c23-7963d338d006", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-maldives", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "c118a79a91d9cce589cb5388987a939c47c67502b7b9950b9cca2c9b46c4e558"}}, "hash": "5f284a6036e444677559cd8d23bbbb7acc48a19b03de8d569181cfc4f444340d", "text": "far to gauge the implications of such a measure. As the IPPs are underrepresented in the energy sector, the focus of the draft NEP of June 2005 is to encourage private power producers, and it recommends tapping the inherent synergies between these producers and STELCO. Additionally, the 6th NDP (2001-2005) has woven public- private energy partnerships into its broader socio-economic vision for the country, urging the development of sustainable partnerships to enable the achievement of national development goals. The recently released 7th NDP (2005-2009) also continues to focus on public-private partnerships. The IPPs are underrepresented in the energy sector. \u25a0 The existing regulatory framework lacks uniformity at the national and local levels, and excludes the rural energy sector in general and the renewable energy sector in particular. \u25a0 Electricity tariff structure has a strong bias toward urban residents: Residents of Mal\u00e9 pay considerably less for electricity than outer island households that spend a substantial 30-40 percent of the family income on electricity. \u25a0 Public-private energy partnerships have not been as successful as hoped, perhaps due to the presence of entrenched state-owned monopolies combined with a lack of financial mechanisms and discriminatory policies on funding the private sector. \u25a0 Specific regulations on independent power generation and the pricing and use of RETs are not currently in place. \u25a0 IDCs are not backed by legal statutes, and hence are unable to provide electricity as cooperatives. BOX 2: KEY CHALLENGES FACING REGULATORY AND POLICY FRAMEWORK 9 THE CHALLENGES Energy and Poverty in the Maldives TABLE 2 MAJOR ENERGY PROGRAMMES AND THEIR LINKAGES TO POVERTY REDUCTION 1. RETDAP Strategy/Policy/ Implementing Goals Programme agency/Donors Global Environment Facility and UNDP, The Transnational Foundation, with co-funding from South Asia Regional Initiative- United States Agency for International Development (USAID), UNESCAP, the French Agency for Environment and Energy Management Seeks to have a significant impact on the socio- economic indices of the less developed outer islands, which do not receive sufficient electricity and have limited power generation capacities of their own to meet both domestic and small industry needs 2. Outer Island Electrification Project MEEW, Asian Development Bank (ADB) Improves electricity services in about 40 remote islands and enhances income generation opportunities* 3. Assessments of least-cost, sustainable energy resources \u2013 Maldives UNDP, Government of Norway Fourteen assessments have been conducted so far to address energy concerns in rural and underdeveloped islands through development of low-cost, efficient energy services Absence of poverty focus in energy programme framework The ongoing energy programmes in the Maldives have a substantial focus on electricity generation through diesel-run generators. Little attention is given to promoting renewable energy for enabling decentralized access to remote islands in order to meet energy needs. Although they incorporate reduced dependency on imported fuel by exploring sustainable energy sources in the country, most RET programmes have not advanced beyond the pilot stage. Few initiatives seek to enhance decentralized capacities for income generation and sustainable development (Table 2). RETDAP and the Atoll Development Project for Sustainable Livelihood, implemented by the Government with UNDP and other bilateral and multilateral support, are two examples where indeed this has been attempted. 10 THE CHALLENGES Energy and Poverty in the Maldives TABLE 2 MAJOR ENERGY PROGRAMMES AND THEIR LINKAGES TO POVERTY REDUCTION (CONT\u2019D) * Financed through a US$8 million ADB-supported \u2018Outer Island Electrification Project\u2019 (RETDAP 2004). Access to modern energy services Households in the Maldives rely on diesel, kerosene, LPG and biomass for their energy needs (Figure 3). Specifically, outer island households still depend on biomass, including fuelwood, for most cooking energy 4. Electricity generation programmes Strategy/Policy/ Implementing Goals Programme agency/Donors STELCO, ADCs and IDCs, with Central Government funding Provides immediate relief from incidences of poverty emerging from a sustained lack of energy use for productive purposes in outer islands 5. Power sector rehabilitation and reconstruction programmes after the tsunami ADB, USAID, Islamic Development Bank Repair and upgrade power systems affected by the tsunami \u25a0 Lack of attention to decentralized renewable energy programmes in outer islands. \u25a0 Requirement of capital-intensive physical infrastructure for renewable energy projects acts as a major barrier to investments. \u25a0 Limited support for research and development (R&D) and documentation of key pilot projects and prior experiments, particularly those with impacts on poverty reduction.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "c6adc8d0-6b7e-493e-9c23-7963d338d006": {"__data__": {"id_": "c6adc8d0-6b7e-493e-9c23-7963d338d006", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-maldives", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in the Maldives", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-maldives", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "440af8b47f0df7e0ce4e684ffb1647064deae87e8030d27c954997a300320770"}, "2": {"node_id": "b4fe3628-6c90-499d-a6a5-778c8c1e94fe", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-maldives", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "5f284a6036e444677559cd8d23bbbb7acc48a19b03de8d569181cfc4f444340d"}}, "hash": "c118a79a91d9cce589cb5388987a939c47c67502b7b9950b9cca2c9b46c4e558", "text": "\u25a0 Difficulty in inducing investments 