pment Fund (ADF) and Revolving Electricity Fund (REF) have emerged as viable alternative sources of funds to enhance rural energy entrepreneurship and access to energy services. However, effectiveness of the national-level REF has been reduced by a short repayment period and limited credit ceilings. Microfinance for renewable energy development is planned through RETDAP, although the allocated funds are not sufficient to meet the initial hardware costs of most renewable energy systems. Moreover, government sources of finance in the energy sector, such as subsidies and grants, have been slow to reach the disadvantaged groups, especially women. Credit facilities for meeting local energy needs Financial mechanism Implementing Fund details agency/agencies MAA, through ADCs and IDCs Credit provided primarily for the purchase of diesel electricity generating sets Atoll Development Fund (ADF) MAA, UNDP Credit provided for both community-based and individual income- generating activities Revolving Electricity Fund (REF) Government of the Maldives Credit provided for community initiatives to establish or upgrade electricity generation capabilities Fund for Renewable Energy System Application (FRESA) Government of the Maldives, RETDAP Funds provided for microfinance facilities, and technical assistance to promote and encourage renewable energy systems Government grants to support community initiatives MEEW Grant aid provided for community initiatives to establish or upgrade electricity generation capacities 15 THE CHALLENGES Energy and Poverty in the Maldives Gender concerns in energy issues While women in the Maldives have made good progress on many fronts, a significant proportion remains vulnerable to poverty, especially in the rural areas. Socially prescribed roles have limited women\u2019s access to economic resources such as land, capital, skills and know-how, and many challenges to improved gender equality persist. However, there is no wage discrimination between men and women in the Maldives. Even though women do take active part in most developmental projects, awareness of specific possibilities for female entrepreneurs and emphasis on encouraging women\u2019s entrepreneurship is lacking. Also special interventions for women, such as improved cook stoves, which would contribute to curbing respiratory illnesses among women, have been rare. Awareness of specific possibilities for female entrepreneurs and emphasis on encouraging women's entrepreneurship is lacking. \u25a0 Energy project loans are given only to individuals who prove their capacity to pay back the loan by putting up collateral, depriving a large segment of the rural population of the necessary finances to implement micro-energy projects for household and productive use. \u25a0 In the available credit mechanisms, the low credit limit in the REF is partly a result of shortage of available seed capital, and demand often surpasses the funds available for disbursement. \u25a0 Stringent funding conditions restrict credit for renewable energy development. \u25a0 Policies encouraging private and public investments are lacking due to the centralized nature of financing energy services.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "b8ba36ed-d375-4781-96d9-90a1aced5202": {"__data__": {"id_": "b8ba36ed-d375-4781-96d9-90a1aced5202", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-maldives", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in the Maldives", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-maldives", "Author": 